<FIRST>u i AM-RitualSlayings 1stLd-Writethru a0775 05-12 0960</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ritual Slayings, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0775,0986</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cult Priestess Says Interpol Officer Was Involved</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with one graf and SUBS grafs 5-7, `Ventura, the...causing
injuries' with 4 grafs to ADD background on Ventura and two women killed;
CORRECT that three stead five charges read in court against Aldrete. Pickup
8th pvs, `The charges...' SUBS 26th, `The attorney...' to CORRECT lawyer's
name and SUBS 29th, `Ms. Aldrete' to DELETE Aldrete and charges, which
moved up.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRIS ANGELO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman described as the high priestess of a
murderous drug cult swore Friday that a former head of Interpol in
Mexico who killed two women and himself last year belonged to the
sect. Members of the sect have been blamed for 15 ritual slayings.
   The woman, 24-year-old Sara Aldrete Villarreal, protested her
own innocence and denied she urged a gang member to kill their
leader as police closed in.
   At one point, she started to cry and said, ``I want to see my
father.''
   Ms. Aldrete, a former honor student in a Texas college,
testified at her arraignment hearing that Florentino Ventura was a
member of the sect.
   Ventura, a veteran police officer who had been the Interpol
chief in Mexico since early 1985, killed his wife and another woman
and then shot himself during an argument on Sept. 17, 1988.
   Authorities called it a case of double murder and suicide. They
said Ventura, 60, and his wife, Maria Cira Villanueva, 39, got into
an argument after dining with another couple and Ventura shot his
wife and Olga Trevino Arizmendi, 39, before killing himself. They
based their report on the testimony f Mrs. Trevino's husband, Elias
Orozco Salazar, who witnessed the killings.
   Interpol is the Paris-based international police organization
that coordinates the police activities of participating nations
against international criminals. Its full name is International
Criminal Police Organization.
   Ms. Aldrete was charged with murder, criminal association and
resisting arrest.
   The charges were filed in connection with the Saturday shootout
in Mexico City in which she and four other cult members were
arrested and the ringleader, Adolfo de Jesus Constanzo, 26, and a
companion were shot to death in a closet.
   ``I never gave orders to kill Adolfo,'' Ms. Aldrete said at her
hearing before Judge Bernardo Tirado Gutierrez of the 58th Federal
District Court.
   No charges have been filed in connection with 15 macabre
slayings on a ranch outside Matamoros, a Mexican border town near
Brownsville, Texas, or the cult's purported drug-smuggling
activities.
   Authorities say the cult believed that through human sacrifices
it could gain occult protection for its drug running. Officials
said members cut off body parts and boiled organs as part of the
rituals.
   Prosectors say Ms. Aldrete, Constanzo and three other cult
members made a pact to kill each other rather than face arrest.
When Constanzo saw police on the street below, he panicked and
demanded to be killed, they say.
   They said Ms. Aldrete encouraged fellow cultist Alvaro de Leon
Valdez to turn his machine gun on Constanzo, a Cuban-born American
from Florida, and Constanzo's right-hand man, Martin Quintana.
   The death pact and her alleged encouragement are the basis of
the murder charge.
   Ms. Aldrete denied ordering de Leon Valdez to shoot Constanzo
and Quintana.
   ``Everyone was yelling,'' she said. ``I was ... extremely
nervous. What I yelled to Alvaro de Leon was that they stop
shooting, that they (the police) were going to kill all of us.''
   Speaking from behind a barred enclosure facing the courtroom,
Ms. Aldrete repeated earlier statements to authorities that she was
not involved in the ritual slayings or the drug smuggling.
   ``The way I found out about the deaths and everything that
happened (at the ranch) was when the bodies were shown on
television,'' she said.
   But she said she suspected Constanzo was involved in drug
trafficking ``because of all the money that he carried.'
   Ms. Aldrete said she tried to escape when the group fled to
Mexico City after the 15 bodies were unearthed.
   Authorities on both sides of the border had been searching for
Constanzo, Ms. Aldrete and other cult members since the first body
was dug up on April 11.
   Most of the victims' bodies were mutilated, including that of
Mark Kilroy, a pre-med student from Santa Fe, Texas.
   Ms. Aldrete said Friday she tried to attract police attention to
the hideout of the fugitive cult members by tossing a note out the
window of the fourth-floor apartment. The note said a woman was
being held hostage in the apartment.
   After the charges and her earlier statements to authorities were
read to her, Ms. Aldrete was allowed to speak briefly with a lawyer
for the first time since her arrest.
   The attorney, Horacio Moyar Quintanilla of Monterrey, said he
was hired by Ms. Aldrete's father.
   ``Something that is not there (in my previous testimony) is that
also Florentino Ventura was a `godson' of Adolfo, according to what
Adolfo told me,'' Ms. Aldrete told the court. She did not elaborate.
   Also arraigned Friday were de Leon Valdez and Omar Francisco
Orea. The lengthy prosecution statement against them also said
Ventura had been initiated into the sect.
   Two other people, Maria del Rocio Cuevas Guerra and Dr. Maria de
Lourdes Guero were charged with covering up a crime in connection
with the killings on the Santa Elena ranch outside Matamoros. Their
case was to be transferred to a federal court.
   Francisco Orea was charged with homicide, firing a weapon at
authorities, resisting arrest, criminal association and causing
injuries. De Leon Valdez was charged with the first four crimes.
   Orea and two other men also were charged in the July 1988
killing of a transvestite. Ms. Aldrete was charged with covering up
that case.
</TEXT>
