<FIRST>u a AM-WaterlooSlayings 1stLd-Writethru a0854 05-12 0226</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Waterloo Slayings, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0854,0229</SECOND>
<HEAD>Family of Five Found Dead</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with further official comment which
reflects that officials, sted relatives became suspicious about children's
absence and found bodies; no pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WATERLOO, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A family of five was found shot to death
in their home Thursday after authorities became suspicious because
the three children had not shown up for school for several days,
police said.
   The victims were identified as David M. Fager, 34, his wife,
Roxane, 31, and their children, Bryce Allan, 16, Michael Edward,
11, and 9-year-old Melissa Lynn, said state police Cpl. Gary
Robbins at Fort Wayne.
   A large-caliber handgun found at the scene was believed to have
been used in the shootings, Robbins said.
   DeKalb County Prosecutor Monte Brown said the family members
were found in their beds about 4 p.m. and the handgun was found
near the father's body.
   The victims apparently had been dead for some time, possibly
since a week ago Wednesday, the last day the children attended
school.
   School officials alerted authorities because the children had
not been in school, Brown said.
   ``They contacted the Waterloo police, the Waterloo police
contacted us. We obtained a court order to go into the house and
that's when we discovered the bodies,'' he said.
   Waterloo is about 25 miles north of Fort Wayne.
</TEXT>
