<FIRST>u w AM-Panama-Travel     05-12 0166</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Panama-Travel,150</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Department Issues Travel Advisory for Panama</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US Panama Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department issued a travel advisory
Thursday for Panama, warning Americans that ``extremely unsettled
conditions'' mean U.S. citizens shouldn't travel in the Central
American nation.
   The advisory was issued hours after President Bush announced a
series of steps, including the dispatching of 2,000 more troops to
Panama, in reaction to that nation's nullification of presidential
elections.
   Although the U.S. ambassador to Panama was recalled by Bush, the
American embassy in Panama will remain open, the State Department
said.
   But ``the extremely unsettled conditions and the reduction of
U.S. embassy personnel in Panama complicate embassy efforts to
provide full protective and consular services to Americans,'' the
State Department said. ``U.S. citizens are advised not to travel to
Panama until further notice.''
   Despite the problems on land, the operation of the Panama Canal
``continues in a normal and efficient manner. Vessels continue to
transit the canal without problem and delay.''
</TEXT>
