<FIRST>r i PM-Israel-Jerusalem     05-12 0795</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel-Jerusalem,0826</SECOND>
<HEAD>East Jerusalem's Arabs: Sticking Point in Peace Plan</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN ALT POWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   East Jerusalem, where 140,000 Arabs live on
land annexed into Israel's capital, is emerging as a major
stumbling block to Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir's peace plan.
   Israel calls Jerusalem its ``eternal capital'' and shudders at
the hint of giving up the eastern sector captured from Jordan in
the 1967 Middle East war. It includes the Western Wall _ Judaism's
holiest shrine.
   ``Jerusalem, the city of Jerusalem, all of the city of
Jerusalem, is part of the state of Israel,'' Shamir declared on a
recent walking tour of the Jewish quarter in the walled Old City.
   But the PLO also has declared Jerusalem as the capital of its
would-be state, and many Palestinians say the Arab sector must be
part of any agreement to end the bloody uprising against Israeli
occupation of the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   ``The West Bank is the body, and Jerusalem is the soul,'' Arab
poet Fauzi Bakri said in an interview. ``One without the other is
empty, nothing.''
   The seemingly irreconcilable demands have cast a shadow over
Shamir's call for elections to choose representatives in the
occupied territories to negotiate an interim peace plan with Israel.
   Shamir and members of his right-wing Likud bloc want to exclude
the Arabs of east Jerusalem from voting.
   But the U.S. State Department and the left-leaning Labor Party,
which shares power in Shamir's coalition government, are pressing
for some arrangement to let those residents vote.
   The question is further complicated because several influential
Palestinians _ likely candidates in any election _ live in east
Jerusalem.
   More than 80 Palestinian leaders from Jerusalem and the
territories have rejected Shamir's plan, as has the PLO. They say
it does not recognize their demand for independence.
   Conflict over Jerusalem is nothing new. Canaanites, Jews,
Greeks, Romans, Christian Crusaders and Arabs have been among its
conquerors.
   Jerusalem was to have been an international city under the
never-implemented U.N. Partition plan to create Jewish and Arab
states in Palestine. The 1948 Arab-Israeli war left east Jerusalem
in Arab hands and the western sector in Israel.
   After east Jerusalem's capture in 1967, Israel sought to annex
it. It met with strikes and boycotts like those of the current
uprising, and only a few hundred Arabs accepted Israeli citizenship.
   Bakri noted that most Arabs have boycotted city elections,
believing that voting would acknowledge Israel's sovereignty.
   ``Israeli democracy for the Arabs is like plastic flowers,'' he
said. ``There is form and color but no scent.''
   Amir Cheshin, an Israeli who advises Mayor Teddy Kollek on Arab
affairs, says Israel has tried to accommodate the Arabs in the 22
years since the barricades splitting the city were torn down.
   ``There are job opportunities, travel opportunities, freedom of
the press and religion, and all the benefits of Israeli law,'' he
said.
   He noted that under Jordanian rule, Jews were not allowed to
live in the Old City and were denied access to the Western Wall,
the last remant of the ancient Jewish temple.
   ``Today, Christians, Moslems and Jews can worship freely,''
Cheshin said.
   But Israel has forced Arabs out of the Jewish quarter. Recently
it has limited access to the Al Aqsa Mosque, one of Islam's holiest
sites, because of the violence of the 17-month uprising.
   Ibrahim Dakkak, an engineer who heads an Arab development group,
charges that Israel has used the past two decades ``to try to
Judaize'' east Jerusalem.
   ``They have put rigid limits on Arab construction,'' he said.
``But they have surrounded east Jerusalem with Jewish colonies to
try to keep it forever separate from the West Bank.''
   The seven housing developments that Israel has built house about
110,000 Jews around east Jerusalem's Arab neighborhoods.
   The population of Jerusalem has grown from 267,800 in 1967 to
more than 482,000 today. Municipal statistics show that four out of
every five Arabs living in Jerusalem were born in the city, while
only two in five Jewish residents were.
   Because the city is disputed territory, most Western governments
keep their embassies in Tel Aviv. Some, like the United States,
have built two consulates in Jerusalem _ one in the east and
another in the west.
   The eastern sector remains largely Arab in character.
   Men go to cafes to drink thick Arabic coffee and linger over
water pipes. Women in ankle-length dresses and white scarves sell
vegetables at street corners, and boys push carts piled high with
Arab bread through crowded markets.
   In a paean to Jerusalem titled ``Candles on the Town Wall,''
Bakri hails the city's Arab traditionalists.
   ``You are the prophets
   Of poverty and steadfastness
   In the old town
   You are the homeland.''
</TEXT>
