<FIRST>r a PM-InsectAlibi     05-12 0282</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Insect Alibi,0290</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Charged With Killing Wife After Using Insect-swatting Alibi</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAT MILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WESTHAMPTON BEACH, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who claimed he accidentally
killed his wife while swatting away insects has confessed to
beating her for calling him lazy, authorities said.
   Kenneth Combs Jr., 46, was arraigned Thursday in Village Court
on a charge of manslaughter and ordered held on $50,000 bail, said
Suffolk County Detective Sgt. Robert Doyle.
   Combs beat his wife with a broomstick handle and his fists after
she accused him of being lazy during an argument in their backyard,
court papers showed.
   He initially told police that he and his wife, Barbara, 45, had
been potting plants when a swarm of insects attacked him, said
Doyle. Combs said that while flailing his arms at the bugs, he
accidentally struck his wife on the neck with his elbow.
   She was pronounced dead at Central Suffolk Hospital on New
York's Long Island.
   Combs changed his story after the medical examiner's report
indicated that Mrs. Combs had sustained multiple injuries by being
struck several times with an object on the back, neck, torso and
arms.
   He confessed on videotape to the killing, according to court
papers.
   He said he had an argument with his wife, a grocery clerk,
because she wanted him to make more money for their 16-year-old
son's college education. Combs told police he works six days a
week, 4 a.m. to 9 p.m., at a laundry.
   ``He apparently worked a double-shift and made only $90 a day,''
Doyle said. He was also entitled to only a one-week vacation.
   The couple were married 22 years and had five children in their
teens.
</TEXT>
