<HEAD>Snake Owner Fined $125 While Refusing To Attend Trial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The owner of a boa constrictor boycotted
his trial on a charge of ``knowingly letting a reptile run at
large'' because he claims the snake was mangled when it was
captured.
   ``They mistreated it,'' said Frankie Dodson, who was found
guilty in his absence Wednesday and fined $125 in Henrico County
General District Court.
   The 7-foot, 8-inch snake named Slick crawled under Dodson's car
in March. Neighbors who saw the snake called authorities, who spent
eight hours trying to capture the creature.
   Dodson's brother, an auto mechanic, had to disassemble part of
the car so the snake could be reached. Authorities then heated the
car frame with traffic flares and a local pet shop owner pulled the
pet off the frame.
   He said the snake suffered burns and cuts and ``looks like
somebody sat down and carved her up with a knife.''
   Dodson said he knows he was in the wrong ``but she was in my car
on my property.''
