<FIRST>u a AM-TrainDerailment     05-12 0381</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Train Derailment,0392</SECOND>
<HEAD>Precautionary Evacuation Ordered After Train Derails in Mississippi</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MERIDIAN, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A hospital and some homes were evacuated
Thursday night after three MidSouth Railroad engines and 12 cars
derailed and leaked chemicals into the Chunky River, about 10 miles
west of Meridian, officials said.
   No injuries were reported in the derailment, which occurred
about 8:30 p.m.
   ``We have directed a precautionary evacuation in a one-mile
radius around the derailment site,'' said Jim Maher, director of
the Mississippi Emergency Management Agency.
   It wasn't immediately known how many patients were being
evacuated from the private Pine Forest Hospital and Sanitarium,
said agency spokesman Sandy Megrolis.
   The patients were being taken to Matty Hersee Hospital in
Meridian, a state charity hospital which has many open beds as
state officials are preparing to close it and two other hospitals
by June 30.
   By 11:30 p.m., officials said they still didn't know how many
families lived in the evacuation area. Emergency management agency
spokesman Dusty Perkins said as few as a dozen people may live
within the evacuation area.
   ``At the point of the derailment, the railroad parallels the
Chunky River and they went off on the river side of the rail line.
They're either in the water or right on it, close to it,'' Maher
said of the cars.
   Perkins said officials' main concern was one car of caustic
soda, which had dumped almost all of its 20,000 gallons into the
river. He said caustic soda can kill fish and would burn on direct
contact with the skin.
   ``Our concern now is a pollution concern, rather than a public
safety concern. Nobody is going to breathe any toxic fumes from
this and die, but we don't know what will happen to the river,'' he
said.
   Investigators had yet to determine the cause of the derailment.
   Besides the caustic soda car, Perkins said three engines were
spilling diesel fuel into the river, and three of six derailed cars
carrying ethylene glycol alcohol had small leaks.
   He said four derailed cars carried vinyl chloride, but they
weren't leaking. He said the vinyl chloride could create toxic
fumes if it caught on fire.
   He said the remaining derailed car carried plastic beads of
styrene B, which would only be hazardous if it burned.
</TEXT>
