<DOCNO> AP890512-0019 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-12-89 0150EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Bush-Crisis     05-12 0676</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Crisis,680</SECOND>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON TODAY: the Words Were Tough, the Actions Kind and Gentle</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush won't have to worry about one
thing following his response to his first major international test
as president: few will accuse him of overreacting.
   For days, the administration had raised expectations of a tough
response to the defiant attitude of Panamanian leader Manuel
Antonio Noriega.
   ``No option is being ruled out,'' White House and State
Department spokesmen said after Noriega, according to scores of
international observers, tried to rig Sunday's national elections
and then decided to throw out the results. Some in Congress were
publicly advocating the removal of Noriega by military force.
   After Bush's brief statement Thursday listing the steps he
intended to take, a reporter asked an administration official how
such modest measures would induce Noriega to seek another line of
work.
   ``We hope he will see the error of his ways,'' the official said.
   But after carefully calculating potential costs and benefits,
Bush apparently felt that a pugnacious response to the tumult in
Panama could be counterproductive.
   Perhaps recalling John F. Kennedy's darkest hour early in his
presidency, Bush may have decided he was not about to risk a Bay of
Pigs-type disaster in Panama.
   Uprooting Noriega with military force presumably would be a
cinch for the Pentagon but the diplomatic costs for the United
States would linger for years, given the Latin American aversion to
evidence of American heavy-handedness.
   The Latin Americans would have been equally unforgiving if Bush
had decided to respond by scrapping the Panama Canal treaties.
   Imposing a trade embargo against Panama would cause even further
damage to the country's already weak economy, but the costs for the
large American business community would be high _ too high, Bush
apparently felt.
   At the start of his remarks, Bush stressed the need to send a
clear signal in support of democratic values in Latin America. But
the one significant action he took _ dispatching more than 2,000
combat troops to Panama _ had less to do with democracy than with
protecting American lives.
   That was the way Bush portrayed the troop movement, but he
wouldn't object if Noriega gave it a less benign interpretation. It
wouldn't be the first time that a strong country tried to achieve
its political goals by projecting its military power without
actually using it.
   Bush is now hoping that international public opinion will
encourage Noriega to do what the Philippines' Ferdinand Marcos did
three years ago _ surrender power to someone who supposedly has a
legitimate claim to it, namely Guillermo Endara, the opposition
candidate last Sunday.
   Some European countries have already weighed in against Noriega
but the Latin Americans thus far have been disappointingly slow to
respond, according to State Department officials.
   At an Organization of American States meeting Wednesday, only
Venezuela, Peru and El Salvador joined the United States in
denouncing Noriega. Delegates from 27 other countries remained
silent.
   Mexico's view is that elections are an internal matter and
should not be on the OAS agenda. But OAS foreign ministers
nonetheless are expected to convene here next Tuesday at
Venezuela's request to discuss the Panama question.
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III has spoken often of the
need for the United States to act in concert with Latin American
countries on issues of common interest. That policy will be put to
its first significant test at the OAS meeting.
   In his first brush with a crisis situation, Bush clearly showed
he is no bomb thrower. Rhetorically, the administration could not
have been tougher on Noriega during the week preceding the election
and in the immediate aftermath.
   All of Noriega's perceived efforts to impose his will on the
Panamanian people were trumpeted from government podiums around
Washington. Noriega was portrayed as Willie Horton in khaki. In the
end, though, Noriega was treated kinder and gentler than Michael
Dukakis _ well, almost.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>_____</NOTE>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   George Gedda has covered foreign affairs for the
Associated Press since 1968.
</TEXT>
