<FIRST>r w PM-Congress-Panama     05-12 0610</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Congress-Panama,610</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Receives Bipartisan Support For Handling of Noriega</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-US Panama Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX9</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush is winning broad support from
Congress for placing ``a much tighter noose'' around the neck of
Panama's Manuel Antonio Noriega without an excessive show of
military force.
   But many lawmakers say Bush will encounter intense pressure for
direct military action to topple Noriega from power and return
Panama to democracy if the situation there worsens, if U.S.
civilians are attacked or if the security of the Panama Canal is
threatened.
   Democratic leaders of the Senate and House joined their
Republican counterparts in endorsing as ``measured,'' ``reasoned,''
``careful'' and ``deliberate'' the Bush plan to protect the 50,000
American civilians in Panama and to send an additional 2,000 combat
troops there.
   They also endorsed his decisions to open a diplomatic offensive
in Latin America and elsewhere to repudiate Noriega's efforts to
undermine last Sunday's presidential election and to condemn the
subsequent violent attack on Panamanian opposition leaders.
   But several lawmakers questioned whether Bush has carefully
considered how the United States will respond if international and
domestic pressure fails to achieve Noriega's downfall.
   Sen. Alan Cranston, D-Calif., the Senate's deputy Democratic
leader, said Bush has so far rejected pressure to either invade
Panama or scrap the treaties that commit the United States to turn
over control of the Panama Canal at the end of the century.
   Senate Republican Leader Bob Dole of Kansas and other key
lawmakers acknowledged that many members of Congress believe the
president did not go far enough and should take tougher action to
drive Noriega from power.
   Sen. Richard Lugar, R-Ind., said the people of Panama, who by
most accounts defeated Noriega's handpicked presidential candidate
by a 3-to-1 margin, may be able to settle matters on their own.
   But Lugar also declared that the United States has the right to
``to keep all further military options open for response to
potential crises.''
   ``We're drawing a much tighter noose around Noriega's neck with
every one of these unified actions,'' Lugar said.
   The bipartisan leadership of Congress issued a joint statement
expressing support for the Republican president, a step that was
unheard of in the rancorous and bitter partisan debates that marked
major foreign policy actions in the Reagan administration.
   The statement was signed by House Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas;
Senate Majority leader George Mitchell, D-Maine; House Majority
Leader Tom Foley, D-Wash.; House Minority Leader Robert H. Michel,
R-Ill.; and Dole.
   At a news conference, Mitchell said he had told the president
there will be those ``who think this does not go far enough.''
   Sen. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn., chairman of the Senate Foreign
Relations subcommittee on Latin America, said he commended Bush for
his restrained action despite a probable ``tremendous degree of
pressure on the president to take actions that were more strident.''
   Defense Secretary Dick Cheney, emerging Thursday afternoon from
a briefing for House and Senate members, said he found wide support
for the president's ``very careful, very measured response.''
   Many members of Congress said they agreed with that.
   But Sen. Brock Adams, D-Wash., sounding a cautionary note,
voiced the hope the president would consult with Congress under the
terms of the War Powers Act if there were any chance that U.S.
troops might be involved in combat in Panama.
   ``I want to be certain that we act all together so we don't have
a split between members of Congress and the administration as we
take action,'' Adams said. ``The situation is fraught with peril
and we want to have more than just briefings, we want them to use
the law.''
</TEXT>
