<FILEID>AP-NR-05-12-89 0209EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-CleanAir     05-12 0351</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Clean Air,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Bill Would Extend Air Pollution Deadlines But Toughen Controls</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new anti-pollution bill would extend
already-expired deadlines for cities to meet clean air requirements
but force many areas to install tougher pollution controls.
   Hearings on the bill were quickly scheduled for May 23-24 by
chief sponsor Rep. Henry Waxman, D-Calif., chairman of the House
Energy and Environment health subcommittee _ the panel with initial
jurisdiction over clean air legislation.
   The legislation is certain to be controversial, because it would
require tough new controls on auto emissions. The powerful chairman
of the House Energy and Commerce Committee, Rep. John D. Dingell,
D-Mich., has opposed such controls in the past.
   Almost every U.S. city is in violation of the current Clean Air
Act's Dec. 31, 1988, deadline for meeting air pollution standards.
The non-compliance could bring those areas economic penalties such
as moratoriums on new industrial facilities or a cutoff of federal
highway money.
   The new measure, sponsored by more than 100 lawmakers, would end
the economic threat, except for areas that act in bad faith in
combatting air pollution.
   Instead, the legislation would extend the deadlines but require
the most severely polluted localities to install tougher pollution
controls.
   Local areas would be classified as having either moderate,
serious, severe or extreme air pollution. Moderate areas would
receive four years to attain federal standards, serious areas would
get eight years, severe areas 12 years and extreme areas 16 years.
   Each area would have to install special measures based on the
category _ the higher the category, the more measures to be
required. Controls would range from tighter control of new
pollution sources to requirements for greater use of alternative
fuels.
   The legislation would require stricter standards for tailpipe
emissions of hydrocarbons and nitrogen oxides, the two key
components of ozone pollution. Controls also would be tightened for
carbon monoxide, including a special standard for cold-weather
conditions.
   New requirements also would be installed for reduction of
hydrocarbon pollution from the evaporation of gasoline while cars
are running, parked or refueling.
</TEXT>
