<FILEID>AP-NR-05-12-89 0219EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-InternationalPanic     05-12 0533</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-International Panic,0548</SECOND>
<BYLINE>Panic Attacks Vary In Different Cultures, Study Suggests ^Eds:
`Michaela' in 5th graf is cq ^By MALCOLM RITTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   North Americans are less likely than
Europeans to fear dying when a panic attack strikes but more likely
to think they may be going crazy, a new study suggests.
   North Americans also appear more likely to avoid situations in
which previous attacks occurred, a condition that can make a person
housebound, said researcher Heinz Katschnig of the University of
Vienna in Austria.
   The differences may reflect cultural influences on how people
perceive symptoms, or different kinds of panic disorder, Katschnig
said.
   Panic attacks afflict some 1.2 million Americans, who suddenly
suffer overwhelming terror for no apparent reason.
   Katschnig and colleague Michaela Amering studied 1,168 panic
attack patients from 14 countries. They presented the work Thursday
at the annual meeting of the American Psychiatric Association.
   The different responses also may result from cultural
differences in how people describe panic attacks, Katschnig said,
or they may reflect differences in how patients in the study were
signed up in different countries. The patients had been recruited
for a drug trial.
   The study included 220 panic attack sufferers in the United
States and Canada; 367 in southern Europe (Belgium, France, Italy
and Spain); 324 in northern Europe (Austria, Denmark, West Germany,
Sweden and the United Kingdom); and 257 in Latin American (Brazil,
Colombia and Mexico).
   Dizziness, feeling faint and palpitations were the most common
symptoms reported by about 90 percent of patients in each of the
four geographic areas.
   Choking or smothering was reported most often in the Latin
American group, followed by southern Europe, northern Europe and
North America.
   Fear of dying followed the same ranking, suggesting it is a
reaction to the sense of choking or smothering, Katschnig said.
   Forty-four percent of North American patients said they feared
death during the attacks, compared to 57 percent of patients from
northern Europe, 70 percent from southern Europe and 72 percent
from Latin America.
   Fear of ``going crazy'' and a sense of unreality were each more
common in the Americas than in Europe, suggesting the fear was a
reaction to the feeling of unreality, Katschnig said.
   Seventy-three percent of North American patients and 64 percent
of Latin American patients reported fear of ``going crazy'' during
an attack. Just under half of the two European groups reported it.
   While 91 percent of the North American patients reported
avoiding situations they associated with previous attacks, only 65
percent of South American patients did. Seventy-nine percent of
northern Europeans reported avoiding such situations and 72 percent
of southern Europeans did.
   Staying home to avoid those situations may be more common in
cultures where most of one's needs can be met at home, through such
means as ordering out for meals, Katschig said.
   The Austrian researchers collaborated with German and American
scientists on the study.
   Armand Loranger, a psychologist at Cornell University Medical
College, cautioned that studies comparing countries must rule out
non-cultural explanations before ascribing differences to culture.
   For example, he said the study sample may be skewed by
differences in how often panic attack victims end up at psychiatric
facilities.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890512-0024 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-12-89 0226EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-US-Nicaragua     05-12 0370</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Nicaragua,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sandinistas ``Smarter Than Noriega'' About Elections, Panelist Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials of the Bush and Carter
administration say the furor over last weekend's elections in
Panama may bode well for prospects that Nicaragua's Sandinista
government will conduct fair balloting next year.
   ``I am prepared to accept the Nicaraguan government's intention
today to carry out an honestly counted election,'' Francis MacNeil,
who was President Carter's ambassador to Costa Rica, told the
Commission on Free and Fair Elections in Nicaragua.
   ``Certainly they have before them the example of Gen. Noriega,
who has demonstrated how not to steal elections,'' MacNeil said
Thursday in the final round of three days of hearings by the
privately financed, conservative-backed bipartisan commission.
   His testimony came as President Bush urged allied nations to
join in condemning Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega, Panama's military
leader, for election fraud in Sunday's balloting, in which Noriega
has claimed victory.
   On Wednesday, Peter Rodman, special assistant to the president
for national security affairs, told the commission, ``I think the
Sandinistas may well have been watching what happened in Panama.''
He added, ``the Sandinistas are smarter than Noriega.''
   But Keith E. Schuette, president of the National Republican
Institute for International Affairs, said his group found
``disturbing parallels, too frequent to be considered accidental,''
in the election laws, government organization and opposition in
Nicaragua and Panama.
   ``Sufficient freedom of organization, expression and activity
does not currently exist to ensure a free and fair election'' in
Nicaragua, Schuette said Thursday.
   Luigi Einaudi, director of policy planning for the State
Department's Bureau of Inter-American affairs and
ambassador-designate to the Organization of American States, agreed
the nature of the Nicaraguan government ``raises major questions
about the ability to in fact carry out a free and impartial
election.''
   However, Einaudi said, ``These need not be insurmountable
obstacles.'' He expressed ``cautious optimism that the game is not
automatically over and that it may in fact be possible to move the
political conflict in Nicaragua to the political ground and away
from the military.''
   The Nicaraguan elections are to be held in February 1990 under
an agreement Managua made with the governments of Costa Rica, El
Salvador, Guatemala and Honduras.
</TEXT>
