<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     05-12 0306</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0315</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Hits Eight-Month High Against Yen, Stocks Off</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar today hit an eight-month high
against the Japanese yen, while the key index on the Tokyo Stock
Exchange fell.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, an 89.14-point
gainer Thursday, shed 215.16 points, or 0.63 percent, to finish at
33,866.33 points.
   The dollar ended trading at 135.80 yen, up 1.25 yen from
Thursday's close of 134.55 yen. Opening higher at 135.40 yen, the
currency remained above that level throughout the day's trading and
at one point hit 135.83 yen.
   It was the dollar's highest closing rate against the yen since
the currency closed at 135.60 yen on Sept. 6.
   Traders said the dollar's surge followed overnight gains against
most major currencies, including the Japanese yen, on overseas
markets.
   The dollar's rise was triggered by a decision Thursday by
President Bush to send U.S. troops to Panama to help protect
Americans in that country, said a trader at the Bank of Tokyo.
There are 10,000 troops already based at U.S. installations in
Panama.
   The U.S. currency is regarded as a safe haven in times of
international tension.
   In a news confernce this morning, Finance Minister Tatsuo
Maruyama said he was not alarmed by the dollar's surge. ``The
dollar was bought due partly to its (potential) strength at the
time of an emergency such as confusion'' over the Panamanian
situation, Maruyama said.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, share prices declined on a broad
front due to concerns over the yen's fall and the possibility of a
discount rate hike.
   Some Japanese economists have said the nation's monetary
authorities are waiting to assess price data due later this month
before deciding on the timing for cutting the discount rate, which
now stands at a post-World War II low of 2.5 percent.
</TEXT>
