<FIRST>r w PM-NuclearPlants     05-12 0473</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nuclear Plants,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Industry Leader Says Rule Changes Won't Revive Nuclear Power</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal rule changes aimed at speeding up
licensing of nuclear power plants are inadequate and won't revive
the stagnant industry, an official of a leading nuclear utility
told Congress.
   Richard B. Priory, a senior vice president of Duke Power Co.,
said his company's analysis of the rule change _ which takes effect
next Thursday _ does not alter its view that ``nuclear power is not
now a viable option in this country.''
   Priory told a House Energy and Commerce subcommittee Thursday
that while the rule change adopted by the Nuclear Regulatory
Commission was a step in the right direction, it did not go far
enough in freeing utilities from legal entanglements.
   ``The rule ... does not provide the necessary assurances that a
utility, having invested more than a billion dollars in a nuclear
power plant, will be able to operate that plant in a timely manner,
or indeed, to operate it at all,'' he said.
   Priory's main objection was that the NRC rule did not eliminate
the possibility of someone raising a legal challenge to a completed
nuclear plant after it had received its operating license but
before it could begin running.
   He said Congress should amend the 1954 Atomic Energy Act to
limit the possibility of such 11th-hour challenges, which in recent
years have stopped plants from opening.
   Duke Power, which provides power in North and South Carolina and
relies on nuclear plants for two-thirds of its electricity, is
widely considered one of the most successful nuclear utilities.
   The main aim of the NRC's rule change was to ensure that
questions about the suitability of a nuclear reactor design, as
well as the plant's location, are answered before construction
begins.
   Lando W. Zech Jr., the NRC chairman, told the subcommittee the
new rule was ``a huge positive step'' toward reviving the nuclear
industry. He said the NRC had received no orders for new plants
since 1978, but that many new generating plants would be needed to
meet energy demands in the 1990s.
   ``The commission is confident that the final rule as presently
structured provides a sound basis for the efficient construction
and licensing of new, safe nuclear power plants,'' Zech said.
   Dean R. Tousley, speaking for the Union of Concerned Scientists,
told the panel that while his group favored speeding up the
licensing process, the NRC revisions go too far by limiting the
kinds of issues that can be raised after a plant is completed. He
said the rule meant only design and site issues could be raised.
   ``Where the commission runs adrift is in thinking that it can
resolve all construction-related issues prior to construction, and
deny a hearing on those issues at the end of construction,''
Tousley said.
</TEXT>
