<FIRST>r w PM-F-14     05-12 0297</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-F-14,290</SECOND>
<HEAD>Study Predicts 21 Percent F-14 Shortfall by End of '96</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The defense budget submitted to Congress last
month will leave the Navy short of F-14 jetfighters, according to a
congressman from the state where the aircraft are made.
   The Navy will have 110 fewer F-14 fighter planes than it needs
by 1996, Rep. George Hochbrueckner, D-N.Y., said Thursday in
releasing an analysis prepared for him by the Congressional
Research Service of the Library of Congress.
   ``No matter how you slice the Bush-Cheney budget, it comes up
dangerously short in Navy aircraft, the conventional weapons
America needs and uses in real life,'' Hochbrueckner said.
   The five-page report, described in its introduction as ``a
quick, rough analysis,'' concludes that the Navy will have 417 F-14
Tomcats at the end of fiscal 1996, 110 fewer than it has said it
will need. That equates to a 20.9 percent shortfall.
   The study assumes that there will be an increased demand for
F-14s as two aircraft carriers are converted from Midway airwings,
which carry no F-14s, to Roosevelt airwings, which carry 20 each.
The analysis also projects a loss of 70 F-14s during the period due
to peacetime accidents.
   The report is the latest weapon in a battle being waged by Long
Island's five congressmen to save the plane, manufactured by the
Grumman Corp. of Bethpage, N.Y.
   The F-14 was a casualty of the pared-down budget submitted last
month by Defense Secretary Dick Cheney. Cheney saved $360 million
in fiscal 1990 by canceling orders for 12 new F-14s.
   Cheney said the F14s are too expensive at a time when the
Pentagon has been ordered to cut $10 billion from its 1990 budget.
According to published reports and Navy calculations, the new
planes cost $75 million each.
</TEXT>
