<DOCNO> AP890512-0035 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-12-89 0408EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Budget     05-12 0620</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Budget,610</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congress Gets $1.17 Trillion Federal Budget Next Week</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congressional budget writers say they expect
the House and Senate to give final approval next week to a $1.17
trillion spending plan for 1990 that claims a big deficit bite but
leaves most federal priorities unmolested.
   House-Senate negotiators agreed to the plan _ which claims a
$99.7 billion deficit reduction _ by a unanimous voice vote
Thursday after only two short days of public meetings. The few
disagreements the two chambers had were worked out behind closed
doors.
   ``I don't expect any problems,'' Senate Budget Committee
Chairman Jim Sasser, D-Tenn., said when asked about the prospects
for approval on the floor of Congress.
   Democratic and Republican leaders have been working together
since the Bush administration and congressional leaders forged a
deal last month that settled most questions about spending levels
and how to achieve savings. On May 4, bipartisan majorities in the
House and Senate approved their own spending plans, which differed
little from each other.
   In reaching their compromise, the House agreed to the Senate's
higher spending totals for energy and commerce programs, while the
two chambers compromised on education, health, law enforcement, and
community development initiatives.
   One of the last disputes was resolved when the Senate agreed to
drop a provision that would have guaranteed $1.1 billion for public
housing subsidies. The decision will instead be left to Congress'
appropriations committees, which normally make most spending
choices.
   Middle ground was also found in the $28 billion the package
claims in deficit reduction for next year. The Senate agreed to
reduce the $2.7 billion in savings it sought from the Medicare
program to $2.3 billion, an amount expected to come from lowered
payments to doctors and hospitals.
   The makeup of $5.3 billion in additional tax receipts still must
be determined, a choice that is expected to be difficult. President
Bush says $4.8 billion of it can come from cutting the capital
gains tax, but Democrats say the plan is a handout to the wealthy
and a money-loser.
   Other fights are expected to be waged over a controversial
proposal to raise $250 million by having the government sell
broadcast rights and $400 million by licensing the production of
chloroflourocarbons, the chemicals blamed for depleting the Earth's
ozone layer.
   Battles will also be raised over about $3.5 billion worth of
undetermined savings expected to come from agriculture,
transportation, community development, health and other programs.
   In addition, out of $16.3 billion worth of savings that will
require changes in the law, the budget assigns only about half to
specified congressional committees for action. The budget simply
assumes that the rest of the savings will occur, an assumption that
Sen. Pete Domenici of New Mexico, ranking Republican on the Senate
Budget Committee, said causes ``a very serious credibility
problem.''
   The spending plan allows $299.2 billion in defense spending,
$4.2 billion less than the amount needed to keep up with inflation.
Another $17 billion would be spent on foreign aid. Both totals were
set in last month's budget pact between Bush and Congress.
   The budget has been savaged by critics who say it relies too
heavily on unrealistic economic assumptions that make the deficit
seem smaller and accounting gimmicks that create little real saving.
   The lawmakers claim $850 million in savings by moving some
payments for farmers from 1990 to this year, and $200 million in
savings because of the ``off-budget'' plan the Bush administration
prefers for rescuing the nation's ailing savings and loan
institutions.
   The claimed $99.7 billion shortfall allows Congress to claim to
have met the $100 billion deficit target set by the Gramm-Rudman
law for the fiscal year beginning Oct. 1.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890512-0036 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-12-89 0441EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Bush-PanamaText 3Takes   05-12 0451</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Panama Text, 3 Takes,0474</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a transcript of President Bush's
announcement on Panama and his news conference Thursday.
   The people of Latin America and the Caribbean have sacrificed,
fought and died to establish democracy.
   Today, elected constitional government is the clear choice of
the vast majority of the people of the Americas and the days of the
dictator are over.
   Still, in many parts of our hemisphere, the enemies of democracy
lie in wait to overturn elected governments through force or to
steal elections through fraud.
   All nations in the democratic community have a responsibility to
make it clear, through our actions and our words, that efforts to
overturn constitutional regimes or steal elections are unacceptable.
   If we fail to send a clear signal when democracy is imperiled,
the enemies of constitutional government will become more dangerous.
   And that's why events in Panama place an enormous responsibility
on all nations in the democratic community.
   This past week the people of Panama, in record numbers, voted to
elect a new democratic leadership of their country.
   And they voted to replace the dictatorship of Gen. Manuel
Noriega.
   The whole world was watching.
   Every credible observer, the Catholic church, Latin and European
observers, leaders of our Congress and two former presidents of the
United States tell the same story: the opposition won.
   It was not even a close election.
   The opposition won by a margin of nearly three to one.
   The Noriega regime first tried to steal this election through
massive fraud and intimidation, and now has nullified the election
and resorted to violence and bloodshed.
   In recenty days, a host of Latin American leaders have condemned
this election fraud.
   They've called on General Noriega to heed the will of the people
of Panama.
   We support and second those demands.
   The United States will not recognize nor accommodate with a
regime that holds power through force and violence at the expense
of the Panamanian people's right to be free.
   I've exchanged these views over the last several days with
democratic leaders in Latin America and in Europe.
   These consultations will continue.
   The crisis in Panama is a conflict between Noriega and the
people of Panama.
   The United States stands with the Panamanian people.
   We share their hope that the Panamanian defense forces will
stand with them and fulfill their constitutional obligation to
defend democracy.
   A professional Panamanian defense force can have an important
role to play in Panama's democratic future.
   The United States is committed to democracy in Panama.
   We respect the sovereignty of Panama and, of course, we have
great affection for the Panamanian people.
   We are also committed to protect the lives of our citizens.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>MORE</HEAD>
</DOC>
