   Q. Mr. President, sir, how many troops will that be? And will
they be quartered in the military compounds? Will they stay there
quietly and just be there, or will they be out on the streets
patroling?
   A. We will assert our treaty rights, enforce our treaty rights.
   And I will refer _ I will let General Scowcroft answer the
question.
   But my estimate of the troops would be about 2,000.
   Yes?
   Q. Mr. President, why _ what is your justification for sending
the brigade of troops? What are you worried about?
   A. I'm worried about the lives of American citizens, and I will
do what is necessary to protect the lives of American citizens.
   And we will not be intimidated by the bullying tactics, brutal
though they may be, of the dictator Noriega.
   Q. Mr. President, your statement just now about defense forces,
would that be a signal that the United States would look favorably
on a coup attempt?
   A. I've asserted what my interest is at this point _ it is
democracy in Panama, it is protection of the life of Americans in
Panama.
   I'm going to take two more and then I'm going to go.
   Right here, and here on the aisle.
   Q. Sir, we've been calling around these Latin American
embassies. We find no enthusiasm for the dispatch of American
troops there. And the Mexican Embassy even said that they warned
against intervention. Are you disappointed with the reaction you're
getting from the Latin Americans?
   A. We've had good reactions from the Latin Americans.
   I haven't talked to them on that particular point but we have
had very good reactions from them.
   And I've been impressed with what the role of several of the
Latin American leaders _ I think, for the first time, there is a
total understanding on their part of the threat to democracy from
the stealing of this election or the threat to democracy in the
hemisphere from totalitarianism.
   And it's brought home by this theft of the election.
   So, they don't _ and I might add, on the troops _ I have a
profound obligation and that is _ as commander in chief of the
armed forces and as president, and that is to protect American life.
   And I'm going to do what is prudent and necessary to do this.
   And so we have a different obligation.
   We also have certain treaty rights and obligations.
   I'm prepared to fulfill our treaty obligations and I am prepared
to see that our treaty rights are exercised.
   And _ I'd leave it right there in terms of the troop deployments.
   Last one.
   Q. Mr. President, in the Reagan administration there was a very
formal negotiating process with General Noriega over terms under
which he might leave. Is there any possibility that that might
repeat itself now _ that there might be some sort of formal
discussions between yourselves and the Panamanian government and
General Noriega about conditions under which he might leave?
   A. Oh, he knows my position on the fact that, if he does leave,
we would have the instant restoration of normal relations with
Panama _ that has been conveyed to him very, very recently.
   But look, I will be open-minded about seeing what it might take
to see him leave.
   I'm not going to go back and do what Helen asked about in
dropping these indictments.
   I'm not going to do that.
   It has _ that has profound implications for our fight against
narcotics, which is _ has got to be worldwide.
   But if there's something short of that, the door's open to
understand what it is that would be required.
   But I don't think he's _ the Panamanian people should be asked
to compromise in terms of their election, which was won
three-to-one by those opposed to Noriega.
   So there'd be certain things, other non-negotiable things, but I
don't think that _ that's between Noriega and the Panamanian people.
   Thank you all very much, and Brent will take your remaining
questions.
   Q. How is Endara? Is he in the hospital?
   Bush: He was out and then I think he's back in.
   But now I don't know whether he's gotten out later on or not.
   Q. Is Noriega capable taking hostages, sir?
   Q. What about Ford?
   Q. Have you made contact with him?
   Q. Are you concerned about him taking hostages?
   Bush: I'm concerned about protecting the lives of Americans and
that's exactly why I've taken the actions that I have here today.
</TEXT>
