<FIRST>u i PM-Venezuela Bjt   05-12 0478</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Venezuela, Bjt,0491</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Completes First 100 Days Despite Deaths, Looming Strike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HAROLD OLMOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Carlos Andres Perez marked
his first 100 days in office today on an ominous note _ unions set
a strike date to protest austerity measures ordered by the
International Monetary Fund. Similar protests last winter sparked
clashes that left nearly 300 Venezuelans dead.
   If the first nationwide strike in 31 years of democratic rule
goes off as scheduled next Thursday, it would underscore the social
democratic leader's difficulties in convincing Venezuelans that his
program will lift this oil-producing nation out of its economic
doldrums.
   Leaders of the powerful Venezuelan Workers Confederation have
vowed to bring the country to a standstill with the strike, saying
a massive work stoppage would force Perez ``to twist and rectify''
his controversial plan.
   The elimination overnight of a number of subsidies that for
years kept prices down triggered a wave of violence in Caracas and
the deaths of at least 276 people in late February and early March.
The elimination of subsidies on basic commodities had been
advocated by the IMF.
   While the violence caused no reshufflings of the Perez
administration, it did expose the radical changes that have
occurred in Venezuela _ a model of stability in Latin America _
since he was first president from 1973-78, when the country was
rich with petrodollars.
   The bonanza of those years helped Perez easily win a second term
in December elections and he begin his new government with a
festive ceremony that featured 20 presidents, heads of state and a
special U.S. delegation presided over by Vice-President Quayle.
   But the enthusiasm soon faded, overwhelmed by crushing economic
realities.
   Inflation during the first four months of the year was 39
percent, and about 15 percent of the labor force of 5.8 millions is
jobless _ almost double that of last year.
   The government too is still far from an agreement with foreign
banks on measures to help alleviate its foreign debt.
   Perez meanwhile has launched a campaign to gain funds from
private institutions and, if successful, news reports say he would
increase his nation's debt from an already high $33 billion to $50
billion by 1994, when his term ends.
   Banks, however, have been reluctant to grant fresh money to
Venezuela.
   ``It is hard to come to terms easily with somebody who is asking
a debt reduction with one hand and with the other asking for more
loans,'' said one foreign banker.
   The debt is among the strike's targets, but it is not clear yet
if the unions will ask the government to declare a unilateral
moratorium, which Perez has consistently rejected, or reiterate
demands for better terms of repayment.
   Private business leaders have condemned the strike, saying it
will cause $300 million in production losses, something the country
can ill-afford.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
