<FIRST>r i PM-Panama-Treaties     05-12 0545</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Panama-Treaties,0564</SECOND>
<HEAD>An End To Panama Canal Treaties Would End A Special Relationship</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Panama, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dispute over the Panama Canal
treaties threatens the special relationship that Panama and the
United States have enjoyed since the Central American nation's
birth.
   This week's annullment of Panama's presidential elections have
focused new attention on the treaties that allow the U.S.
government to operate the canal and nearby military bases, but say
it must turn relinquish control of the canal and pull out its
troops by the end of the century.
   Cancellation of those treaties was one measure U.S. legislators
suggested Thursday after President Bush announced he would send
nearly 1,900 troops to augment the 10,000 servicemen already
stationed in Panama.
   The troops are part of an effort to force out Gen. Manuel
Antonio Noriega, who the U.S. government says rigged the elections
and was behind attacks by his supporters on the opposition
presidential and vice presidential candidates.
   Noreiga, the country's de facto ruler since 1983, has said the
U.S. government plans to renege on the treaties.
   Panama's relationship with the United States dates to 1903, the
year it seceded from neighboring Colombia with President Theodore
Roosevelt's help.
   That same year, the two countries signed a treaty to construct a
50-mile canal across the narrow isthmus connecting the Pacific and
Atlantic oceans.
   The canal, designed to save ships the long voyage around the
southern tip of South America, was inaugurated in 1914.
   In subsequent years, the United States built numerous military
installations along the canal and constructed a huge communications
network.
   That early treaty formed a U.S.-administered Canal Zone. While
Panama retained sovereignity in the area, the United States had
unilateral control over canal operations.
   The arrangement continued with minor modifications until 1977,
when President Jimmy Carter and dictator Gen. Omar Torrijos signed
a new set of treaties that said:
   _ The United States would relinquish canal administration to
Panama and pull out all its military installations in a gradual
process ending on Dec. 31, 1999.
   _ The United States would retain control of and have primary
responsibility for protecting and defending the canal until then.
   The treaties went into effect in 1979, when the United States
relinquished a bit of Americana known as the Canal Zone, along with
several military installations.
   Still, the Carter-Torrijos treaties included a clause allowing
the United States to station, train and transport military forces
in Panama.
   Many Panamanians worry that that clause could allow the United
States to pack the area with soldiers if it believes its control of
the canal is at stake.
   The Carter-Torrijos treaties said ``after the termination of the
Canal Treaty only Panama will administer the Canal and maintain
military forces, defense sites and military installations within
its national territory.''
   But the U.S. Congress approved the treaties, with an amendment
giving its government ``the right to act against any aggression or
threat aimed at the Canal or against the peaceful movement of
ships.''
   That amendment also said the two countries could make future
arrangements to allow a U.S. military presence in Panama by mutual
agreement.
   Noriega says the opposition, which claims victory in Sunday's
aborted elections, planned to give the United States that option.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
