<FIRST>r a PM-Exxon-Stock     05-12 0496</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Exxon-Stock,0511</SECOND>
<HEAD>Exxon Supports Suggestions From Pension Group</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Exxon Corp. has recommended naming an
environmentalist to its board, but one of the nation's top wildlife
advocates emerged from a meeting with the company's chairman saying
Exxon was shirking its duties.
   ``They simply are looking at a short-term fix,'' National
Wildlife Federation President Jay D. Hair told reporters Thursday
after meeting with Exxon Chairman Lawrence G. Rawl and other
company officials.
   The oil company, bowing to pressure from pension funds holding
about $1 billion in the company's stock, announced earlier it would
establish a special committee on environmental matters that would
review corporate policies and programs related to worker safety and
the environment.
   In addition, Exxon said it would consider spending more money on
environmental research and pollution prevention. About $5.5 billion
has been spent on that from 1970 to 1988, the company said.
   The announcement comes about a week after a meeting between
Exxon management and representatives of New York City's pension
fund, a large shareholder.
   New York City Comptroller Harrison J. Goldin, who recommended
the changes Exxon plans to adopt, said he was pleased by Exxon's
announcement.
   ``It's a rather extraordinary development for a large American
company,'' he said in a telephone interview. ``We're pleased that
they have accepted our proposals, and it's clear that these ...
could go far in helping prevent a repeat of the Alaska disaster.''
   But Ed Rothschild, a spokesman for the Washington-based consumer
group Citizen Action, called the announcement nothing more than ``a
public relations window dressing'' that will do nothing concrete to
improve the environment.
   New York officials had said three city pension funds owning 6
million shares of Exxon stock would vote against company management
at the May 18 annual shareholders meeting if the company failed to
act on their recommendations.
   California's state employee pension fund, the nation's biggest,
had indicated that it might back the New York group.
   About 35 percent of Exxon's shares are owned by institutional
investors. The company has some 713,000 shareholders.
   Hair said Exxon's efforts to clean up the spill resulting from
the March 24 wreck of the tanker Exxon Valdez were ineffective and
the company had no long-term plans for restoring the delicate
balance of life in Prince William Sound.
   Hair said Rawl rejected several proposals designed to ``ensure
that Exxon is going to be there as long as it takes, no matter how
much it costs.''
   Among the federation's proposals was a plan for Exxon to
contribute $1 billion annually to an independent trust fund ``until
the total extent of the long-term economic and environmental
impacts to the Prince William Sound region have been objectively
determined.''
   Sarah Johnson, an Exxon spokeswoman, said the company believed
that such a trust fund ``would not be in the best interest of its
shareholders.''
   Fears that Exxon would abandon the region once the visible
effects of the spill are gone were unwarranted, she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
