<FILEID>AP-NR-05-12-89 0456EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-HUDProbe     05-12 0656</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-HUD Probe,660</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Panel Blasts HUD Attorney General for Investigation Methods</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENISE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House panel weighing a report on alleged
mismanagement and contract abuse in a federal low-income housing
renovation program denounced aspects of the Housing Department's
probe.
   Members of the Banking and Finance subcommittee on housing and
community development on Thursday called Department of Housing and
Urban Development Inspector General Paul A. Adams to task for his
investigative methods, which turned up no evidence of criminal
wrongdoing.
   Democrats criticized Adams for waiting until a day before former
HUD Secretary Samuel Pierce was to leave the department to question
him.
   ``Why would you have waited ... until Jan. 19 of this year to
interview the HUD Secretary Samuel Pierce, who was going out of
office the next day?'' asked Rep. Henry Gonzalez, D-Texas, the
subcommittee's chairman. He noted the inspector general's probe had
begun almost a year earlier.
   ``This seems to be quite planned,'' charged Gonzalez, calling
Adams ``derelict'' in waiting so long.
   Adams said the delay in interviewing Pierce ``was just a matter
of scheduling.''
   The subcommittee also criticized Adams for singling out for
culpability Thomas T. Demery, the former assistant secretary for
housing who was responsible for administration of the controversial
renovation program.
   Current Housing Secretary Jack Kemp two weeks ago suspended more
than $100 million in fiscal 1989 funding for low-income renovation
projects, saying Adams' investigation had uncovered a system that
``was undocumented, ignored existing standards and regulations, and
was based on the perception and reality of favoritism and abuse of
non-public information.''
   The inspector general reported that former housing appointees
and other government officials _ including former HUD
Undersecretary Philip Abrams, former Assistant Secretary for
Housing Philip Winn and former Sen. Edward Brooke, R-Mass. _ used
the system to win lucrative consultant contracts with public
housing authorities and developers.
   But the report found no evidence of criminal wrongdoing in the
investigation, which covered activities in the HUD Section 8
Moderate Rehabilitation Program from January 1984 through November
1988.
   Gonzalez asked why Adams made no ``specific recommendations
regarding possible violations of law'' by former HUD officials.
   Adams said his office had consulted with the Justice Department
throughout the investigation and found no evidence that criminal
statutes had been violated.
   ``I find a disturbing indication in the documents that because
these allocation formulas and the laws that pertain to HUD are not
criminal statutes, that the conspiracies that go on here of
individuals working together in order to go around established
procedures are treated as if they are not criminal matters,'' said
Rep. Bruce Morrison, D-Conn.
   Adams said the Justice Department is reviewing the report.
   Adams and Demery, appearing for the second time this week before
a congressional panel, described to the subcommittee their roles in
the program and the subsequent investigation into its selection and
allocation process.
   Demery insisted, as he had earlier, he shared with other HUD
officials concern about the ``discretionary'' nature of Pierce's
funding decisions in the program soon after his appointment in
October 1986.
   Demery said as a result of his persistence, a selection
committee was set up in January 1987, but Pierce retained final
approval over its recommendations.
   Rep. Joseph Kennedy, D-Mass., warned that the inspector
general's conclusions might ``compromise'' any future investigation.
   Rep. Marci Kaptur, D-Ohio, indicated she might request that a
special prosecutor investigate the program.
   ``I don't really hear legal reasoning, I hear administrative
reasoning'' in the inspector general's conclusions, she said.
   Other Democrats on the panel also questioned Adams and Demery
about how the congressionally mandated ``fair share'' allocations
to the states and regulations for public notice of competitive
bidding for contracts were circumvented.
   Peter Pretorius, the founder of Food for Africa, a favored
charity of Demery's, made a surprise appearance. Adam's report
indicated that Food had received large donations from several
developers that won contracts to renovate housing under the federal
rehabilitation program.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
