<FIRST>r i PM-Shamir     05-12 0314</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Shamir,0325</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prime Minister Released from Hospital After Tests</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir was released from
Jerusalem's Hadassah Hospital today after undergoing two days of
tests following complaints of fatigue, Shamir's office said.
   ``Mr. Shamir is feeling well and is in excellent mood. He will
rest at home during the weekend and will return to work Sunday,'' a
spokeswoman at prime minister's office said.
   Officials at Haddasah confirmed that Shamir, 73, intended to
attend a crucial Cabinet debate on his Middle East peace plan.
   ``Our prime minister took us by surprise and decided to leave
(three hours) earlier than scheduled,'' hospital spokeswoman Ruth
Mekel said. ``I think he went first to his home. As far as I
understand, he resumes work Sunday and will attend the Cabinet
meeting.''
   Mrs. Mekel quoted Shamir's doctors as saying the premier's tests
were good and that his physical condition was ``excellent.''
However, neither she nor officials in Shamir's office would say
what tests he underwent or provide details of his illness.
   ``He only complained of fatigue,'' Mrs. Mekel said. ``He really
worked very hard after returning from abroad.''
   Shamir traveled to the United States in April to unveil his
peace plan, calling for elections among Palestinians living in the
Israeli-occupied territories.
   Tuesday night, Shamir struck his head in a fall and complained
later he felt weak, according to his spokesman Yossi Ahimeir.
   However, during Israel's Independence Day celebrations, which
ran from Tuesday night to Wednesday night, Shamir appeared at a
half-dozen rallies.
   At the International Bible Quiz on Wednesday, he was wearing
dark glasses, with a large reddish welt visible on his right cheek.
   The lack of official comment on the nature of Shamir's illness
or what tests he was given prompted complaints by Israeli media.
They noted that illnesses of foreign leaders _ notably Americans _
usually brought detailed reports from government officials.
</TEXT>
