<DOCNO> AP890512-0054 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-12-89 0452EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-US-Panama-Chronology     05-12 0735</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Panama-Chronology,710</SECOND>
<HEAD>Look at 2-Year Slide in US-Panama Relations</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-US-Panama Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush's decision to order more U.S.
troops into Panama and evacuate some American dependents in the
wake of aborted elections and the beating of opposition leaders is
another benchmark in the two-year slide in relations between the
two nations.
   Twenty-five years ago, the United States and Panama actually
broke off diplomatic ties, temporarily, following anti-American
riots. But the more recent government of Gen. Manuel Antonio
Noriega, himself charged in the United States with drug
trafficking, has caused even more frustration and anger in
Washington.
   Here is a chronology of key events related to the Noriega regime:
   June 1987 _ Col. Roberto Diaz Herrera, the retiring
second-in-command of the Defense Forces, accuses Noriega of
drug-related activities, of rigging the 1984 election in favor of
government candidates, and of murdering Dr. Hugo Spadafora, a
former vice minister of health who had accused Noriega of drug
trafficking.
   June 9, 1987 _ A protest movement headed by the National Civic
Crusade, a grouping of professionals and students, demands a probe
into Herrera's allegations and a return to democracy. Street
protests are crushed brutally.
   Feb. 4, 1988 _ A federal grand jury in Miami indicts Noriega on
drug-  running charges. A grand jury in Tampa returns similar
indictments.
   Feb. 25, 1988 _ President Eric Delvalle, who was put in place by
Noriega, announces he has fired his patron. Eight hours later, the
National Assembly meets, ousts Delvalle and names Manuel Solis
Palma as minister in charge of the presidency, a title he retains.
The United States refuses to recognize Solis Palma. The government
closes opposition news media.
   March 16, 1988 _ A coup organized by Defense Forces officers
against Noriega fails. Demonstrations erupt in the capital and a
power outage blacks out the nation.
   March 28, 1988 _ After a large anti-Noriega march, members of
the Defense Forces enter the Marriott Hotel, beating and arresting
journalists and opposition leaders.
   April 9, 1988 _ The United States announces economic sanctions
that prohibit American companies and the government from making
payments to the Panamanian government. Some $56 million in
Panamanian funds in American banks are frozen. The United States
tries to negotiate the departure of Noriega without success.
   May 9, 1988 _ Banks reopen but with severe restrictions,
including a freeze on savings accounts.
   Aug. 21, 1988 _ The United States charges there were more than
240 cases of harassment of American military personnel by
Panamanian authorities so far that year.
   Sept. 13, 1988 _ The U.S. Defense Department reduces the tour of
duty for soldiers stationed in Panama to lower the number of
dependents in the country.
   Oct. 30, 1988 _ Assistant Secretary of State for Inter-American
Affairs Elliott Abrams admits the Reagan administration's efforts
to oust Noriega have failed.
   April 9, 1989 _ Economic sanctions are renewed for one year on
the basis that Washington considers Panama a threat to American
security.
   April and May 1989 _ The United States accuses Panama of
planning to win May 7 presidential elections by fraud. News reports
contend the United States authorized $10 million for the Panamanian
opposition, which becomes a major campaign issue.
   May 7-9, 1989 _ The elections are held, but Noriega's victory
claim is countered by rioters as well as international observers
who say the ballots were rigged. Former President Carter, one of
the U.S. observers, storms out of Panama's vote tabulation center
and denounces Noriega as a dictator who was stealing the election.
The protest is echoed in Congress and at the White House, which
says independent exit polling showed Noriega's slate was losing by
a 3-to-1 margin. One senator introduces legislation calling for
abrogation of the Panama Canal treaties, but the White House
rejects that approach.
   May 10, 1989 _ As defense forces look on, thugs loyal to Noriega
beat opposition candidate Guillermo Endara and his two running
mates, and one of their bodyguards is killed. The
Noriega-controlled Electoral Tribunal declares the elections null
and void ``in their totality.'' But ``We won and we will continue
to fight,'' says Guillermo Ford, the bloodied second vice
presidential candidate.
   May 11, 1989 _ President Bush orders 2,000 additional U.S.
military troops to Panama, joining 10,000 already there and decides
to evacuate more of the American dependents there. Some of the
dependents will be sent home, others moved to military bases for
safety.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890512-0055 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-12-89 0452EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-US-Panama-MilitaryUnits     05-12 0622</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Panama-Military Units,590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Details on U.S. Military Units Bush Ordered to Panama</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-US-Panama, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Army battalions on their way to Panama
include one from a ``light'' division organized for quick movement
around the world and one from a standard mechanized division that
trains to fight with personnel carriers and tanks.
   The one company from the 2nd Marine Division, meantime, is the
first to deploy on a real-world mission in what the corps calls its
Light Armored Vehicle, or LAV.
   President Bush ordered the battalions to Panama on Thursday.
   The LAV is an armored, eight-wheel personnel carrier that sports
a 25mm chain gun, which is a high-speed, heavy type of machine gun,
as well as a 7.62mm machine gun.
   The 7th Light Infantry Division and the 5th Infantry Division
are part of different corps within the Army _ I and III,
respectively _ and are based at different parts of the country _
Fort Ord, Calif., and Fort Polk, La.
   They also reflect deliberately different capabilities.
   The 7th, known as the Bayonet Division, was the first of four
active-duty light infantry divisions created by the Army during the
Reagan administration. Although the 7th has a long history as a
regular Army division, it didn't become a light infantry division
until Oct. 1, 1985.
   With about 10,700 soldiers assigned to it instead of the roughly
17,000 assigned to a normal mechanized division, the 7th is full of
riflemen; carries no heavy vehicles, and deploys with only modest
amounts of artillery and anti-tank weapons.
   The idea behind the light divisions, championed by former Army
Chief of Staff Gen. John Wickham, was to provide a president the
option of using a fairly large force that could be moved rapidly
around the world.
   For example, a normal heavy division, such as those assigned to
Europe, would require about 2,850 flights of a C-141 to deploy. A
complete light division could show up for combat with just 500
flights.
   The 7th was one of two Army units _ the other being the 82nd
Airborne _ tapped for a similar emergency deployment to Central
America in March 1988. In that case, the troops were sent to
Honduras because of incursions by Nicaraguan troops.
   The 5th Infantry Division, meantime, is a standard mechanized
division whose history dates to World War I. Known as the Red
Diamond Division, the 5th fought in four major campaigns during
World War I and five major campaigns in Europe during World War II.
   The 5th includes three active-duty mechanized brigades _ which
rely on armored personnel carriers such as the M-113 or the Bradley
Fighting Vehicle _ and three active-duty armor brigades equipped
with M-1A1 tanks.
   One ranking military official said Thursday a mechanized force
was being sent as a precaution in case the situation in Panama
deteriorated further and additional protection was needed to help
dependents evacuate.
   Although a mechanized infantry division can be transported by
air, the heavy equipment makes it a slow process. In this case, the
Pentagon announced the one battalion from the 5th would travel to
Panama by sea aboard the ship Bellatrix.
   The Marines, meantime, are sending Alpha Co. of the 2nd Light
Armored Infantry Battalion. That unit will be traveling by aircraft
with 18 of the new LAVs.
   The 2nd Marine Division traces its roots to Feb. 1, 1941, when
it was formed for World War II. During that war, the division
fought in some of the bloodiest battles of the Pacific, including
Guadalcanal, Tarawa and Okinawa.
   The 2nd also went to Lebanon in 1958 and 1982; to the Dominican
Republic in 1965, and to Grenada in 1983. It fights under the
motto, ``Second to None.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
