<DOCNO> AP890512-0060 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-12-89 0533EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-MidgetmanFails     05-12 0354</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Midgetman Fails,0365</SECOND>
<HEAD>Midgetman Missile Destroyed After Malfunction In First Test Flight</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VANDENBERG AIR FORCE BASE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first test flight
of an unarmed Midgetman missile was cut short when Air Force
officials destroyed the rocket after a malfunction.
   The missile began tumbling about 70 seconds after launch
Thursday morning as its second stage was firing. A range safety
officer issued a command that destroyed the missile two minutes and
nine seconds into flight, said Maj. Gen. Ed Barry, director of the
Midgetman program.
   ``This was a partial success in that we achieved 50 percent of
our flight objectives,'' Barry said.
   Excellent telemetry data was received on the first stage and
most of the second stage, he said. The missile was destroyed 10 to
12 seconds before the third stage was to ignite.
   The Midgetman is designed to be fired from a mobile, trucklike
launcher and has been in development since 1983.
   Steam pressure popped the missile 150 to 200 feet out of a
launch canister on a pad. Then its first stage rocket motor ignited
and boosted it across the partly cloudy, windy sky.
   The missile was supposed to deliver a dummy warhead to a test
range about 4,600 miles away in the Kwajalein Atoll about 30
minutes after launch.
   Barry said congressional critics shouldn't view the test as a
setback. ``This is a developmental flight testing program,'' he
said.
   The Midgetman, formally the Small Intercontinental Ballistic
Missile, is designed to carry a single nuclear warhead to a target
up to 6,900 miles away.
   Its future is clouded by an intense political debate over
whether the United States should develop one or two mobile,
land-based missiles for its nuclear arsenal. The Soviet Union
already has developed and begun deploying two such missiles. The
United States has none.
   A version of the 10-warhead MX missile that could be launched
from a railroad car is favored by Defense Secretary Dick Cheney,
who says the Pentagon would be hard pressed by the $25 billion cost
of 500 Midgetmans.
   But President Bush recently decided that both the MX and the
Midgetman should be developed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
