<DOCNO> AP890512-0062 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-12-89 0538EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i China-MoslemProtest     05-12 0663</FIRST>
<SECOND>China-Moslem Protest,0682</SECOND>
<HEAD>Moslem Students Protest Book on Sexual Practices</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 2,500 Chinese Moslems chanting ``Punish
China's Rushdie'' marched through Beijing today demanding two
editors be imprisoned for publishing a book on the sexual habits of
Moslems.
   ``These men must be jailed,'' said Li Jing, a Uighur Turk from
the Central Academy of Nationalities and a leader of the protest.
``If they disappeared from the face of the earth, we would be
happy.''
   The protest came a day after Iranian President Ali Khamenei told
a news conference in Beijing that Iran still demands the execution
of British author Salman Rushie, who is accused of blaspheming the
Islamic religion in his book, ``Satanic Verses.''
   The Chinese book in question is called ``Sex Habits,'' a
compilation of essays on the sexual tastes of people around the
world.
   The section on Islam says that the purpose of a Moslem's
pilgrammage to Mecca is to engage in bestiality. It said the domes
and towers of Moslem mosques symbolize human sex organs.
   In an unusually early report by Chinese standards, Beijing's
afternoon newspaper, the Beijing Evening News, reported the
demonstration. It also said the book had been banned in Beijing
``because it has hurt the unity of China's minorities.''
   ``The city Communist Party committee and city government clearly
stated that this book must be swiftly suppressed,'' the paper said.
   The demonstration, which included students from eight school and
13 minority groups, twisted through the streets of Beijing's Moslem
quarter to the Niujie Mosque, Bejing's oldest.
   Mullahs at the temple set out tea for the marches and police
directed traffic out of their path. The demonstration was the first
in more than three weeks of student protests in Beijing to be given
official approval. Earlier protests have called for a free press
and democracy.
   ``Allah is great!'' the crowd chanted as it marched down the
street. ``Down with blasphemy!''
   A member of the Uzbek minority led the protest, cradling a
framed letter of permission from the Beijing Public Security
Bureau. Hundreds of men in white fezzes and women in colored
scarves followed.
   ``We support them fully,'' said Ma Yue, an official at the
Niujie Mosque, as he watched the marchers pass. ``These men should
not be allowed to publish this stuff. They have seriously insulted
the Moslem peoples.''
   Uighur Turks, who inhabit the northwest province of Xinjiang,
are also known to clash occasionally with local Chinese in smaller
protests.
   The book's editors are Han Chinese, the main ethnic group in
China comprising more than 90 percent of the population. They are
apparently teachers from Shanxi province but published the book
under pen names.
   The book has been selling rapidly since it was published by the
Shanghai Cultural Publishing Co. in March. Chinese sources said
that in early May the Shanghai city government stopped a second
printing of the book, which had already sold 50,000 copies.
   City officials also are trying to recall the book, offering
three times its official price of 94 cents, but to no avail, they
said.
   ``The black market price has already hit 50 yuan ($13.50),''
said one Chinese journalist familiar with the book.
   On the street, students passed out leaflets.
   ``Our great and holy Islam religion has again been insulted by
vicious scoundrels,'' read one pamphlet referring to the first
insult as being the Rushdie affair. ``Facing this kind of brazen
insult, how can a true Moslem remain aloof?''
   The demonstration ended at Tiananmen Square, where student
leaders presented a letter to the National People's Congress,
China's legislature, calling for the imprisonment of the editors.
   One Moslem student, who watched from the protest from the Niujie
Mosque, said he supported the demonstration but did not believe the
editors should be jailed.
   ``It's just like the Rushdie case,'' he said. ``We shouldn't
kill these people or throw them in jail. We should criticize them.
I may be a Moslem but I am also a modern youth.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
