<FIRST>r a PM-PressAwards     05-12 0505</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Press Awards,0526</SECOND>
<HEAD>AP's Moscow Bureau Wins Overseas Press Club Prizes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Moscow bureau of The Associated Press won
two awards from the Overseas Press Club for coverage of the
earthquake in Soviet Armenia. The Wall Street Journal and CBS Inc.
also won two awards each.
   Three Time Inc. magazines _ Time, Fortune and People _ were
cited for their coverage of international news in 1988, the club
announced Thursday.
   Also, the Journalists Committee to Free Terry Anderson received
the President's Award for its efforts on behalf of the AP's chief
Middle East correspondent, who was captured on March 16, 1985.
   In an open letter to President Bush, Overseas Press Club
President Leonard Saffir called on the government to increase
efforts to bring about Anderson's release.
   ``What is our government doing?'' he wrote. ```We don't
negotiate with terrorists' has been the official line, but that's
not good enough. I pray that we don't exit our 50th anniversary
year without our friend and colleague back home.''
   The AP Moscow bureau's reporting on the Armenian earthquake in
December won the Hal Boyle Award for best daily news coverage, and
AP photographer Boris Yurchenko won for his photos of the disaster.
   Chris Steele-Perkins of Time magazine won the Robert Capa Gold
Medal for photographic coverage ``requiring exceptional courage and
enterprise'' for ``Graveside Terror,'' a photo essay of a terrorist
attack in Northern Ireland.
   The other awards for news coverage from abroad were:
   _Interpretation of foreign affairs, Barry Newman of The Wall
Street Journal for articles on the Soviet Union and Eastern Europe.
   _Business or economic reporting in a newspaper, Philip Revzin,
The Wall Street Journal, for articles on the European Common Market.
   _Business or economic reporting in a magazine, John Curran of
Fortune magazine for a report on Tokyo's stock market.
   _General magazine article on foreign affairs, Karsten Prager,
Murray J. Gart, Johanna McGeary, Michael Kramer and Ed Magnuson,
writers, and Dean Fischer and B. William Mader, reporters, Time
magazine.
   _For reporting ``showing a concern for the human condition,''
Harry Benson and Civia Tamarkin, People magazine, for ``Celia
Goldie: Dealing with the Aged, a World Wide Problem.''
   _For television spot news, the ``CBS Evening News with Dan
Rather'' for ``Inside the Kremlin.''
   _For radio spot news, David Ben-Aryeah, WCBS News-AM Radio, for
reports on the crash of Pan Am Flight 103.
   _For photographic reporting in magazines or books, Maggie
Steber, U.S. News and World Report.
   _For best radio interpretation of foreign affairs, Alex
Chadwick, National Public Radio.
   _For television interpretation or documentary on foreign
affairs, Ted Koppel and Richard Kaplan, ABC News ``Nightline.''
   _For magazine reporting from abroad, Richard M. Smith and team,
Newsweek.
   _For cartoons on foreign affairs, Jim Morin, The Miami Herald.
   _For a book on foreign affairs, Whitman Bassow, for ``The Moscow
Correspondents: Reporting from the Revolution to Glasnost.''
   _For reporting on human rights, Colin Campbell and Deborah
Scroggins, Atlanta Journal and Atlanta Constitution.
   _For print reporting for publication outside the United States,
Alex Brummer, The Guardian (London and Manchester).
</TEXT>
