<DOCNO> AP890512-0067 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-12-89 0627EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-DupontPlaza     05-12 0296</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dupont Plaza,0303</SECOND>
<HEAD>$100 Million Settlement Reported in Dupont Plaza Fire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A settlement has been reached in
the Dupont Plaza fire of New Year's Eve 1986 that calls for the
hotel to pay $100 million to about 2,300 plaintiffs, a newspaper
reported. The blaze killed 97 people.
   The San Juan Star, an English-language daily, said in its report
Thursday that lawyers had agreed to $100 million and signed the
deal late Tuesday in the Philadelphia court chambers of U.S.
District Judge Louis Bechtle.
   Federal Judge Raymond L. Acosta was given a sealed envelope
Wednesday containing details of a settlement. Court spokesman Pedro
A. Malonet would not reveal the terms, but said Acosta would
announce today whether he accepted the agreement.
   The Star Tribune of Minneapolis quoted James Fetterly, a
Minneapolis lawyer for the hotel, as saying the settlement would be
substantially less than the $200 million for the the 1980 MGM Hotel
fire in Las Vegas.
   Plaintiffs in the case, being tried in U.S. District Court in
San Juan, had sought damages of $1.8 billion.
   A former hotel maintenance worker pleaded guilty to setting the
Dupont Plaza fire during a labor dispute at the 22-story hotel,
which was packed with almost 1,000 tourists. About 140 people were
injured.
   The hotel was cited for 25 violations by the Occupational Safety
and Health Administration, including lack of emergency exits from
the casino, where 84 of the victims died.
   Richard Bieder, whose Bridgeport, Conn., law firm represents the
families of the nine Connecticut people killed in the blaze,
confirmed Wednesday there was a settlement, but refused to discuss
the amount.
   Fetterly said the settlement did not cover claims against about
170 defendants, including those who provided furnishings and
services in the hotel.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890512-0068 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-12-89 0639EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-China-MoslemProtest     05-12 0669</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Moslem Protest,0689</SECOND>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING a0499 to restore cycle designator</HEAD>
<HEAD>Moslem Students Protest Book on Sexual Practices</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 2,500 Chinese Moslems chanting ``Punish
China's Rushdie'' marched through Beijing today demanding two
editors be imprisoned for publishing a book on the sexual habits of
Moslems.
   ``These men must be jailed,'' said Li Jing, a Uighur Turk from
the Central Academy of Nationalities and a leader of the protest.
``If they disappeared from the face of the earth, we would be
happy.''
   The protest came a day after Iranian President Ali Khamenei told
a news conference in Beijing that Iran still demands the execution
of British author Salman Rushie, who is accused of blaspheming the
Islamic religion in his book, ``Satanic Verses.''
