<HEAD>Thunderstorms Erupt in the West</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Thunderstorms continued to pound western Texas early today,
hours after tornadoes touched down in New Mexico and Montana.
   In Texas, thunderstorms left dime-size hail 3 inches deep at
Frankel City, and more than 4 inches of rain fell in less than an
hour at Fort Stockton late Thursday.
   A combination of moist, unstable air and a cold front produced
severe thunderstorms across parts of the Rockies and high Plains
late Thursday.
   A tornado near Jal, N.M., destroyed a horse barn made of steel
pipe. In other parts of the state, baseball-size hail pounded
Roswell and more than an inch of rain fell in an hour near Santa
Rosa.
   In Montana, a tornado touched down east of Miles City, ripping
part of a dormitory roof off the Pine Hills State School. Two other
tornadoes were spotted in eastern Montana, and hail an inch in
diameter fell at Billings.
   Heavy rain also fell over northern Utah, with 1{ inches at
Bountiful and 1\ inches east of Salt Lake City.
   Thunderstorms also produced as much as 1{ inches of rain and
lowland flooding in Banner and Scottsbluff counties in western
Nebraska.
   Rain continued to fall over New England and the lower Great
Lakes. More than 3 inches of rain soaked Portland, Maine, in the 24
hours ended early today.
   Today's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms from the
northern and central Rockies to the western Plains; severe
thunderstorms likely from southwest Texas to the Texas and Oklahoma
panhandles; and showers over the northern and middle Atlantic
Coast, the lower Great Lakes and the upper Ohio Valley.
   Highs were expected to be in the 50s and 60s over much of the
northern and middle Atlantic Coast, the Ohio Valley, the Great
Lakes, the northern and central Pacific Coast and parts of the
western Plains; in the 80s over southern and central Florida,
southern Louisiana, most of Texas, the Desert Southwest and parts
of the northern Plains; and in the 70s elsewhere.
   Temperatures at 2 a.m. EDT ranged from 33 degrees at Ely, Nev.,
to 77 degrees at Corpus Christi, Texas.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 50 fair; Boston 52 drizzle; Buffalo 44 drizzle;
Charleston, S.C. 53 fair; Cincinnati 43 fair; Cleveland 45 cloudy;
Detroit 46 rain; Miami 69 smoke; New York 51 cloudy; Philadelphia
49 partly cloudy; Pittsburgh 41 rain; Portland, Maine 50
thunderstorm.
   _Central: Bismarck 59 windy; Chicago 46 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth
65 cloudy; Denver 59 cloudy; Des Moines 51 fair; Indianapolis 38
fair; Kansas City 52 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 50 fair; Nashville
48 fair; New Orleans 65 fair; St. Louis 51 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 59 fair; Anchorage 41 partly cloudy; Las
Vegas 56 cloudy; Los Angeles 55 fair; Phoenix 67 fair; Salt Lake
City 47 rain; San Diego 60 cloudy; San Francisco 51 fair; Seattle
49 rain.
   _Canada: Montreal 50 rain; Toronto 50 foggy.
