<FIRST>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     05-12 0395</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0414</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Higher But Off Best Levels, Gold Also Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar was higher in early European
trading today but off its best levels after the Bank of Japan
indicated its recent rise had gone too far. Gold prices were also
higher.
   Some traders maintained the dip was only a technical correction
and said support for the dollar remains strong.
   As the dollar surged to an eight-month high in Tokyo, the Bank
of Japan said it will take appropriate action with other
industrialized nations if necessary to curb its strength.
   But one trader in Milan said despite concerns of the West German
and Japanese central banks that the dollar is too strong, the
market will continue to call the shots.
   ``This is a situation where the market is dictating. Even if
they want to revalue the mark there is nothing they can do as long
as marks are being sold to buy dollars,'' one trader said. He said
central bank intervention was unlikely until current conditions
change.
   Traders said a report later today on U.S. producer prices for
April may give an additional boost to the dollar if it confirms
market expectations that inflationary pressures aren't easing. The
market forecast a rise of 0.7 percent in the producer price index
for April following a 0.4 percent increase in March.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar hit 135.80 yen, up 1.25 yen. Later, in London,
it rose even higher to 135.90 yen.
   Other dollar rates at mid-morning, compared with late Thursday:
   _1.9160 German marks, up from 1.9135
   _1.71215 Swiss francs, up from 1.7060
   _6.48075 French francs, up from 6.4665
   _2.16235 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1580
   _1,396.80 Italian lire, up from 1,395.75
   _1.1870 Canadian dollars, unchanged
   In London, the British pound fell to $1.6635, compared with
$1.6655 Thursday.
   Bullion dealers said gold prices were flirting with the $380
level for the first time in recent weeks.
   Gold opened in London at $380.15 a troy ounce, up from $379 bid
late Thursday. At midmorning, the city's five major bullion dealers
fixed a recommended price of $379.65.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $379.70, up from $378.20 bid late
Thursday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $2.30 to close at $380.26.
   Silver was quoted in London today at $5.66 a troy ounce,
unchanged from Thursday's late bid.
</TEXT>
