<FIRST>r a PM-RunawayTruck     05-12 0438</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Runaway Truck,0451</SECOND>
<HEAD>Five Killed by Runaway Tractor-Trailer; Mountain Road Had Drawn Complaints</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAUGHLINTOWN, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Villagers complained about the safety
of a steep mountain road just two days before a runaway
tractor-trailer careened down the road and smashed a car, killing
five people, a resident said.
   The 18-wheel truck with yellow ``Wide Load'' signs was carrying
a huge ditch-digging machine down Laurel Mountain on U.S. 30, about
50 miles east of Pittsburgh, state police said.
   With its headlights flashing and horn blaring, the runaway truck
roared about two miles down the two-lane road into this village of
750 people, slamming into a passenger car and killing the three
people inside. The truck's driver and his passenger also died.
   Westmoreland County Deputy Coroner Joe Musgrove identified the
victims as Walter Lepley, 63, who was driving the car; his wife,
Helen, 57; and Robert Holsopple, 83, all of Boswell.
   The driver of the truck was identified as Donald Frey, 34, of
Clyde, Ohio, and his passenger as James Burkholder, 45, of
Bloomington, Ind.
   No other injuries were reported.
   After hitting the car, the truck's cab and flatbed trailer
slammed into a three-story frame apartment house. Witnesses said
the cab burst into flames, which soon engulfed the building.
   ``I ran to the scene and saw bodies lying everywhere, pieces of
bodies everywhere,'' said Jack Steitz, who operates Ligioner
Mountain Outfitters, directly across from the highway from the
apartment building.
   Tom Harrison, who lived in the apartment building, said he was
stepping out of the building at midmorning when he saw the truck
coming. He said he alerted the only other person in the building at
the time, a woman on the third floor, and both escaped safely.
   Meanwhile, the ditch-digging machine spun about 100 yards beyond
the truck, hitting several telephone poles and signs before
skidding to a stop in front of the Ligonier Country Inn, witnesses
said.
   For several hours, electricity was cut to about 400 homes and
the highway was closed while authorities cleared the debris and
doused the fire.
   State police said the rig may have lost its brakes.
   Steitz said the mountain has a turnoff near its summit for
trucks to check their brakes, but no escape ramp on the descending
curves.
   As recently as Tuesday, Laughlintown residents presented a
petition to the Ligonier Township Commission demanding the
municipal government do something about the danger of runaway
trucks on the highway, he said.
   Authorities said the truck was owned by Bower Billing Services
of Clyde, Ohio, and was en route from Baltimore to Clyde. The
company was not listed in an Ohio telephone directory.
</TEXT>
