<DOCNO> AP890512-0076 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-12-89 0753EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Lebanon     05-12 0458</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon,0473</SECOND>
<HEAD>Syrian Rockets Hit Christian Coastline</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syrian gunners fired six rockets at the
Christian coastline today in a barrage apparently designed to warn
Gen. Michel Aoun against using a cease-fire to resupply his troops.
   The United States and the Soviet Union called in a joint
statement for an end to hostilities in Lebanon.
   Police said the Soviet-designed 122mm Grad rockets were fired
from Moslem west Beirut shortly before dawn. They crashed along the
coast north of Beirut, causing damage but no injuries.
   A police spokesman said that was the only violation today of a
day-old cease fire called by the Arab League. It was the fifth
truce called by the league in two months of bloodletting between
Aoun's 22,000 Christian army troops and an alliance of Syrian and
Druse Moslem forces.
   Lebanon's government is split by rival Cabinets, the Christian
on headed by Aoun and the Moslem one led by Salim Hoss.
   By police count, 359 people have been killed and 1,393 wounded
since the fighting broke out March 8. It has been described as the
most destructive of Lebanon's 14-year-old civil war, with damage
estimated at more than $300 million.
   In a joint statement issued at the end of Secretary of State
James Baker's visit to Moscow, the two superpowers said they ``are
prepared to provide good offices so that, jointly with other
states, they may promote a political solution to the problem of
Lebanon, taking into consideration the interests of all sides.''
   Syria and its allies have claimed that the barrages on the
Christian ports were to prevent three ships cruising in the
Mediterranean from unloading Iraqi supplies. Aoun has denied in the
past receiving arms from Iraq.
   Syria is Iraq's chief Arab enemy. Ruled by rival wings of the
Baath Party, the two governments are competing for influence in
Lebanon.
   Baghdad has openly declared support for Aoun's pledge to drive
Syria's 40,000 troops out of Lebanon. These soldiers control about
70 percent of Lebanon under a 1976 Arab League peacekeeping mandate.
   Fighting flared two days after Aoun ordered a blockade of three
illegal ports run by Syrian-backed militias south of Beirut to
recoup millions of dollars of customs dues.
   Druse warlord Walid Jumblatt said in an interview published
today did not believe a settlement was possible.
   He told the Kuwaiti newspaper Al-Watan: ``There is no solution
in Lebanon, but rather a long war interrupted by limited truces.''
   He criticized the six-member Arab League panel on Lebanon,
saying it was seeking ``a truce whereby Aoun replenishes his
arsenal, not a settlement.''
   He said the Christians were also receiving help not only from
Iraq but from Yasser Arafat's Palestine Liberation Organization,
another enemy of Syria.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890512-0077 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-12-89 0806EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Vietnam-Excavation     05-12 0301</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Vietnam-Excavation,0310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ancient Teeth Found in Important Archaeological Discovery</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S.-Vietnamese scientific team has
found two human teeth believed to be 40,000 years old, an official
report said.
   The Vietnam News Agency reported the discovery in a recent
excavation at the Lang Trang Cave in the Ba Thuoc district of Thanh
Hoa province, 95 miles south of Hanoi.
   The report, dated Thursday, was monitored in Bangkok today.
   ``The teeth, one an incisor and the other a first molar,
unearthed from a layer of carbonate-rich clay sediment, are
believed to date to 40,000 years back, probably belonging to homo
sapiens,'' the report said.
   Recent archaeological finds have traced back about 500,000 years
the earliest human habitation of northern Vietnam.
   Also found in the sediment were animal fossils of 36 species and
23 families, the report said. It did not specify when the
discoveries were made.
   The team, set up by the Vietnam Archaeology Institute, included
Nguyen Van Hao, deputy head of the institute; paleontologist Le
Trung Kha; archaeologist John Olsen of the University of Arizona
and paleoanthropologist Russel Chioson of the University of Iowa.
   Olsen and Chioson were among scientists who in January journeyed
to Thanh Hoa to join Vietnamese scientists in searching a limestone
cave for remains of the ``gigantophithecus,'' an ape that became
extinct more than 200,000 years ago.
   They hoped to establish relationships among homo erectus, the
direct ancestors of modern humans, stone tools used by early man,
and the giant ape, since the remains of all three have been found
in that area.
   The excavation was one of the first joint scientific field
research projects in Vietnam in recent years. Diplomatic relations
have been blocked by Washington's opposition to Vietnam's
decade-old occupation of Cambodia, but private contacts have
increased substantially in recent years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
