<FILEID>AP-NR-05-12-89 0832EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Germany-Missiles     05-12 0445</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Germany-Missiles,0459</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kohl Applauds Soviet Arms Reduction Offer</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Baker</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GIRARD C. STEICHEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chancellor Helmut Kohl said today he
welcomed the Soviet Union's offer to reduce its stockpile of
short-range nuclear missiles and tactical weapons.
   But Kohl, at the center of a divisive NATO dispute over the
short-range missile issue, urged the Kremlin to take further steps
to eliminate its superiority in conventional and nuclear forces.
   ``This proposal is certainly a step in the right direction,''
Kohl said in a statement. ``But we urge once again that the Soviet
Union work toward reducing its crass superiority in conventional
and nuclear forces.''
   ``We want to arrive at a point where the Soviet Union _ like
NATO already _ is no longer capable of launching a surprise attack
or an invasion,'' he said.
   Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev on Thursday offered to
unilaterally remove 500 tactical nuclear warheads from Eastern
Europe this year. He also proposed superpower negotiations on the
reduction of short-range nuclear weapons in Europe.
   Kohl's statement on the offer mirrored that of Secretary of
State James A. Baker III, who called Gorbachev's proposal ``a good
step, but a small step.''
   Kohl said Gorbachev's offer was in part the result of his
continued calls for such cuts.
   Baker described Gorbachev's decision to carry out a unilateral
reduction of 5 percent from an arsenal of 10,000 battlefield
nuclear weapons as a ``modest move.''
   The cuts Gorbachev intends to make this year _ without requiring
action by NATO _ include 284 short-range missiles, 166 nuclear
bombs carried by airplanes and 50 nuclear artillery shells.
   Gorbachev also proposed reductions in tanks, combat aircraft and
artillery pieces.
   Baker was in Brussels today to brief senior NATO officials on
the results of his visit to Moscow.
   He was expected to meet with West German Foreign Minister
Hans-Dietrich Genscher, who along with Kohl has urged early
superpower talks on the reduction of short-range nuclear weapons.
Most of the weapons are in West Germany.
   The United States and Britain have rejected the call, saying
that the Warsaw Pact was so far ahead in tactical nuclear weapons
and conventional forces that negotiations could not be considered
until the imbalance was significantly reduced.
   The dispute has split the alliance before a crucial NATO summit
to be held in Brussels later this month.
   The arms reductions proposals were expected to be a central
topic of conversation during talks today between Kohl and Soviet
Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze, who was in Bonn.
   In Moscow, the official Tass news agency said Shevardnadze would
discuss a document setting out the ``fundamental concept'' of
relations between the two countries.
</TEXT>
