<HEAD>Report Deng To Retire After Gorbachev Visit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hong Kong newspapers reported today that
China's paramount leader Deng Xiaoping will retire from political
life after his summit next week with Soviet leader Mikhail
Gorbachev next week.
   The Chinese language Ming Pao Daily News, which is respected for
its China coverage, quoted unidentified sources as saying Chinese
Premier Li Peng disclosed the 84-year-old Deng's retirement plans
at a meeting Tuesday in Beijing with Iranian President Ali Khamenei.
   Another Chinese daily, Sing Pao Daily News, said Communist Party
General Secretary Zhao Ziyang will replace Deng as chairman of the
influential Central Military Commission, the only major official
post now held by Deng.
   It did not indicate whether Zhao would retain his party
chairmanship.
   Ming Pao said Deng no longer will meet foreign leaders after the
Gorbachev visit, which begins Monday, and will retire formally from
domestic politics.
   Deng has been in semi-retirement for several years and
repeatedly has said he would like to turn over power to younger
leaders.
   He is believed to be in declining health, and Ming Pao said his
doctors originally discourged him from meeting Khamenei so he could
conserve his energy for the Gorbachev visit.
   It said the Iranians pressed for a meeting and the Chinese
agreed.
   Reports from Beijing said Deng looked frail at the meeting,
which lasted only 20 minutes.
   Gorbachev will be the first Soviet leader to viist China in 30
years, when Beijing challenged Moscow's right to dominate the world
communist movement. The visit is expected to normalize relations
between the neighbors.
</TEXT>
