<FIRST>r a PM-RacketeeringSentences     05-12 0365</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Racketeering Sentences,0376</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mob Boss Scarfo Gets Longest Sentence of 55 Years</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE LINDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mob boss Nicodemo ``Little Nicky'' Scarfo
drew a 55-year sentence and a $500,000 fine in a racketeering
conspiracy case that investigators say crippled one of the nation's
most powerful Mafia families.
   In nine days of sentencing, a U.S. district judge handed out
sentences of 30 to 45 years to 15 of the 16 others convicted along
with Scarfo last November. Charges in the racketeering conspiracy
included 13 murders and attempted killings.
   An 18th defendant, before trial, pleaded guilty only to illegal
gambling and got a 3{-year sentence in a deal for leniency. One
convicted gangster won an indefinite delay in his sentencing when
he agreed to cooperate with the government.
   For the 59-year-old Scarfo, of Atlantic City, N.J., Thursday's
maximum sentence of 55 years imprisonment means he'll probably
spend the rest of his life behind bars.
   U.S. District Judge Franklin Van Antwerpen directed that the
sentence begin only after Scarfo completes a 14-year federal term
he is serving for a $1 million extortion attempt and a life term
for murder imposed last month by a Pennsylvania judge.
   Scarfo is said to be boss of a Philadelphia-South Jersey mob
considered to be one of the most powerful among the nation's 24 La
Cosa Nostra organizations.
   The government alleged that Scarfo, as a member of the Mafia's
national commission, was among the most powerful criminals in the
United States.
   David Fritchey, one of the five members of the government team,
told the judge ``the end of this mob family hasn't happened yet,
but it is severely crippled.''
   Scarfo's sentencing followed that of his nephew, Philip
Leonetti, 36, of Margate, N.J., who was identified as the mob
underboss. He drew the maximum 45-year term.
   The judge directed that Scarfo be sent to federal prison at
Marion, Ill.
   Scarfo stood impassively next to his lawyer, declining to
address the court, and merely shrugged his shoulders, in a gesture
of expectation, when the sentence was handed down.
   Scarfo was found guilty of participating in eight murders, four
attempted murders, 17 extortions, two drug deals plus bookmaking
and loansharking.
</TEXT>
