<FIRST>r w PM-RaidFoulup     05-12 0480</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Raid Foulup,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Local Cops, Feds Make Back-to-Back Drug Raids</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Marion Barry arrived at an alleged crack
house with eviction papers in his hand and television cameras by
his side, surprising 16 people in the apartment and federal agents
who arrived an hour later to serve a search warrant.
   Barry directed city workers to nail shut the apartment's windows
and doors Thursday. Agents from the Treasury Department's Bureau of
Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms soon appeared and tore down the
plywood boards and ignored the ``No Trespassing'' signs erected by
the city.
   ``This is a classic case of no coordination,'' Lt. Reginald L.
Smith, a city police spokesman, told The Washington Post. ``You're
going to need coordination to fight this war on drugs and ... no
one's talking to each other.''
   Federal agents said their search warrant was based on a previous
alleged drug purchase at the apartment in the city's southeast
section, where drug-related violence has been high.
   ATF spokesman Dick Pedersen said both local and federal
authorities were just trying to do their jobs. ``If there is a
little overlap, that's OK. No one got hurt,'' he said.
   No one was found in the apartment in the federal raid and no one
was arrested in the city raid, conducted by police, Barry and more
than a dozen representatives of the city housing department.
   A small plastic bag containing what appeared to be 18 rocks of
crack cocaine, worth $50 each, was found in the middle of the front
room during the first raid and confiscated by police.
   Capt. Robert Boggs, who accompanied Barry and a handful of
reporters through the apartment, said he could not make arrests
based on such evidence.
   Barry said the home was being closed because the tenant listed
on the lease owes the city $1,200 in back rent and the apartment
had been the scene of a gunfight between an off-duty police officer
and two men Wednesday night.
   According to housing officials, police had raided the residence
twice before, in August and October 1988, and found guns and crack.
The tenant had been given two previous eviction notices, but
because of delays in the eviction process, he remained in the
building, they said.
   The mayor said he initiated the eviction after he heard over his
police radio a gunfight between an off-duty police officer and two
men in the neighborhood Wednesday night. He visited the housing
project that night and warned residents of the apartment, ``I'm
going to put you out.''
   Barry's administration has come under criticism for failing the
stem the increase in drug-related violence, and the White House has
chosen Washington as the focal point for a new national anti-drug
campaign.
   Barry himself has been criticized for his personal associations,
including his friendship with a former official of the U.S. Virgin
Islands government recently convicted of drug trafficking.
</TEXT>
