<FIRST>r a PM-FallenStar 1stLd-Writethru a0466 05-12 0660</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fallen Star, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0466,0673</SECOND>
<HEAD>Player Once Seen As Can't-Miss NBA Star Shot Over $8 Drug Debt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 2 grafs to recast, UPDATE that Daniels remains critical
today; Picks up 3rd graf, `Daniels reportedly ...'; A longer version slugged
PM-Lloyd Daniels moving on sports wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY McSHANE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Once he was compared to Magic Johnson, but Lloyd
Daniels _ a National Basketball Association all-star in waiting _
never escaped the city streets where his game first flourished.
   Daniels was in critical condition today after a drug-related
shooting. It was the latest episode in a troubled 22-year life that
has taken him through five high schools, two rehabilitation centers
and, finally, to a hospital.
   Daniels reportedly was shot three times in the neck and torso
Thursday in a dispute over an $8 drug debt.
   Although his talent helped him receive chance upon chance to
straighten out his life, it might have aggravated some of his
problems, said a close friend of the 6-foot-8 Daniels.
   ``I definitely think certain things were overlooked because of
his talent,'' said Lou D'Almeida, a basketball fanatic who took
Daniels under his wing four years ago. ``He wasn't required to make
any decisions early on.
   ``That was the only problem he had _ trouble making the right
decisions. That, and pushing himself in school.''
   Academics were never Daniels' strong suit. ``I ain't allergic to
no school. I just don't want to go,'' he said.
   When he arrived at the University of Nevada-Las Vegas in 1987,
Daniels could read at a third-grade level.
   Time magazine aptly summed up his diploma-less odyssey through
five high schools in three states: ``Each school had availed itself
of his talents on the court but never managed to solve his profound
reading problems.''
   As he got older, Daniels began making the wrong decisions: he
was arrested on a drug charge in Nevada. He began drinking heavily.
His work habits led to his release from two teams within three
months last year.
   But through the drinking, the drugs, the dropouts, Daniels had
one thing to hold on to: his game.
   At Andrew Jackson High School in New York City, ``Sweet Pea''
Daniels averaged 31.2 points, 12.3 rebounds and 10 assists per game
_ until quitting in February 1986.
   In a high school all-star game several months later, Daniels
limited Sean Higgins _ a key performer for champion University of
Michigan _ to 8 points while pouring in 24 himself.
   As he was refusing help from a drug rehabilitation program,
Daniels was scoring 16 points per game and showing glimpses of his
old skills with the Topeka Sizzlers of the Continental Basketball
Association. He wore out his welcome there in just 29 games and was
cut in February 1988.
   While sucking down a case of beer per day, he still averaged 27
points per game in the New Zealand Basketball Federation last year,
but his drinking led to his release in May 1988.
   ``He's as gifted a ball player as I've ever seen,'' said Jerry
Tarkanian, head coach at college basketball powerhouse UNLV.
``Without question, he could have been an NBA all-star every year.''
   Tarkanian compared his overall skills to those of Los Angeles
Lakers star Magic Johnson. St. John's University head coach Lou
Carnesecca _ who's handled such home-grown talent as Chris Mullin,
Mark Jackson and Walter Berry _ said Daniels was one of the
greatest players New York City had ever produced.
   Recently, Daniels was showing signs of making another comeback.
He visited the Tarkanian family on Christmas Day and appeared
clean, healthy and ready to play ball, Tarkanian recalled.
   But Daniels may be running out of chances _ if he hasn't run out
of them already.
   ``I'm just keeping my fingers crossed. Now he should learn his
lesson _ what else could be more scary than the possibility of
losing his life?'' asked D'Almeida. ``Hopefully, he'll come through
this.''
</TEXT>
