<FIRST>r i PM-Japan-BankThreats     05-12 0256</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Bank Threats,0265</SECOND>
<HEAD>Group Reportedly Mails Cyanide Letters to Japanese Banks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A suspected right-wing group sent threatening
letters with packages of cyanide to 10 Japanese banks that
reportedly provided loans to Soviet bloc nations, news reports said
today.
   The nationally circulated Asahi Shimbun quoted unidentified
police officials as saying it was the first time they had dealt
with the group, which called itself ``Heisei Shimpuren.''
   The group sent the letters to the banks after the political
affairs magazine Shokun reported they had provided loans to the
Soviet Union and Eastern European countries, the newspaper said.
   The banks included Fuji Bank, Taiyo Kobe Bank, Sumitomo Trust
and Banking, and Mitsui Trust and Banking, the newspaper said.
   The Sankei Shimbun newspaper said the envelopes contained
packets of cyanide along with messages including ``Do not provide
funds to the USSR!'' ``If you do not stop, we will attack your
company!'' and ``Take the poison and die!''
   Police believe the group is made up of rightists, the Kyodo News
Service reported.
   The name Shimpuren is the same as that of a rightist group that
opposed the modernizing reforms of the Japanese government during
the late 19th century, Asahi said. Heisei is the name of the
present Japanese emperor's reign.
   Police said the letters were sent from various locations in
western Japan between May 1 and Wednesday, the newspapers said.
   Police officials refused comment on the reports.
   One of the four banks identified in the newspaper reports
confirmed having received a letter, but the others refused comment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
