<FIRST>r i PM-Cambodia     05-12 0365</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cambodia,0373</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vietnam Says China Reneged on Promises Of Normalization</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China has reneged on a promise to
normalize relations with Vietnam if Hanoi withdraws its forces from
Cambodia, Vietnam's official Communist Party newspaper charged
today.
   The Nhan Dan newspaper said China backed away from a previous
pledge during talks in Beijing this week on Cambodia, where
Vietnamese forces are battling insurgents armed by China.
   The newspaper said that during the talks, the Chinese ``made an
overall solution to the Cambodian issue a condition for the
normalization of relations between China and Vietnam, urged Vietnam
to agree to the composition of a transitional government ... and to
resolve the question of the armies of the Cambodian factions.''
   ``Obviously, these demands of the Chinese side are inconsistent
with the position it has taken earlier,'' it said.
   It said that on March 1, 1985, China's Foreign Ministry issued a
statement saying: ``If the Vietnamese government decides to pull
out all of its troops from Cambodia, the Chinese side will, right
after the first withdrawal of Vietnamese troops, be ready to resume
negotiations between the two countries.
   ``At the same time, as more and more Vietnamese troops continue
to be withdrawn, the Chinese side will take practical steps to
improve its relations with Vietnam.''
   Vietnam invaded Cambodia in late 1978 and overthrew the
fanatical Khmer Rouge, which is accused of killing tens of
thousands of people while trying to set up a Marxist agrarian
system. The Khmer Rouge now is one of three guerrilla factions
seeking to oust the Vietnamese-backed regime.
   Vietnam has promised to withdraw its troops from Cambodia by
Sept. 30. But the makeup of a transitional government and fears
that the Khmer Rouge will return to power have complicated the
talks.
   On Thursday, Chinese Foreign Ministry spokesman Jin Guihua
blamed Vietnam for the failure of the talks between the vice
ministers.
   He said the Cambodian issue is one of the major topics on the
agenda of the May 15-18 summit between Soviet President Mikhail
Gorbachev and China's top leaders, including Deng Xiaoping. He
indicated China will ask the Soviets to urge Vietnam to withdraw
its troops and seek a comprehensive settlement.
</TEXT>
