<FIRST>r a PM-WaterlooSlayings     05-12 0304</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Waterloo Slayings,0314</SECOND>
<HEAD>Authorities Suspect Murder-Suicide in Family's Deaths</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WATERLOO, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A couple and their three children who were
found in their home after being dead for more than a week died in
an apparent case of murder-suicide, police said.
   The bodies of David M. Fager, 34; his wife, Roxane, 31; and
their children, Bryce Allan, 16; Michael Edward, 11; and Melissa
Lynn, 9, were found Thursday in their locked home by authorities
who became suspicious because the children had not been in school
for days.
   The parents died of gunshot wounds to the head, said DeKalb
County Prosecutor Monte L. Brown. The children also died of
gunshots wounds, but no other details on their deaths were
available.
   A large-caliber handgun was found near David Fager's body,
police said.
   Police were unsure if the same weapon was used in each slaying.
   ``Until we do an autopsy and recover the bullets, we won't
know,'' Brown said. ``There is no reason to believe there was more
than one weapon.''
   Brown said he believed Fager had been unemployed for more than
six months. Mrs. Fager also is believed to have been unemployed.
   Neighbors said the family gave no indication of being troubled
or violent.
   ``They were just a beautiful family, beautiful people,'' said
Marcia Tomaszewski, who lives across the street from the Fagers in
this town of 1,900.
   The family apparently had been dead since May 3, Brown said.
That was the last time any of them was seen in public. School
officials alerted police.
   ``They contacted Waterloo police. The Waterloo police contacted
us. We obtained a court order to go into the house, and that's when
we discovered the bodies,'' Brown said.
   Police said they were no signs of forced entry and they had to
break in a door to enter the home.
</TEXT>
