<FIRST>r i PM-Greece-USBases     05-12 0239</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Greece-US Bases,0245</SECOND>
<HEAD>Negotiators Hold Last Round of Talks Before Greek Elections</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Greek and U.S. negotiators today suspended
talks on the future of four U.S. military bases in Greece and will
resume negotiations following elections next month, a government
spokesman said.
   The spokesman, Sotiris Kostopoulos, did not say if any headway
had been made in the negotiations, the 17th round of talks on a new
bases agreement to replace a five-year accord that expired in
December.
   Kostopoulos said a date for the next round of talks would be set
``following an agreement between the two sides.'' The talks would
follow the June 18 elections, he said.
   In previous rounds, negotiations stalled because Greece insisted
the United States make assurances it would help solve Greece's
differences with Turkey.
   The neighbors have differences over military control of the
Aegean Sea, seabed mineral rights and the divided eastern
Mediterranean island of Cyprus.
   Western diplomatic sources said talks also have been stymied by
Premier Andreas Papandreou's decision to close an Air Force base
adjacent to Athens international airport and his pre-election
pledge to hold a national referendum on any new agreement.
   Under the old accord, Greece and the United States have until
June 1990 to reach an agreement before the bases are shut.
   Four U.S. military bases have operated in Greece since the ealy
1950s _ two near Athens and two on the southern Aegean island of
Crete.
