<FIRST>r a PM-DrunkenPolice     05-12 0290</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Drunken Police,0301</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Alcohol Training Session Embarrasses Department</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAWRENCE, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A police department training session to
demonstrate the effects of alcohol went sour because of
insufficient supervision, resulting in one participant being
hospitalized after she passed out, the mayor says.
   Mayor Thomas D. Schneider said further disciplinary action is
expected because of the May 2 training session.
   ``Obviously, something went wrong with the way it was done,'' he
added. ``That drinking is supposed to be a controlled situation,
not getting sloppy, falling-down drunk.''
   The program was intended to educate 15 volunteer reserve
officers about effects of alcohol.
   Police Chief Robert A. Jones said three dispatchers and two
police officers drank alcohol. Reserve officers then observed their
behavior, gave sobriety tests and used a Breathalizer machine to
measure blood alcohol content.
   One dispatcher passed out and was taken by ambulance to
Community North Hospital, Schneider said Thursday. She was treated
and released.
   Officer Steve York, who is certified to teach the training
sessions, was in charge but Jones said Capt. Lana Robinson, in
charge of training for the department, should have been present.
   ``There was a lack of supervision,'' Jones said.
   Schneider said the incident disappointed him.
   ``What really just irks me to death is that the new reserve
officers have been given the impression this kind of conduct is
acceptable behavior when it is, in fact, totally unacceptable by
this administration,'' Schneider told The Indianapolis News.
   He said a supervisor should be held accountable. ``There is no
question that someone will have to pay.''
   But Jones said he did not blame Robinson for what happened.
   ``We all have to be broad minded enough to know that we are
human and we all make mistakes,'' he said.
</TEXT>
