<FIRST>r i PM-China-USShips     05-12 0306</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-US Ships,0317</SECOND>
<HEAD>China Plays Down Close Encounter Between Gorbachev, U.S. Navy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet officials said today they were not
concerned about the presence of U.S. warships in Shanghai on the
day Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev is to visit China's largest
city.
   ``I don't think we should overestimate the importance'' of the
planned port call by the U.S. Navy during Gorbachev's visit, Soviet
Foreign Ministry spokesman Gennady Gerasimov said.
   At least two warships from the 7th Fleet are to sail into
Shanghai the afternoon of May 18, when Gorbachev is to tour the
city on his final day in China.
   It will be only the second port call by U.S. naval vessels to
Communist China. The first was in 1986, to the Yellow Sea port of
Qingdao.
   Foreign diplomats see the port call as a clear signal by the
Chinese that better relations with the Soviet Union will not
interfere with China's strong ties with the United States.
   China has stressed that Gorbachev's visit, and normalization of
long-strained relations with the Soviet Union, will not affect its
ties with other countries.
   Gorbachev arrives Monday for the first Sino-Soviet summit in 30
years.
   Yevgeny M. Primakov, director of the Institute of World Economic
and International Relations of the Soviet Academy of Sciences, also
denied any relation between the port call and the Gorbachev visit.
   ``There has been no request either from the Soviet leader or
from Chinese leaders to visit the ships at that time,'' he said.
   Primakov and other Soviet speakers at a news conference
emphasized the importance of Sino-Soviet rapprochement.
   ``This is not just another visit in the framework of times, but
of historic necessity,'' Primakov said.
   ``We are two socialist states faced with major challenges. Our
rapprochement will in one way or another make it easier to clarify
our difficulties.''
