<FIRST>r a PM-JamesTrial     05-12 0375</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-James Trial,0385</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Found Guilty Of Killing Infant Son</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who set off a nationwide search when
he claimed his infant son had been kidnapped has been convicted of
murder in the death of the 3-month-old boy.
   A jury deliberated less than four hours Thursday before
convicting Steven Ray James, 37, in the death of Steven Roy James,
whose body was found wrapped in bedding weighted with rocks in the
marshes of the Bear River on Oct. 11, 1986.
   James let out a deep breath when the verdict was read and
proclaimed his innocence to reporters as he was led away. Several
of his relatives ran weeping from the courtroom when the decision
was announced.
   The defense maintained throughout the seven-day trial that the
baby was kidnapped Aug. 16, 1986, from James' car while he shopped.
   ``We thought very strongly that it would be an innocent verdict
on Steven,'' said Roy James Sr., the defendant's father.
   ``We're disappointed,'' said defense attorney Robert Gutke.
   Prosecutors did not comment after the trial.
   James, of Logan, rallied his northern Utah community when he
reported the baby kidnapped. Sixteen-thousand fliers were printed
and mailed by volunteers, the story was sent out with monthly gas
bills in three states and the baby's picture was printed on grocery
bags distributed to 600 stores.
   The jury will return Monday to decide if the crime was first- or
second-degree murder. It is the first time in Utah that a murder
trial has been divided into separate guilt phases.
   The prosecution is not seeking the death penalty and Judge Pat
Brian has agreed to a life imprisonment sentence in the event of a
first-degree murder conviction. Second-degree murder carries a
sentence of five years to life, to be determined by the state Board
of Pardons.
   In closing arguments, Deputy Cache County Attorney James Jenkins
told the jury that James had the motive and opportunity to kill the
baby and planned the slaying to salvage his deteriorating
relationship with the boy's mother, Victoria DeLeon.
   Medical examiners were unable to determine the cause of the
baby's death, and Gutke said the child might have been killed by
kidnappers or died of natural causes and was ``improperly disposed
of.''
</TEXT>
