<FIRST>r a PM-DelinquentTaxChief     05-12 0299</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Delinquent Tax Chief,0306</SECOND>
<HEAD>Revenue Director Behind on Vacation Lot Taxes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state's chief tax collector paid
$192.82 today to clear up a delinquent 1988 tax bill on a vacation
island lot in Florida's Panhandle, a spokesman said.
   ``It was a mixup which she is correcting today,'' said Jere
Moore, spokesman for Katie Tucker, executive director of the state
Revnue Department. ``She owns two lots down on St. George Island.
One is listed in her name and the other is listed in the name of
Dan and Katie Miller. The one in her name is the smaller one and
that's the one she owes the tax (on).''
   Miller, Tucker's husband, is president of the Florida AFL-CIO.
   Moore said she wrote a $1,169 check March 31, thinking it
covered both parcels. Taxes in Florida become delinquent April 1.
   ``Then she got another bill from the tax collector,'' Moore
said. ``She thought it was a mix-up and has been intending to get
in touch with the tax collector down there.''
   Franklin County tax collector Betty W. Sangaree, in office for
more than 20 years, read the owner's name on the delinquent tax
list Thursday.
   ``Katie Tucker,'' she said, pausing. ``Hey, that's my boss.''
   Tucker makes $83,620 annually as Florida's revenue chief. She
heads an agency that collects nearly $1 billion a month in sales,
gasoline and other taxes and supervisor local tax collectors.
   Because of the delinquent tax, Tucker's property has been on a
list of property up for grabs at a tax-deed auction next month.
   Residents can bid on the deeds and earn up to 18 percent
interest on their money until the back taxes are paid. If the taxes
aren't paid within two years, the holder of the tax deed can keep
the property.
</TEXT>
