<FIRST>u i PM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru   05-12 0670</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0555,0686</SECOND>
<HEAD>One Dead, 10 Wounded In Unrest</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 13 grafs to UPDATE with violence; picks up 3rd pvs:
When it...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soldiers shot and killed a Palestinian and
wounded at least 10 others today in clashes in the Israeli-occupied
West Bank and Gaza Strip, Arab reports said.
   The worst confrontation came in the Sheikh Radwan neighborhood
of Gaza City, where troops opened fire on stone-throwing youths,
Arab reports said.
   Mahmoud Awad Akraa, 24, was struck in the head with a bullet and
was dead on arrival at Shifa Hospital, doctors said. Five
Palestinians were injured in the Sheikh Radwan clash, officials at
Gaza City hospitals said.
   In other clashes, two Palestinians were wounded in Shajeih
neighborhood of Gaza City, one in the Rimal neighborhood of Gaza
City, one in the Nusseirat refugee camp, and one in El Bireh near
Ramallah on the West Bank, Arab reports said.
   The army said it was checking the reports.
   Akraa's death raised to at least 472 the number of Palestinians
killed since the Palestinian uprising began in December 1987.
Twenty-one Israelis have died.
   The clashes occurred in Gaza despite a curfew that confined the
strip's nearly 700,000 residents to their homes for a fifth
consecutive day.
   Also today, Israelis continued anti-Arab violence in the coastal
city of Ashdod, the hometown of Sgt. Avi Sassportaz, an Israeli
soldier found slain on May 7. Arab reporters said Israelis stoned
the cars of Palestinians as they passed.
   One Arab driver, Majdi Abu Jama, 21, was treated for a skull
fracture at Shifa Hospital in Gaza City, doctors said. A passenger
also was injured, they said.
   In the West Bank, 23-year-old Abdulla Yamani and a passenger in
his car, 2-year-old Mohammed Masoud, were treated for cuts and
bruises at Tulkarem Hospital. Yamani told doctors that his car was
stoned by soldiers driving by in an army truck near the Tulkarem
refugee camp.
   The army said it had no report of the incident.
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir and his Cabinet plan to meet
Sunday to set up guidelines for elections in the territories.
   Shamir has proposed elections to choose Palestinian
representatives who would negotiate with Israel on a period of
limited autonomy. Talks would follow three years later on a
permanent settlement.
   When it meets on Sunday, the 25-member administration likely
will sidestep controversial issues such as international
supervision and the participation of Palestinians from outside the
territories in the elections.
   ``What we are bringing are the main principles, the skeleton of
the plan, without getting into details,'' said a Shamir aide who
spoke today on condition of anonymity.
   Ministers of Shamir's right-wing Likud bloc are expected to
approve the elections idea Saturday night, Shamir's spokesman,
Yossi Ahimeir, said. ``Maybe one or two will oppose, but the
majority support it,'' he said.
   Among the opponents is Ariel Sharon, the trade and industry
minister who has argued such elections would lead to a Palestinian
state and be a calamity for Israel.
   Ministers of the left-leaning Labor Party in the coalition
government approved the plan Thursday, with only two ministers
stating opposition.
   Once the plan is approved, it is to be conveyed to Dennis Ross,
an aide to Secretary of State James Baker III. Ross arrives
Saturday to meet with prominent Palestinians and brief Israeli
leaders on Baker's talks in Moscow with Soviet Foreign Minister
Eduard Shevardnadze.
   Ross is expected to try to make the election plan more
attractive to Palestinians by urging Israelis to allow
participation of 140,000 east Jerusalem residents _ a concept that
has been opposed by Shamir.
   The Jerusalem Post said that in a letter to Foreign Minister
Moshem Arens 12 days ago, Baker called for Palestinians abroad to
also be allowed to participate.
   The Post said the participation of outside Palestinians is
rejected by Israeli officials who fear it would be tantamount to
involving the Palestine Liberation Organization, which the
government views as a terror group bent on Israel's destruction.
</TEXT>
