<FIRST>r i PM-LostBomb 1stLd-Writethru   05-12 0428</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lost Bomb, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0542,0434</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: Brakes or Distracted Pilot May Have Caused 1965 Accident</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 6th graf, `In Washington...' with one graf to restore Kudla's
first name; picks up 7th graf: Weldon, 44,...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DARMSTADT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. military newspaper today
quoted sailors as saying either brake failure or a distracted pilot
may have caused a U.S. Navy jet with a hydrogen bomb on board to
fall into the sea off Japan 24 yers ago.
   Stars and Stripes interviewed a former crewman of the U.S.
aircraft carrier involved in the Dec. 5, 1965 mishap. Philip G.
Weldon was a petty officer third class on board the carrier, the
Ticonderoga, when the Navy attack jet rolled off the deck about 80
miles from a Japanese island, the paper said.
   The bomb was lost in the sea.
   ``Some sailors on the deck claimed that the pilot, who was
killed in the accident, was reading a book and may have been
distracted,'' Stars and Stripes said. ``Weldon believes other
causes such as brake failure can't be ruled out.''
   Pentagon officials have confirmed the accident but given few
details on the loss of the plane or the 1-megaton bomb, which has a
force of 1 million tons of TNT.
   In Washington, Pentagon duty officer, Lt. Cmdr. Jim Kudla said
he had ``no information at this time'' about the report by the
Darmstadt-based newspaper.
   Weldon, 44, was quoted as saying the accident occurred as
sailors pushed the A-4E plane onto a hanger deck elevator during a
training exercise.
   The pilot had been in the cockpit for about an hour as sailors
loaded the bomb on the plane. Once the bomb was on board, members
of the crew backed the craft into the elevator to raise it to the
flight deck, Stars and Stripes, the unofficial U.S. military
newspaper, said.
   The elevator was open to the ocean and had no barrier at the
back. The pilot was supposed to apply the brakes, but about 50
sailors watched as the jet slipped off the egde, flipped nose-up
and dropped into the water, Weldon said.
   ``It all happened in a matter of seconds,'' the Stars and
Stripes quoted Weldon as saying.
   Weldon, a native of Lebanon, Ore., joined the Navy in 1963. At
the time of the accident he was assigned to the 51st Fighter
Squadron as an electronics technician, the newspaper said.
   Weldon, who now works as a librarian at a U.S. military
Elementary-Junior High School in Goeppingen, West Germany, left the
Navy in 1966, the paper said.
</TEXT>
