<FIRST>r a PM-GreenService 1stLd-Writethru a0507 05-12 0452</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Green Service, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0507,0458</SECOND>
<HEAD>Green Wake Held as Selection Process Starts Up Again</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with morning service, quotes; Picks
up 2nd graf, `City leaders ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ALAN HARPER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 4,000 New Yorkers packed a church
today to say goodbye to Schools Chancellor Richard Green, who died
this week after 14 months of running the nation's largest school
system.
   The memorial service began with a student choir singing ``You've
Got a Friend'' and the church organist playing two of Green's
favorite songs _ ``The Greatest Love of All'' and ``Reach Out and
Touch.''
   ``He inspired a lot of young people with a zest and optimism and
enthusiasm,'' said Manhattan Borough President David Dinkins upon
arrival at the Cathedral of St. John the Divine.
   Serving as honorary pallbearers for Green were the schools
superintendents of Atlanta; Detroit; Chicago; Newark, N.J.;
Memphis, Tenn.; and Tucson, Ariz. The Rev. Paul Moore, Epsicopal
Bishop of New York, and Rev. James Park Morton, dean of the
cathedral, conducted the service.
   On Thursday, hundreds of New Yorkers solemnly walked past
Green's bronze-colored, open casket and paid their respects to the
late schools chancellor. His funeral will be held in Minneapolis.
   City leaders on Thursday stood next to teachers and students
alongside Green's open casket at the Cathedral of St. John the
Divine. Green died early Wednesday after an asthma attack. He was
52.
   A memorial service was scheduled for today in the cathedral. The
funeral will be held later in Minneapolis, where Green spent most
of his life.
   ``I think what he left is the spirit of rejuvenation of our
school system,'' Mayor Edward I. Koch said outside the cathedral.
``He commenced it and someone now will have to pick up his mantle
and carry on.''
   Another mourner was 11-year-old Jason Lewis. He said the news of
Green's death upset many of his classmates at P.S. 51, who were
scheduled to see the chancellor this week to plan a Mother's Day
surprise for their moms.
   ``Everybody was crying. I was crying too,'' said Lewis. ``It was
a tragedy it happened.''
   Green became the first black to head the city's schools in March
1988, after a 4{-month search for a new chancellor. Board of
Education President Robert F. Wagner Jr. suggested Wednesday that
the same search committee that selected Green pick his successor.
   Nathan Quinones, chancellor in 1984-88, said gender and race
should be a key factor in filling the job.
   ``I think the outpouring here is the best example of the effect,
the sense of strength, the model he played as a strong black
male,'' he said of Green.
</TEXT>
