<FIRST>u w PM-IndianInvestigation 1stLd-Writethru a0437 05-12 0733</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Indian Investigation, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0437,720</SECOND>
<HEAD>An Indian Woman Said She Lost Home Because of Lost Oil Royalties</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 9 grafs new; picks up 4th graf, ``Let me ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Cheyenne-Arapaho woman, choking back tears,
told a Senate committee today she lost her home and children
because her royalties from federally managed oil wells stopped
without explanation.
   Mary Limpy, speaking before a special investigating committee of
the Senate Select Committee on Indian Affairs, said she is living
in an abandoned house in Oklahoma City, Okla., and lost custody of
her two youngest children because she could not pay her bills.
   The checks were small, but she used them to support her family,
said Mrs. Limpy, who is disabled from polio and ineligible for
welfare programs as long as she is on the oil royality rolls.
   Her three wells are managed by the Bureau of Indian Affairs, but
when she went to the agency to find out why her checks stopped,
they could not help her, she told the committee.
   Mrs. Limpy is part of a federal class-action lawsuit charging
that the government is not living up to its trust responsibilities
to Indians with oil well interests, said attorney Steve Moore.
   That lawsuit has been held under advisement of the judge for two
and a half years, Moore said.
   On Thursday, Sen. Dennis DeConcini, D-Ariz, chairman of the
special committee announced that the Navajo Indian nation may be
owed as much as $5 million in back taxes from companies that have
purchased oil from its property.
   The committee discovered the tax error during its investigation
of oil theft and royalties underpayment by companies doing business
on Indian land.
   DeConcini said it appears taxes owed the Navajos have been
miscalculated for eight years.
   ``Let me make clear that we have found no evidence that the oil
companies themselves intentionally misstated the amount of taxes
paid, or even that the oil companies were the source of the
possible misinformation,'' DeConcini said.
   He said the committee alerted the tribe and will assist it in
making the correction needed to collect the money and ensure the
problem isn't repeated.
   DeConcini's announcement, which came on the third day of
hearings about Indian oil, hinted at the extent of confusion over
royalty and tax payments.
   ``Accounting errors are rampant in the industry,'' said Randy
Fetterolf, an oil and gas expert working as a consultant to the
committee. Companies are so busy finding, producing and selling oil
that they don't have time to perform the intricate but necessary
accounting procedures, he said.
   Fetterolf called the oil industry a ``boom and bust'' business
and said many companies that failed to pay royalties are now
bankrupt.
   DeConcini and committee member Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., have
been highly critical of the three agencies charged with protecting
Indian oil rights _ the Bureau of Indian Affairs, the Bureau of
Land Management and the Minerals Management Service.
   Chuck Norman, a committee investigator, said Thursday that the
Minerals Management Service was ``a model of efficiency'' compared
to the other two agencies.
   However, he said the service fails to catch improper valuation
of oil and improper deductions that companies make from the
royalties they are supposed to pay.
   Norman said unlike the IRS, the minerals service doesn't have
any built-in signals to alert it to illegal deductions.
   He says companies are allowed to deduct some expenses from
royalties, but evidence exists that the privilege may be abused.
   Furthermore, said Norman, ``there is a very serious problem with
the MMS penalty system.''
   He said in the last seven years, the service imposed 35
penalties on Indian and non-Indian public land, but only collected
five, none of which were on Indian land.
   Norman said that because of a loophole in the law, companies
that fail to pay their penalties escape unscathed.
   Earlier in the day, witnesses from the Southern Ute tribe in
Colorado described how they took over management of their oil wells
because of the federal government's failure to do the job.
   Tom Shipps, attorney for the Southern Utes, told the committee
he didn't trust the minerals service to effectively police royalty
payments. His tribe uses its own accountants to audit oil
transactions.
   Norman praised the work of the Southern Utes.
   ``What needs to be encouraged is more autonomy for the Indians,
like the Southern Utes,'' said Norman.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890512-0108 </DOCNO>
