<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Netherlands-Army     05-12 0145</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Netherlands-Army,0150</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dutch Soldiers Call For Shorter Stint</HEAD>
<DATELINE>THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Dutch soldiers' union on Friday
called for the government to cut the draft time by one-quarter,
citing inefficiency and boredom.
   The government, however, won't consider such a move because of
NATO commitments on military training and personnel strength, said
Defense Ministry spokesman Hans Schonau.
   The draft period for lower ranks could be cut from 14 to 10
months, because at least 25 percent of a conscript's time is
squandered, said union spokesman Frans Vergouwe.
   Concripts make up 49,000 of the Netherlands' 65,000-member armed
forces.
   A union poll of 408 drafted men showed 56 percent thought they
worked inefficiently. Thirty percent said they routinely completed
their day's work in four hours instead of the regulation eight,
Vergouwe said.
   More efficient use of time would allow for shorter army stints,
he said.
</TEXT>
