<FILEID>AP-NR-05-12-89 1227EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-TeacherDinners Bjt   05-12 0745</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Teacher Dinners, Bjt,0767</SECOND>
<HEAD>Businessman Sponsors Dinners To Get Parents Involved in School</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JULIA RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thanks to an invitation to dinner at a restaurant,
construction worker Jaime Polomo got to meet his son's first-grade
teacher and tell her why he had not gone to school for conferences
this year.
   ``I work all day,'' he said. ``At night, I study English.''
   Polomo; his wife, Valentine; their son, Jaime; and teacher Jean
Smith-Andrade had dinner courtesy of local businessman Phil Garvin,
who has sponsored more than 100 such teacher-parent dinners.
   Garvin gave Jose Valdez Elementary School $10,000 from his
television production company, Norac Productions Inc., to encourage
the six first-grade teachers to take their students and the
students' parents out to dinner.
   ``We wanted to start this the first year that kids have homework
so we can set in motion, hopefully for the rest of their lives,
this communication between teachers and parents,'' he said.
   Seven-year-old Jaime said his first-grade classmates all were
talking about these teacher-parent dinners and he was excited.
   Garvin said that enthusiasm and the occasion is what his
investment is all about.
   ``That's it _ if the exciting thing of the year can be a meeting
with the teacher, that's it: Education is important,'' said Garvin.
   The dinners are meant to be ``a special occasion'' that ``sends
a clear message to the parents: ``hey, you can make a difference,'
'' Garvin said.
   Mrs. Polomo, who had met the teacher a few times before, said
the dinner provided ``time to talk. When you go to school, you have
about 15 minutes to talk with the teacher and that's all.''
   Garvin lives in the comfortable suburb of Englewood but does
business a few blocks from the school north of downtown Denver. He
said he wanted to put something back into the poor, largely
Hispanic neighborhood, where teachers say about 60 percent of
first-graders speak Spanish at home.
   Garvin said he was disturbed by news reports in recent years of
a decline in the quality of American public education.
   ``I was reading all these studies that say that the big
difference between a successful school and an unsuccessful school
is parental involvement,'' he said.
   He said his interest in helping education was inspired partly by
the example of New York City businessman Eugene Lang, who pays for
college for students who graduate from the Harlem high school Lang
attended. He said he also was moved by the movie ``Stand and
Deliver,'' about Los Angeles super-teacher Jaime Escalante.
   When Garvin suggested his dinner plan to Valdez officials last
Christmas, his business already had been giving $10,000 a year for
the past three years to nearby North High School to reward good
teaching. Under that program, five teachers receive $2,000 grants
each.
   The dinners generally have drawn rave reviews.
   Some parents said it was the first time they had eaten in a
sit-down restaurant.
   Teacher Josie Garcia, who has 16 students and was able to
arrange 15 dinners, said that at one of her dinners the student's
father worked in the restaurant kitchen and got time off to come
out for the occasion.
   ``We found out how hard the parents work,'' said teacher Amy
Pleasant-Phillips. ``We sort of knew it, but weren't aware quite
how hard they work _ how much of their time is spent paying the
rent.''
   ``It gave us a realistic picture of where the priorities are,''
said Garcia. ``Most parents are very involved with their children,
but it's very hard for them to find time to help them with school.''
   Teachers said they talked to parents at dinner about the
importance of education and ways parents can help their children:
from making sure they have a place to do homework to reading with
them for even 10 minutes a night.
   Said Smith-Andrade: ``We tell them that attitude is an important
part. A parent doesn't need to take much time _ just show they
care.''
   She said many parents in the area are recent immigrants, and
many are dropouts. Such parents tend to be intimidated by teachers
and school authorities.
   ``A restaurant is neutral ground,'' she said.
   For the children, the dinners are events. One child wore an
Easter bonnet, and others talked for days about what they would
wear and what they would order to eat, teachers said.
   When asked what they enjoyed most about the dinner, a group of
five children answered unanimously: ``ice cream.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
