<FIRST>u i PM-DupontPlazaSettlement 2ndLd-Writethru a0514 05-12 0391</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dupont Plaza Settlement, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0514,0401</SECOND>
<HEAD>Precede PHILADELPHIA</HEAD>
<HEAD>Federal Judge Accepts Settlement in San Juan Hotel Fire</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: New thruout with judge accepting settlement. ADDS byline.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JULIO GHIGLIOTTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge today accepted a
reported $100 million settlement of lawsuits stemming from the 1986
Dupont Plaza Hotel fire that killed 97 people on New Year's Eve.
   U.S. District Court Judge Raymond L. Acosta did not disclose the
amount of the settlement but said he was ``generally satisfied''
with it.
   Agreement in the case, involving about 2,300 plaintiffs from
across the country seeking damages from at least 200 defendants,
was reached Tuesday and approved Thursday night by District Judge
Louis C. Bechtle in Philadelphia.
   U.S. Supreme Court Chief Justice William Rehnquist had appointed
Bechtle to head the negotiations. Bechtle was the presiding judge
in a similarly complex case for the 1980 MGM Grand Hotel fire in
Las Vegas that left 84 people dead. The settlement in that case
totalled $200 million.
   An envelope with the settlement was handed to Acosta on
Wednesday.
   Plaintiffs in the case, tried in U.S. District Court in San
Juan, had sought damages of $1.8 billion.
   A former hotel maintenance worker pleaded guilty to setting the
Dupont Plaza fire during a labor dispute at the 22-story hotel,
which was packed with almost 1,000 tourists. About 140 people were
injured.
   The hotel was cited for 25 violations by the Occupational Safety
and Health Administration, including lack of emergency exits from
the casino, where 84 of the victims died.
   Under the agreement signed in Philadelphia, $50 million will be
paid by the insurer, American International Underwriters Corp., and
$35 million by the so-called Dupont-family group of partnerships
and individuals who owned many hotel enterprises, including the
Dupont Plaza. Other insurance carriers will pay the remaining $15
million.
   The settlement halted a complex trial in San Juan that focused
on who owns the hotel and who is liable for damages.
   Acosta said the agreement was ``fully binding on all parties''
but contingent on certain unspecified conditions being met within
60 days. He said the jury will be recalled July 14 to learn whether
those conditions have been met and whether the trial should move on.
   In the meantime, Acosta issued a 60-day stay against all claims
in the case.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
