<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--ChineseBishop     05-12 0164</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Chinese Bishop,0168</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chinese Bishop Who Spent 30 Years in Jail Meets Pope</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Chinese bishop who spent 30 years in jail
for his religious activities met Friday with Pope John Paul II and
said he felt ``full of happiness.''
   Bishop Ignatius Kung said he and the pontiff discussed the Roman
Catholic Church in China, which the bishop said suffered ``many
difficulties.''
   Kung, 88, was released from prison in 1985, reportedly following
an appeal from the Vatican. His political rights were restored in
1988.
   The Vatican appointed Kung bishop of the Shanghai Diocese in
1950. He was arrested in 1955 on treason charges and sentenced to
life in prison for leading ``a counterrevolutionary clique under
the cloak of religion.''
   China severed relations with the Vatican in 1957 and allows
worship only under the Chinese Patriotic Catholic Church, which
consecrates its own bishops. The church claims more than 3 million
members.
   Many other Catholics secretly remain loyal to the pope.
</TEXT>
