<FIRST>u w PM-Bush-North 2ndLd-Writethru a0580 05-12 0859</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-North, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0580,850</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cranston Attacks Bush's Ambassadorial Candidate for Contra Supplies</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs after 2nd graf with Gregg reacting in testimony;
SUBS 15th graf to remove now-redundant reference to Rodriguez</HEAD>
<BYLINE> By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Alan Cranston accused
Ambassador-designate Donald Gregg today of deliberately misleading
Congress and perhaps lying under oath about his involvement in the
illegal resupply of the Contra rebels while serving as intelligence
chief to then-Vice President George Bush.
   Leveling a barrage of accusations against Gregg, Cranston,
D-Calif., said an intensive investigation and an examination of
documents submitted during the trial of Oliver L. North leads him
to believe that Gregg sponsored ``a free-lance covert operation out
of the vice president's office'' to illegally resupply the Contras
in their fight against the leftist government in Nicaragua.
   Gregg said Cranston's characterization, based on Gregg's
friendship with former CIA operative Felix Rodriguez, was
inaccurate.
   ``I think it is a rather full-blown example of a conspiracy
theory,'' Gregg said of Cranston's comments. ``That's not what I
was doing. It is not what Felix was doing to my knowledge. My job
was to keep the vice president informed. I did not have operational
responsibility for anything. ... To do that would have been the
quickest way for me to lose my job.''
   Gregg said Bush ``made it clear'' that Gregg's job was ``sitting
and listening and reporting.'' He said he did not learn until
August 1986 that Rodriguez was involved in assisting the Contra
military resupply operation and that he didn't learn until December
1986 that North had recruited Rodriguez in September 1985 to assist
that effort. Gregg said he thought Rodriguez' efforts were focused
on assisting the Salvadoran military combat guerrillas.
   Cranston told the Senate Foreign Relations Committee that the
investigation has raised so many questions about Gregg's
credibility and truthfulness that many senators believe he is not
qualified to become U.S. ambassador to South Korea, the post to
which President Bush has nominated him.
   North, during his trial, contradicted the sworn testimony of
Gregg, who says he didn't find out until August 1986 that North was
assisting the Contras.
   Cranston asked why senators, ``who it appears that you have
systematically misled, should now be asked to reward your actions
and entrust you with the position of ambassador of the United
States?''
   Cranston said that he asked Secretary of State James A. Baker
III weeks ago to withdraw the Gregg nomination so an airing of
allegations against the nominee would not be necessary.
   ``Since this nomination is now before us we must now endeavor to
make clear whether you, Mr. Gregg, have played any part in
deliberate efforts to deceive the Congress,'' Cranston said.
   In his lengthy opening statement, Cranston said he is now
prepared to expand the investigation to include Gregg's other
activities while working as a national security adviser in Bush's
vice presidential office.
   He said these include Gregg's activities relating to Honduras,
Panama and the secret U.S. arms sales to Iran.
   ``If we are obliged to, we will explore all of these, and
consider calling other witnesses to obtain sworn evidence,''
Cranston said.
   Gregg, in a 21-page prepared opening statement, made no
reference to any of the issues raised by Cranston and spoke only
about U.S. relations with South Korea.
   Cranston challenged Gregg's previous congressional testimony
that prior to the revelation of the secret arms sales to Iran and
the diversion of a portion of the profits to the Contras in
Nicaragua in November 1986, ``you and the vice president `had never
discussed the Contras. We had no responsibility for it. We had no
expertise in it.'''
   He said Gregg, a 30-year veteran of the Central Intelligence
Agency, had also told a U.S. District Court that he ``had no
respoonsibility'' to Bush for Central American issues.
   ``Yet, the committee is now in receipt of memos under your name
which indicate that your involvement in the promotion of Central
American activities did not, in fact, end when you joined the vice
president's staff,'' Cranston said.
   
   Four months after joining the Bush staff, Cranston said Gregg
gave ``enthusiastic written support'' for a 1982 proposal by
Rodriguez ``to conduct helicopter strikes against a wide range of
Central American targets.''
   On Sept. 19, 1984, Cranston said, Gregg wrote a memo briefing
Bush on sources of Contra resupply.
   In April 1986, he said, Gregg wrote a memo setting up a meeting
for Rodriguez to brief Bush on ``the status of the war in El
Salvador and resupply of the Contras.''
   Cranston noted that 18 months earlier the Boland amendment
barring certain U.S. personnel from any involvement in military
resupply of the Contras had gone into effect.
   Cranston ticked off memo after memo, all of which he said
indicate Gregg played a far greater role in Central American
activities than he has publicly acknowledged.
   ``We could go on to explore the other glaring contradictions in
your sworn testimony _ and we will,'' Cranston said.
   ``But at a certain point your repeated denials and professions
of ignorance take upon themselves a certain `the dog ate my
homework' refrain,'' the senator said.
</TEXT>
