<FIRST>r a AM-AirlineBias     05-12 0322</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Airline Bias,0329</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man in Wheelchair Sues Airlines, Airport</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An executive with the Easter Seal Society,
who says he was barred from a commuter flight because of his
battery-powered wheelchair, is suing the airlines involved and
Tampa International Airport.
   Dennis J. Celorie, chief executive officer for the
Sarasota-based Easter Seal Society of Southwest Florida, filed the
$2 million lawsuit Thursday naming Delta Air Lines and its feeder
line ComAir Inc.
   He claims ComAir wouldn't let him board a March 17 flight to
Tallahassee because it was against airline policy to transport
battery-powered wheelchairs. He was on his way to a state Labor
Department advisory committee meeting.
   Celorie, 50, has cerebral palsy and has used a powered
wheelchair since college. Airlines used to worry that battery acid
might spill onto luggage, he said, but new chairs use sealed, gel
batteries designed for air travel and approved by federal
regulators.
   His travel agency told ComAir about the wheelchair when
reservations were made two weeks in advance, he said. But when
Celorie tried to board, an attendant refused to let him on the
19-seater, according to the lawsuit.
   Celorie is seeking more than $1 million in compensatory damages,
saying the incident hurt his sensibilities and left him with
``feelings of powerlessness and exclusion.'' He also wants $1
million in punitive damages and an injunction prohibiting the
airlines from banning passengers with similar wheelchairs.
   Officials at ComAir's headquarters in Cincinnati, Ohio, said
they were not aware of the suit and could not comment. Delta
spokeswoman Jackie Pate said the carrier did nothing wrong in the
incident.
   Delta owns 20 percent of ComAir, one of a number of commuter
airlines that coordinates schedules with Delta to provide air
service to smaller cities.
   Celorie sued the airport because it leases space and landing
rights to the two airlines. ``I really didn't want to sue,''
Celorie said. ``I just wanted to change the policy.''
</TEXT>
