<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     05-12 0399</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0414</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The bailiff entered the quiet courtroom, ushered
in the jury, then burst into song.
   ``From bias free of every kind, this trial must be tried,'' sang
the bailiff.
   Singing lawyers rhapsodized and harmonized before a singing
judge in a Chicago courtroom in presentations of Gilbert and
Sullivan's operetta ``Trial by Jury'' on Wednesday and Thursday.
   ``Litigation is just like acting,'' said Scott Cooper, a trial
lawyer who played the judge in the Chicago Bar Association
Orchestra production.
   ``A lot of times we get a song and dance in the courtroom,'' he
added.
   Jim Guthrie, the stage director, said lawyers can be trying as
performers.
   ``They're used to being in charge,'' he said. ``They listen,
they take notes very well, and if you make a mistake, they're there
to tell you.''
   The operetta, about a woman who accuses a man of breaking his
promise to marry her, drew a packed courtroom.
   Unlike a regular court session, the spectators were allowed
outbursts of applause. And unlike a regular operetta, the cast
could not tear down the set after the last performance _ under
penalty of law.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>GAITHERSBURG, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Psychic consultant Karen Herbst has
traded in her crystal ball and tarot cards for a computer and a fax
machine to predict her clients' futures.
   Herbst has created a computer program that she said is superior
to the old ways because it removes the psychic's personal views and
prejudices from the process. The only information required for a
$12 to $50 reading is the subject's time, date and place of birth.
   ``When you go to a psychic or an astrologer, their view of the
situation is filtered by who they are. Starfax is not as biased,''
Herbst said.
   Herbst runs the month-old Starfax service from the basement of
her home. She says she computes 15 to 20 readings a day and uses
her facsimile machine to receive requests and transmit forecasts by
phone line to anyone with a similar machine.
   ``I just wanted some information regarding my girlfriend,'' a
recent fax request by a financial analyst read. ``Her birthday is
December 31, 1960. Can you tell me if she's in the mood for love?''
   ``Sherri is not in the mood for love,'' Herbst advised after
checking with her computer. ``Buy her flowers and be patient until
the first week of May.''
</TEXT>
