<FIRST>r a AM-PotLuck     05-12 0302</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pot Luck,0309</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Allows Marijuana Bust On Burglar Search</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dudley Haines' first mistake, leaving
his door ajar when he went fishing, was spotted by a neighbor who
told police there might be a burglar inside. His second, police
allege, was growing marijuana in his closet.
   A state appeal court ruled Thursday that prosecutors can use
those plants in a drug possession case against Haines. The panel
overruled a lower court.
   ``The closet was sufficiently large to have provided a hiding
place for a possible burglar,'' wrote Winifred Sharp, chief judge
of the 5th District Court of Appeal. ``The fact that the police
discovered cannabis in plain view in a place they were entitled to
search for an intruder was bad luck for Haines, but it does not
invalidate their search and discovery.''
   Haines, 26, a supermarket produce clerk who now again faces a
felony drug charge, went fishing on March 5, 1988.
   Lawrence Moore, Haines' neighbor, noticed the open door at 8
p.m. and, seeing no light on, called police to report a possible
burglary, according to court documents.
   ``I don't think he had anything bad in mind,'' Haines said of
Moore. ``He was just looking out for my interests, in his own way.''
   Police said that when they pulled aside a curtain in the hall,
they discovered a closet containing a plant light and a terrarium
holding six marijuana plants.
   Haines was arrested as soon as he came back from his fishing
trip. He said the plants were for his personal use, not
distribution.
   Authorities said the charge against Haines _ possession of more
than 20 grams of cannabis _ is punishable by as much as five years
in prison, but that since he has no prior convictions a jail
sentence would be unlikely.
</TEXT>
