<FILEID>AP-NR-05-12-89 1435EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Bangladesh     05-12 0450</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bangladesh,0462</SECOND>
<HEAD>Drought Toll 160 in Two Weeks, Reports Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FARID HOSSAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 160 people have died in the
past two weeks from dehydration, diarrhea and other effects of a
deadly drought, newspapers reported Friday.
   Temperatures hovered at 102 on Friday and the Health Ministry
warned that citizens should drink more water and mix it with salt
to fend off dehydration. It also cautioned against drinking unsafe
water, the cause of the diarrhea outbreak.
   The government has given no statistics for drought-related
deaths. But the state-owned Bangladesh Times said 100 people in the
northern drought-hit regions had died of diarrhea in the past two
weeks. It quoted local health officials as recording 3,000 cases of
people seeking treatment for diarrhea.
   The newspaper Banglar Bani said 45 people died from the heat in
the Rajshahi, Rangpur and Nilphamari districts of northwestern
Bangladesh in the past 10 days. It said 15 others died in the
neighboring Bogra, Padma and Dinajpur districts.
   The Bengali-language daily said crops had withered, ponds and
lakes had dried up, and there was not enough groundwater to operate
pumps.
   Other newspapers put the heat wave death toll at 30 for the last
10 days. A privately owned news agency, United News of Bangladesh,
said 20 people died from heat in the last week.
   Government officials, speaking on condition of anonymity,
declined to confirm or deny the death tolls. They said people had
died but they were unable to give numbers because of the remoteness
of the regions.
   The Education Ministry ordered all schools in the 16 of the
country's 64 districts to close until the summer monsoon rains
arrive to ease the three-month drought.
   Earlier this week, temperatures reached 107. The government's
weather office said there appeared to be no chance of rain for at
least a week.
   Bangladesh, one of the world's poorest countries with a per
capita income of only $160 a year, alternates between devastating
drought and innundating floods, as well as being buffeted by
cyclones and tornadoes.
   Last summer, more than 1,400 died when monsoon-swollen rivers
flooded four-fifths of the nation. Another 1,100 died in cyclones
in November.
   Late last month, President Hussain Muhammad Ershad led
nationwide prayers for rain to ease the current drought for his 110
million countrymen and women. The following day rains came,
accompanied by tornadoes that killed more than 1,100 people and
left 130,000 homeless.
   The current drought threatens to destroy at least 50 percent of
the spring grain crops now in the ground. The government had
counted on the the spring harvest to yield 5.6 million tons of rice
and wheat, about one-fourth of the country's annual needs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
