<FIRST>r w AM-SovietInspection     05-12 0222</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet Inspection,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>Monitoring Teams Arriving for Short-Notice Inspections</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Soviet monitoring teams planned to arrive
in San Francisco for short-notice inspections under the
intermediate-range nuclear treaty, U.S. officials announced Friday.
   The teams, each consisting of about 10 Soviets, were scheduled
to arrive at Travis Air Force Base, and are to inform U.S.
authorities on Saturday which of five sites they intend to inspect,
said Lt. Col. Joe Wagovich, a spokesman for the On-Site Inspection
Agency.
   Possible sites they might visit are Pueblo Depot Activity,
Pueblo, Colo.; Dugway Proving Grounds, Dugway, Utah; Davis-Monthan
Air Force Base, Tucson, Ariz.; Fort Huachuca, Sierra Vista, Ariz.;
and Air Force Plant 19, San Diego.
   Also aboard the Soviet aircraft was a team to replace the
permanent group stationed at Magna, Utah, to monitor Hercules Plant
No. 1, formerly associated with the production of Pershing-2
missiles, one of the American weapons being destroyed under the
treaty.
   Under the treaty, which requires the superpowers to destroy all
nuclear missiles with ranges of 300 to 3,000 miles, each side can
make 20 short-notice inspections of sites associated with the
weapons during a 12-month period.
   With the completion of the current inspections, the Soviets will
have made 19 such visits, one short of their limit during the
12-month period that ends this month, said the spokesman.
</TEXT>
