<HEAD>Customs Officers Charged With Taking Bribes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thirty-three customs officers at Taiwan's
Chiang Kai-shek International airport were indicted for taking
$500,000 in bribes to expedite imports of fish, fruits and other
goods, a district court reported Friday.
   Eight customs brokers and three businessmen also were charged
with offering bribes, according to the Taoyuan District Court.
   The customs officers were arrested in March following reports of
corruption that dated back to 1985.
   About one-quarter of the airport's 410 customs officers went on
a three-day strike last month to protest extra work resulting from
a staff shortage after the arrests.
   If convicted, they face up to seven years in prison.
