<FIRST>r i AM-China-Soviet     05-12 0315</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Soviet,0327</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gorbachev And 7th Fleet: Two Ships Passing In Shanghai</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev will have a
close encounter with the U.S. Navy next week when he makes his
historic visit to China's largest city.
   But Soviet authorities said Friday they were not worried that
Gorbachev is to visit Shanghai on the same day U.S. warships are to
pay a port call.
   ``I don't think we should overestimate the importance'' of the
port call, Soviet Foreign Ministry spokesman Gennady Gerasimov said.
   At least two warships from the U.S. 7th Fleet will sail into
Shanghai on Thursday, when Gorbachev will be touring the city on
his final day in China.
   It is only the second port call by Navy vessels to communist
China. The first was in 1986 to the Yellow Sea port of Qingdao.
   Foreign diplomats see the port call as a clear signal by the
Chinese that better relations with the Soviet Union won't interfere
with China's strong ties with the United States.
   China has stressed that Gorbachev's visit, and normalization of
long-strained relations with the Soviet Union, won't affect its
relations with other countries.
   Gorbachev arrives Monday for the first Sino-Soviet summit in 30
years.
   Yevgeny M. Primakov, director of the Institute of World Economic
and International Relations of the Soviet Academy of Sciences, also
denied any relation between the port call and the Gorbachev visit.
   ``There has been no request either from the Soviet leader or
from Chinese leaders to visit the ships at that time,'' he said.
   Primakov and other Soviet speakers at a news conference
emphasized the importance of Sino-Soviet rapprochement.
   ``This is not just another visit in the framework of times, but
of historic necessity,'' Primakov said.
   ``We are two socialist states faced with major challenges. Our
rapprochement will in one way or another make it easier to clarify
our difficulties.''
</TEXT>
