<FIRST>u i PM-WHO 2ndLd-Writethru   05-12 0523</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-WHO, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0572,0536</SECOND>
<HEAD>WHO Assembly Votes Against Accepting PLO</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Leads with 9 grafs to UPDATE on delegates opposition measure
to grant immediate acceptance to PLO. Pickup 9th pvs, `The PLO's...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HANNS NEUERBOURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Delegates of the World Health Organization today
voted against a measure that would have granted immediate
membership in WHO to the Palestine Liberation Organization.
   In a secret ballot, the WHO annual assembly voted 80-49 against
the Nicaraguan proposal. There were 19 abstentions.
   Another proposal to defer the question of PLO admission until
next year has yet to be voted on. WHO's chief urged delegates to
support that measure, saying to do otherwise would jeopardize WHO's
future.
   The United States has threatened to withdraw funding for WHO if
the Palestinian state declared in November is allowed to become the
organization's 167th member state.
   In Paris, a PLO spokesman said the Palestinian group is prepared
to finance WHO's Africa operations if the United States carries
through on its threat.
   A compromise proposal by nine Western and Third World countries
calls for deferring the PLO application until next year while
calling for more aid to go to residents of the Israeli-occupied
territories.
   WHO Director-General Hiroshi Nakajima, who has urged PLO
Chairman Yasser Arafat to put off his application, called on the
assembly ``not to jeopardize the future of our organization'' and
to agree to the compromise.
   ``That future is in your hands,'' he told the more than 1,000
delegates.
   Nicaragua then submitted what it termed ``amendments'' to the
compromise proposal. Those amendments were tantamount to an Arab
draft resolution calling on the assembly to admit the state of
Palestine immediately. They failed in the secret ballot.
   The PLO's parliament-in-exile, the Palestine National Council,
declared the independent state in November. The PLO, which has
non-voting status in the U.N. system, is attempting to join all of
the major U.N. agencies as a full member.
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III has said admitting the PLO
would harm the Middle East peace process and the entire U.N.
system. The United States and its Western allies say the nation
proclaimed by the PLO does not fulfill internationally accepted
criteria of statehood, including control of a defined territory and
a capital.
   The United States has contributed $94 million to WHO's regular
budget and special programs to fight specific diseases.
   WHO plays a vital role in assisting governments worldwide to
strengthen their health services and advance work to eradicate
diseases, such as AIDS, and to promote health care and nutrition.
   In an apparent bid to woo Third World countries to the PLO's
side, PLO spokesman Omar Massalha said in Paris the organization
would take over funding of African programs in the event of a U.S.
withdrawal of aid.
   ``The PLO has already put together necessary funding for
financing the programs and activities of the WHO in Africa in the
event that the United States should suspend its financial
contribution following the admission of the state of Palestine as a
member state of WHO,'' Massalha said.
   Massalha said the money had been raised from several Arab and
non-aligned countries.
</TEXT>
