<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Corpse     05-12 0168</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Corpse,0173</SECOND>
<HEAD>Qantas Loses Body Among Vegetable Cargo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SYDNEY, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Qantas Airways said Friday it lost
track of a body bound for burial in Fiji that instead went around
the South Pacific with a cargo of vegetables.
   The airline said the family of Jag Mohan Singh, an immigrant who
died in April, had arranged to ship home his body for a funeral.
   But the airline said it inadvertently flew the body to Tahiti
and Los Angeles then back to Australia over three days before
discovering the error.
   The body finally was delivered to the family 36 hours after the
scheduled funeral. More than 1,500 people turned up for the funeral
in Suva only to be told the body had not arrived.
   The coffin was placed aboard a Qantas flight April 13 but was
stacked beneath cartons of vegetables, and airport workers at Nadi,
Fiji, were unable to find it.
   ``They treated my father like a sack of vegetables,'' said
Hamendra Singh, the dead man's son.
</TEXT>
