<FIRST>u a PM-SecondAbduction 1stLd-Writethru a0633 05-12 0367</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Second Abduction, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0633,0371</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Mother Charged In 1986 Death Of Newborn</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with background on case, recasts lede; ADDS
byline; No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL DE LA GARZA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERSEYVILLE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who claimed her two young
daughters were abducted by masked gunmen in similar circumstances
three years apart was charged today with concealing a homicide and
obstruction of justice in the death of the first child.
   The charges against Paula Sims, 29, were filed 13 days after she
reported that her second daughter, 6-week-old Heather Lee, had been
abducted by a masked gunman. Heather was found dead May 3.
   Jersey County State's Attorney Richard J. Ringhausen signed a
criminal complaint alleging one count of concealing a homicide and
three counts of obstructing justice in the 1986 death of 13-day-old
Loralei Sims, said Linda Long, chief deputy court clerk.
   An arrest warrant was issued and Mrs. Sims was expected to
surrender today. Jersey County Circuit Judge Claude Davis set bond
at $100,000, Ms. Long said.
   Mrs. Sims and her husband, Robert, of Alton, have denied any
wrongdoing through their attorney, Donald Groshong.
   Police say Sims told them he believes Mrs. Sims may have killed
their daughters accidentally.
   The Simses told police Heather Lee was abducted by a masked
gunman April 29. Heather's body was recovered in a trash barrel on
the Missouri side of the Mississippi River four days later. An
autopsy showed the infant had been smothered by someone putting a
hand over her mouth. Tests also indicated that the body had been
frozen before it was placed in the trash can.
   On June, 17, 1986, the Simses gave police a nearly identical
account in the disappearance of their firstborn daughter, Loralei.
   The decomposed remains of a baby, believed to be Loralei, were
found several days later near the couple's home in Brighton, where
they were living at the time. Brighton is about 10 miles from Alton.
   The Simses refused to answer questions before the grand jury
that investigated Loralei's death and the panel took no action.
   The family buried Heather on Wednesday next to the unmarked
grave containing remains believed to be Loralei's.
</TEXT>
