<DOCNO> AP890512-0140 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-12-89 1542EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Berlin-Airlift     05-12 0258</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Berlin-Airlift,0266</SECOND>
<HEAD>Berliners Mark 40th Anniversary of End of Soviet Blockade</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West Berliners on Friday paid their respects to
the U.S. and British pilots who were killed during the Allied
airlift that sustained the city during an 11-month Soviet blockade
40 years ago.
   The Soviets lifted the blockade on May 12, 1949, after failing
in their quest to bring the Western sector under their control.
   The Berlin Airlift was ordered by American military governor
Lucius D. Clay on June 24, 1948, _ the same day the Soviets imposed
their blockade.
   The Allies flew 1.8 million tons of food and fuel to the Western
enclave surrounded by Communist territory, making more than 277,000
flights.
   To mark the 40th anniversary of the end of the blockade, West
Berliners joined politicians in honoring those who died in the
Allied effort.
   Dozens of wreaths were placed at the Airlift Memorial at
Tempelhof airport. The memorial was built in honor of the 39
British and 31 American airmen and eight German ground personnel
who died in plane crashes during the airlift.
   The U.S. ambassador to West Germany, Vernon A. Walters, renewed
his country's pledge to guarantee the freedom of West Berlin.
   West Berlin Mayor Walter Momper expressed the gratitude of the
city's resident to the Allies. He said the airlift turned the
occupation powers into ``protectors and partners of the city.''
   Another ceremony was held at the Reuter power plant. The Allies
flew most of the parts needed to build the plant after the Soviets
cut off power supplies.
</TEXT>
