<FILEID>AP-NR-05-12-89 1440EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-TrainAccident 5thLd-Writethru a0620 05-12 0681</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Train Accident, 5th Ld - Writethru, a0620,0694</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Freight Train Derails, Hits Houses; 3 Dead, At Least 10 Injured</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to UPDATE with 3 confirmed dead, including
2 children; 10 injured, new quote from witness; Picks up 10th graf, `Four
adults ...'; SUBS 15th graf, `The train ...' to tighten; ADDS byline.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT JABLON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN BERNARDINO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A speeding freight train jumped
its tracks and smashed into a row of houses today, killing at least
three people and injuring at least 10, city officials and witnesses
said.
   The dead were believed to be the train's engineer and two boys
whose home was hit by the train, said mayor's spokesman Gregory
Garcia. At least one person was missing and rescuers searched the
wreckage for others.
   The 69-car Southern Pacific freight, which witnesses said was
traveling at high speed off the grade from the Cajon Pass, derailed
at 7:41 a.m. It toppled off an embankment and into a neighborhood
of modest two- and three-bedroom homes on the outskirts of the
city. It was not immediately known how fast the train was traveling.
   ``The engine came off the track and went through a house,'' said
Dane Maloney, who saw the crash on his way to work.
   ``It was terrible, there were train cars on top of houses, train
cars on top of cars. It sounded like a couple of bombs going off.''
   Reports of the number of cars and houses involved varied as
authorities tried to help the injured and assess the damage
inflicted by the train, flying dirt and rocks from the roadbed.
   Garcia said 55 cars left the tracks, and that none of them were
carrying toxic material. The train carried potash, a compound used
to make fertilizer and soap. It had the consistency of sand.
   Twelve homes were damaged and two of them were destroyed, Garcia
said. Four of the homes were buried under freight cars.
   ``It was going down from Cajon real fast, didn't have no brakes.
I looked over, part of the train was in the air. It just fell back
on the ground and all the sand started flying up in the air and
stuff,'' said Kelly Michaels, a little boy who saw the wreck.
   In addition to the three confirmed dead, at least 10 people were
injured, Garcia said, adding that most of the injuries were minor.
   Four adults and one child with only minor bruises, abrasions and
lacerations apparent were treated at San Bernardino Community
Hospital, said Dr. Frank Letson. ``Their homes were involved,'' he
said.
   A train engineer and one resident were in fair condition at St.
Bernardine's Medical Center. They had cuts and abrasions and were
being X-rayed for other possible injuries, said spokeswoman Tony
Callicott.
   The resident ``was a homeowner whose home collapsed. He was not
in it, fortunately,'' Ms. Callicott said.
   The train was carrying potash from the high-desert town of
Mojave to Long Beach, said Southern Pacific spokesman Jerry Pera.
He said he was unable to confirm some witnesses' reports that the
train was traveling at high speed. The cause of the crash wasn't
immediately known.
   Tracks were expected to remain closed at least a day, forcing
detour of 15 freights and two passenger trains a day, Pera said.
   Radio reporter Don Booth said he saw several victims, apparently
dead, and several others injured.
   ``It's just splintered rubble everywhere,'' said Booth, of
station KRSO in San Bernardino. ``The police are pulling bodies
from the wreckage. Cars are scattered all over the neighborhood.
The locomotive is buried in sand.''
   Booth counted seven houses destroyed, and said sand and gravel
were strewn throughout the neighborhood. Scores of residents milled
around the demolished homes, watching rescuers search for their
friends and neighbors.
   Southern Pacific spokesman Jim Loveland confirmed ``a major
derailment'' but couldn't immediately provide details on the
accident.
   The accident site is about 60 miles east of Los Angeles near the
foothills south of 4,190-foot Cajon Pass, the major road and rail
conduit from the Los Angeles basin to Las Vegas.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
