<FIRST>r a AM-Green-Ambulance     05-12 0276</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Green-Ambulance,0283</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ambulance Reached New York Schools Chancellor in 13 Minutes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The city ambulance service took 13 minutes _
three more than its goal _ to respond to the home of schools
Chancellor Richard Green as he lay dying of an asthma attack,
officials said Friday.
   Sixty to 90 seconds were consumed by the dispatcher completing
an earlier call, and another 60 to 90 seconds were used when the
dispatcher tried to summon a private ambulance that turned out to
be out of service, they said.
   The private ambulance's operator, Lenox Hill Hospital, had
failed to notify the Emergency Medical Service the ambulance was
not available, said Lynn Schulman, an EMS spokeswoman.
   The city complained to Lenox Hill of that oversight in a letter
Thursday. A Lenox Hill spokeswoman said it would respond sometime
Friday.
   EMS was called to Green's home at 1:41 a.m. Wednesday and sent
an ambulance five minutes later. Schulman said two minutes, ``maybe
three,'' was the norm for dispatch. Still, the overall 13-minute
response time was ``within the range'' of the EMS goal of 10
minutes or less for top-priority calls, she said.
   ``We're not talking about something that took a half-hour or an
hour,'' Schulman said. ``It's not a terrific response time, but
it's not anything that there should be a lot of concern about.''
   She said it was impossible to say whether a faster response
could have saved Green.
   Last week, 57 percent of priority ambulance calls were handled
by the EMS in under 10 minutes, and the average response time was
10 minutes and 23 seconds, about a half-minute over the goal,
Schulman said.
</TEXT>
