<FIRST>r a AM-VetFraud     05-12 0299</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Vet Fraud,0305</SECOND>
<HEAD>Authorities: `Forgotten Man' Buyers Forgotten by Flimflam Man</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOCA RATON, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fugitive captured at the polo club in
this coastal city cashed in on national concern for Vietnam
veterans by offering $100 ``Forgotten Man'' medallions, authorities
say.
   Michael J. Crosby persuaded 6,000 people, including many
veterans, to buy $100 silver medallions, but only 400 people
received them, said Assistant U.S. Attorney Joan Lancaster of
Minneapolis.
   He also misled famed former test pilot Chuck Yeager to get him
to make a videotape promoting a veterans memorial park supposedly
benefited by the medallion sales, prosecutors say.
   Crosby, 42, was arrested Thursday by the FBI at his home at the
Polo Club of Boca Raton. He was ordered held without bail until he
can be returned to Minneapolis, where he faces a prison sentence of
160 years from a November conviction on mail fraud charges.
   ``I think he exploited the feelings of people that Vietnam vets
were not given a fair shake,'' said Lancaster. ``Through
exploitation, he induced people to make an investment they
otherwise would be prevented, through common sense, to make.''
   An FBI agent in San Diego said Crosby is wanted there on charges
of bilking an 88-year-old woman out of $50,000 in bank stocks.
   Crosby's company, ``Vets for Vets,'' used a testimonial from
Yeager to help solicit investors in a plan to build a memorial park
near Mount Rushmore in the Black Hills of South Dakota, Lancaster
said. But Crosby reneged on a $90,000 land contract, and the park
was not built.
   Yeager, the first man to fly faster than sound, testified on
Oct. 19 that he had not signed a contract permitting Crosby to use
the videotape. Yeager said he had hoped to check out Crosby's
company before granting such permission.
</TEXT>
