<FIRST>r i AM-SouthAfrica     05-12 0547</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-South Africa,0562</SECOND>
<HEAD>De Klerk Calls for Quick and Drastic Change</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURINDA KEYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   National Party leader F.W. de
Klerk, expected to become South Africa's next president, called
Friday for a new political system free from domination by the white
minority or black majority.
   De Klerk said the racially segregated system ``will have to
change drastically and quickly,'' but his speech before Parliament
dealt more with policies he rejects than details of the type of
government he proposes.
   He said the governing party wanted decisions by consensus,
dismissing the continued white rule supported by the Conservative
Party and calling a one-person, one-vote system favored by the
anti-apartheid Democratic Party ``totally unacceptable.''
   ``A mere majority decision would be domination, and failure to
reach consensus should be settled by a fair referee,'' he said
without elaboratation.
   De Klerk, 53, became party leader when the post was vacated by
President P.W. Botha, who suffered a stroke in January. Botha, head
of government since 1978, plans to retire after an election on
Sept. 6, and de Klerk, the education minister, is virtually assured
of succeeding him.
   De Klerk's speech in Cape Town came a day after Constitutional
Development Minister Chris Heunis announced his resignation. Last
week, Heunis attracted wide publicity with a speech suggesting that
blacks be given a role in Parliament, in the Cabinet and in the
selection of a president.
   De Klerk called Heunis' speech ``exploratory,'' and said, ``to
deduce from his speech that the National Party is now following ...
the way to majority rule is untrue.''
   Parliament includes subordinate chambers for Asians and people
of mixed-race, but the 28 million blacks have no formal role of any
sort in national politics.
   ``White security can never be built on injustice towards
others,'' de Klerk said. ``White domination, over the greatest
portion of our country, as the Conservative Party calls for, leads
inescapably to catastrophe. And it will be our children
particularly who will pay the price.
   ``The Conservative Party stands for a minority government in a
South Africa that will, by their own admission, in perpetuity be
populated by a majority of people of color. It is unfair and does
not pass the test of justice,'' de Klerk said.
   ``The Democratic Party stands for a majority government. In a
country with such a massive and wide diversity as ours, this is
unfair to the smaller peoples and population groups. Their policy,
too, fails the test of justice.''
   The Conservative Party leader, Andries Treurnicht, charged that
de Klerk's policies would lead to black rule. ``South Africa is at
the end of a failed political experiment, and the National Party
government is in disarray,'' he said.
   Zach de Beer, a co-leader of the Democratic Party, debated de
Klerk on what kind of stand he was taking.
   ``(De Klerk) condemns majority government and condemns minority
government but what form of government does he not condemn? He will
have to get off the fence some time or other.''
   De Klerk then responded, ``I said we will come with a whole new
constitution'' to be placed before voters in a referendum.
   De Beer replied, ``He says he will change the constitution. But
I am begging him to tell us how he will change it.''
</TEXT>
