<DOCNO> AP890512-0151 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-12-89 2032EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-PressFreedom     05-12 0641</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Press Freedom,0664</SECOND>
<HEAD>International Forum On Press Freedom Ends in Disagreement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAGGIE JACKSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 35-nation forum on press freedom ended without a
communique Friday as East bloc hard-liners rejected criticism of
their repressive practices from both East and West.
   Hungary's pledge to pull down ``No Photography'' signs was among
few promises made at the month-long forum to monitor compliance
with a new accord to improve the information flow between communist
and capitalist-minded nations.
   But delegates said the sometimes heated criticism gave hope for
improvements, and the inclusion of journalists added to the
openness of the meeting.
   ``The accomplishment is latent or potential, messages have been
conveyed,'' said Canadian chief delegate William Bauer.
   ``You have to maintain constant pressure and hope in the end
that the fear of being revealed as hypocrites will be greater than
the fear of losing power,'' said Bauer, ambassador to the
Conference on Security and Cooperation in Europe. That conference
ended in January with the signing of an accord on press freedom and
free speech.
   The London Information Forum brought together all the
signatories _ every European nation except Albania, plus Canada and
the United States.
   Romania, the most reluctant signatory, proved the major obstacle
to a final communique although East Germany and Czechoslovakia also
proved unwilling, delegates said.
   Leonard H. Marks, leader of the U.S. delegation and former head
of the U.S. Information Agency, said Romania was ``the odd man
out.''
   Officials from Romania, where typewriter owners have to license
their machines, could not obtain permission to sign a communique
for 48 hours. So more than 60 proposals tabled at the forum had to
be forwarded to the next meeting, in Helsinki in 1992.
   Proposals ranged from an East German-Czechoslovak call to
prevent distribution of neo-Nazi propaganda to a 29-point treatise
signed by members of NATO and the European Economic Community for
the scrapping of a wide range of restrictions on information and
the media.
   Bauer, Marks and others said they did not mind the lack of a
concluding statement because they got what they needed: ``some
forward motion in how these commitments are carried out.''
   Romania, East Germany, Bulgaria and Czechoslovakia _ countries
Bauer said remain ``locked in a dark age of information'' _ drew
the most criticism.
   In an East-East outburst, Hungary charged Romania with breaking
the accord by banning ``an entire editorial staff from Hungarian
television.''
   Czechoslovakia and Bulgaria said such criticism was
counterproductive.
   ``There were instances when some of us were put in a position to
resist the attempts to slide our debate on the worn-out tracks of
confrontation,'' Philip Bokov, Bulgaria's chief delegate, told the
meeting Friday.
   Changes in Hungary, Poland and the Soviet Union were applauded,
although Marks said ``this doesn't mean they've fully satisfied the
regulations.''
   Western governments did not escape unscathed, delegates said,
mostly because of journalists and other non-diplomatic delegates.
   ``They were loose cannon who could fire in any direction they
wished to and they took up their opportunity to do so,'' said Bauer.
   British delegates accused Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher of
curbing press freedom through measures such as a ban on broadcast
interviews with members of the outlawed Irish Republican Army and
its supporters.
   But not all discussions were critical, and signs of change
emerged.
   The Soviet Union promised to let foreigners use profits from the
sale of periodicals there to pay for their in-country expenses in
local currency.
   Several countries, including the United States, promised to
speed up journalists' visa application processes, and cut red tape
governing the import of high-tech equipment.
   Hungary promised to award visas at its borders to journalists
from countries that reciprocate and remove signs banning
photography.
   ``I can only confess that to date these notices have rather
drawn the attention of passers-by than kept away undesirable
scrutiny,'' chief delegate Laszlo Demus admitted.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890512-0152 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-12-89 1536EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-DearShoplifter Bjt   05-12 0636</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dear Shoplifter, Bjt,0650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Retailers Strike Back at Shoplifters With Letters Demanding Restitution</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARLENE LEVINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The father of an 11-year-old girl was irate when a
drugstore chain sent him a letter demanding he fork over $100
because his daughter allegedly swiped an 89-cent tube of lip balm.
   He was successful in fighting the demand, but retailers across
the country are increasingly dispatching similar missives to
shoplifters and their parents, newly armed with state laws giving
stores more power to fight sticky fingers.
   ``The reason it's popular, it acts as a deterrent when the word
gets out: When you steal from the store, you're going to pay for
it,'' Carol Sommer, a founder of Civil Demand Associates in Sherman
Oaks, Calif., said in an interview Friday. The 4-year-old firm has
clients nationwide and is only one of several law firms dedicated
to this new weapon against shoplifting.
   The tactic of recouping shoplifting losses by sending demand
letters to shoplifters or their parents is known in the business as
``civil recovery'' or ``civil restitution.''
   ``It's a boon for getting some money back,'' said Jack Fraser,
operations chief for the New York-based National Retail Merchants
Association, which has 55,000 member stores.
   According to FBI figures gathered from police nationwide for
1987, the latest numbers available, there 1.1 million shoplifting
offenses averaging $96 per item.
   Since Nevada passed the country's first law offering retailers a
civil remedy in 1973, it has been joined by 34 others. The law
takes various forms, but the message is the same: Shoplifters won't
get away with just a red face; they can be hounded until they pay
up.
   Laws governing civil recovery vary widely from state to state.
But in all of them adult shoplifters are held liable for damages
and penalties. In about half the states, stores can go after minors
by making parents responsible for restitution, according to Delany
Stinson, senior investigations coordinator at Dayton Hudson
Department Store Co. in Minneapolis,
   Some states require that police be notified. Others, like
Massachusetts, do not.
   Some states restrict repayment to the value of the item. Others
allow the retailer to tote up the additional costs of crime
prevention, damage to displays or injuries that occurred when the
shoplifter was nabbed and even the cost of putting a new price tag
on the stolen merchandise, Ms. Stinson said.
   Mrs. Sommer of Civil Demand Associates stressed that demand
letters are not intended to generate profits.
   ``This is not a money-making operation,'' Mrs. Sommer said.
``It's meant to be a deterrent. That's really the bottom line.''
   ``Each time somebody gets in trouble, at least 20 people know
about it. The word does get into the community,'' said Lewis
Shealy, head of loss prevention at Marshall Field's and Co.
department stores. For five years the store has been demanding $300
from each shoplifter. Last year it recouped close to $100,000.
   ``That's paying the salary of at least six security guards,''
Shealy said from his Chicago headquarters, which spends about $5
million a year on guards and anti-theft devices.
   The success rate varies from 25 percent recovery to up to 90
percent, loss prevention experts say. The better-heeled the
shoplifter, the easier it is to collect restitution, largely
because they are easier to track down than more transient, lower
income earners.
   The Massachusetts case of the girl and the lip balm was an
instance of the retailer _ the CVS drugstore chain _ going further
than the law allows, the state attorney general said.
   Massachusetts law says parents of youngsters 7 to 17 years old
are only liable for the cost of the item. Adult shoplifters can be
taken to small claims court, where they may be ordered to pay $50
to $500 in damages on top of the item's cost.

</TEXT>
</DOC>
