<HEAD>Jury Convicts Man Alleged of Having Slain Dozens in Three States</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 1st graf to note he could face death penalty, and adds
5 grafs at the end to update with penalty phase of trial, background.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA ANA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Randy Kraft, who authorities said
killed nearly 40 people in three states, was convicted by a jury
today of killing 16 young men in Southern California over 12 years
and could face the death penalty.
   In addition to the slayings in Orange County, authorities have
said Kraft is suspected of killing an additional 21 young men in
California, Oregon and Michigan.
   Jurors also found Kraft, a 44-year-old former Long Beach
computer programmer, guilty of one count of sodomy and one count of
sexual mayhem.
   Kraft sighed loudly as the court clerk began reading the
verdicts, then showed no other emotion during the 30-minute
recitation of guilty verdicts.
   Orange County Superior Court Judge Donald A. McCartin set a
Tuesday hearing to determine a date for the penalty phase of the
trial, during which jurors will hear about the other slayings for
which Kraft is suspected.
   Jurors had been deliberating since April 28 after seven months
of trial that included evidence of necrophilia and mutilation
surrounding the sex-related deaths of young men beginning in 1972.
   When Kraft was arrested, police said they found 47 color
photographs of young men, many of them nude and apparently dead.
   They also found a notebook with more than 60 handwritten
notations which prosecutors have called a ``death list.''
   Kraft was arrested May 14, 1983, when California Highway Patrol
officers pulled him over for erratic driving and discovered a
strangled Marine in the passenger seat of the car.
