<FIRST>u i AM-Canada-US     05-12 0375</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Canada-US,0388</SECOND>
<HEAD>Great Lakes Governors Sign Cooperation Accord With Ontario</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SOLL SUSSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Great Lakes governors agreed Friday to work
together with Ontario to promote their heartland region for
business and tourism.
   ``People talk about the East Coast and the West Coast,'' said
Wisconsin Gov. Tommy Thompson, the new chairman of the Council of
Great Lakes Governors.
   ``But when you talk about what we have in the heartland. This is
a great region. ... We just haven't done enough.''
   Ontario Premier David Peterson said about $83 billion of the
trade between the two countries passes between central Canada and
the eight states making up the council.
   That is about half of the annual trade between the United States
and Canada.
   Besides boosting business, the agreement signed here also calls
for expanding environmental cooperation.
   The six governors on the trip to Canada met Thursday with Prime
Minister Brian Mulroney in Ottawa, where they announced they would
name a staff member to work on partnerships between Canadian and
U.S. business.
   ``As Great Lakes governors, we recognize the importance of
building new bridges of understanding to strengthen and enhance
cooperation,'' said Ohio Gov. Richard Celeste, the council's
outgoing chairman.
   The council is a private, non-partisan organization established
in 1983 and intended to increase cooperation on environmental and
economic issues.
   The governors of Ohio, Michigan, Wisconsin, Minnesota and
Illinois visited both Ottawa and Toronto while New York Gov. Mario
Cuomo went only to Ottawa. The governors of Pennsylvania and
Indiana did not participate in the trip.
   The group was questioned repeatedly during public appearances
about an escalating controversy in Canada over reports that fuel
tainted with polychlorinated biphenyls, or PCBs, and other toxic
substances was exported from the United States.
   Michigan Gov. James Blanchard, speaking to reporters on a boat
tour of Toronto's harbor, said the news was to be taken seriously
but ``it's something that's basically news to us.''
   The governors said regional environmental officials would meet
this summer to discuss the issue.
   Federal Environment Minister Lucien Bouchard announced Friday in
Ottawa that about 125 of the 175 border crossings between Canada
and the United States would be closed to oil tanker trucks so that
the fuel imports can be monitored.
</TEXT>
