<HEAD>U.S., Spain, Italy Agree to Anti-Drug Cooperation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States, Spain and Italy have
agreed to increase their cooperation to thwart drug trafficking, an
Italian Interior Ministry source said Friday.
   The agreement came during a meeting in Madrid between U.S.
Attorney General Dick Thornburgh and officials from Spain's and
Italy's interior ministries, the source said, speaking on condition
of anonymity.
   Thornburgh, FBI Director William S. Sessions and U.S. Drug
Enforcement Administration chief John C. Lawn are attending a
two-day meeting of interior and justice ministers from the
12-nation European Economic Community.
   Thornburgh praised cooperation from Italy and Spain in
combatting drugs, particularly cocaine, brought into southern
Europe from Latin America, the source said.
   Spain and Italy have close historical, cultural and economic
ties with Latin America. U.S. officials hope to capitalize on those
ties in their anti-drug efforts, the source said.
   A meeting among top-level U.S., Spanish and Italian police and
narcotics officials is planned in Madrid next month to discuss
details of cooperation in drug-related matters, the Italian source
said.
