<FIRST>r a AM-USTroops-Panama     05-12 0668</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US Troops-Panama,0685</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Light Fighters' Head To Panama</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Panama, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE GEISSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TRAVIS AIR FORCE BASE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first planes carrying
the Army's elite ``light, silent and deadly'' 7th Infantry Division
from Fort Ord left Friday on non-stop flights to Panama.
   Crews air-lifted howitzers, field cannons, trucks, trailers and
camouflaged soldiers under tight security as similar exercises were
under way with a 726-soldier infantry division at the Army's Fort
Polk, La., and the 165-member 2nd Marine Division at Camp Lejeune,
N.C.
   President Bush ordered on Thursday that the combat troops be
deployed to protect Americans amid Panamanian post-election
violence.
   ``We're the most strategically deployable unit in the army,''
said 7th Division spokesman Maj. L.D. Walker. The self-proclaimed
``masters of the night'' carry mostly small arms, mortars and M-16
automatic rifles on their backs and can be ready for action
anywhere in the world within 18 hours.
   The General Accounting Office has reported that the 7th has been
bogged down by outdated, immobile and inefficient equipment, but
Army spokesman Maj. Phil Soucy disagreed, calling the division
``combat-ready.''
   At dawn, C-5 Galaxy jets began departing from the Travis
airstrip about 35 miles northeast of San Francisco. The Air Force's
largest plane, with seats for 73 soliders on its upper level and a
huge hold below, is capable of carrying 100 tons and has a cruising
speed of 500 mph.
   In addition, the Air Force loaded soliders into C-141
Starlifters in a deployment Lt. Col. Jim Dilda said could continue
into the night. He would not disclose the number of planes flying
to Panama or their exact destinations.
   Chief Warrant Officer Charles Rowe, with the 150 Camp Lejeune
Marines flying out of coastal North Carolina, described the
deployment as ``an open-ended commitment.''
   ``Just showing up will make a statement within itself,'' said
Marine Lance Cpl. James Camp of Peoria, Ill. ``That we're not going
to take any more of what's going on in Central American and those
little countries down there.''
   Most 7th Division soldiers approached by reporters said they
were instructed not to speak to the media. Those who did talk said
they were prepared, that the mission would be a good test of their
training and that they were just doing their jobs.
   ``The U.S. hasn't declared war. We're going down to protect
American citizens. There's not a lot to worry about,'' said Pfc.
Daniel Grabowski of Cleveland.
   Leaning against a jeep while waiting his turn to board a C-5,
the 20-year-old soldier assigned to the field artillery unit, said
this was his first foreign deployment since joining the military a
year ago.
   ``All I can do is what I'm told to do,'' said Cpl. Roger Little,
23, of Milwaukee, echoing other soliders' comments that they knew
little of the situation they were flying into. ``The president says
I've got to go. There's got to be a good reason.''
   The corporal in the air defense artillery section that operates
the highly potent Stinger missile expressed pride in the weapon,
but added, ``I hope we won't have to use it.''
   Spec. Brian Kimes, a 19-year-old artillery gunner from Denver,
said the mission interrupted important personal plans.
   ``This means I won't be able to make my girlfriend's graduation
from high school,'' he said. ``My leave was canceled by the alert.
I couldn't even call to let her know.''
   One soldier who refused to be interviewed was nevertheless in
good spirits before TV cameras. He smiled, waved and said, ``Hi,
Mom!'' Beaming, he turned to his companions and added, ``I've
always wanted to do that.''
   Sheila Coffey, 24, said her husband, Kent, barely had time to
say farewell to his family before leaving Fort Ord on the Monterey
Peninsula as troops rolled out for the trip.
   ``I kissed him goodbye and he hugged our two kids and that was
it,'' she said. ``He's just doing his job _ what he was trained
for. He's a good soldier. But I'll worry about him, of course.''
</TEXT>
