<DOCNO> AP890512-0162 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-12-89 1602EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-People'sPark Bjt   05-12 0801</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People's Park, Bjt,0824</SECOND>
<HEAD>Berkeley's People's Park: Two Decades in Limbo</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICH CARTIERE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERKELEY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   People's Park, a hippie haven that
touched off a bloody riot 20 years ago, remains much as it was in
1969, a vacant lot that the University of California wants to
develop and activists want to see as a shrine to the '60s.
   ``This is going to be one of the top 10 or top 20 most important
pieces of land in history because it represents how the youth of
the '60s stood up to the big, powerful institutions that tried to
control their lives,'' said Jon Read, a landscaper who helped
organize the park project two decades ago.
   A virtual truce between activists and the university that began
in 1972 was disrupted last month when activists poured concrete for
a a permanent toilet at the park. The university had the concrete
torn up _ twice _ and had four activists who chained themselves to
the slab arrested.
   On Tuesday, religious activists moved a 66-foot mobile home set
up as a restaurant and dubbed the ``People's Cafe'' to the park to
feed the homeless. No immediate action was taken to remove the blue
trailer.
   But for the first time last week, UC-Berkeley officials said
longstanding plans to use the 2.3 acres for student housing and
recreational facilities are negotiable. Chancellor Ira Michael
Heyman's statement is considered a breakthrough by many of the
activists who tried to build People's Park in 1969.
   The university created the vacant lot, less than a mile from
campus, in 1967, tearing down a dozen buildings with the hopes of
building student housing and recreation facilities on the 2.3-acre
site.
   But in April 1969, activists attempted to claim the vacant
building site for ``the people,'' both to thumb their noses at the
establishment and because they believed the university's expansion
plans were insensitive to environmental concerns, said Read, 52.
   Thousands of activists, fraternity members, dropouts, elderly
residents and families trekked to the site with shovels and hoes to
plant flowers and roll sod.
   Matters came to a head on May 15, 1969, when the school tore up
the plants and put a fence around the site, and rioting ensued.
Sheriff's deputies shot dozens of protesters with shotguns. One,
James Rector, died a few days later; an artist was blinded and two
news reporters were among the wounded.
   Then-Gov. Ronald Reagan sent 2,000 National Guard troops to
occupy the city for 17 days. A nightly curfew was imposed and
meetings of more than three people were banned. In the first week
after the riot, 1,000 people were arrested.
   Demonstrators eventually tore down the park fence in 1972, and
the university agreed to give the public limited use on a temporary
basis.
   Since then, it has become a sort of no man's land, for the most
part overrun with drug dealers and transients, while the city and
the university blame each other for the park's deteriorating
condition.
   Today's city officials, who include some of the demonstrators of
1969, continue to fight development, for a variety of reasons.
   ``Ordinary people built a park out of a mudflat, and it came to
symbolize that the individual can make a difference, but the
university is still coming to grips with that,'' said Mayor Loni
Hancock, 49, who planted vegetables when the park was founded.
   ``You wouldn't build a volleyball court on the battlefield at
Gettysburg,'' she added.
   Heyman has called city council opposition to development of the
site a ``declaration of war.'' But he told reporters recently that
the issue could finally be resolved through negotiations with the
city over the university's long-range building plan.
   Aging activists are anxious for a resolution. There have been
rallies, marches, street fairs, ``teach-ins'' and civil
disobedience protests held to commemorate the park's 20th
anniversary.
   ``It's sacred ground and I hope we all succeed, someday, in
taking this land for everybody's enjoyment and use,'' said Jane
Goodwin, 47, who said she was wounded by a shotgun pellet during
the confrontation with police.
   The current Berlekeley student body president, Jeff Chang, who
was just 2 when the rioting took place, said today's students are
angry with the university for ``rolling back community efforts to
improve the park at every turn.''
   The university says that its rule against permanent facilities
on the spot is needed for legal reasons.
   Sociologist Todd Gitlin, a former president of the radical
Students for a Democratic Society, argues the police reaction to
the park symbolized the end of the radical political movements of
the '60s.
   ``People's Park was the last glimmering hope for a glad-eyed
movement, one that would be ecumenical, constructive and combative
all at once,'' he writes in ``The Sixties: Years of Hope, Days of
Rage,'' published last year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890512-0163 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-12-89 1740EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-BusinessInventories     05-12 0365</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Business Inventories,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Economists Not Worried Yet About Signs of Weakness</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Inflation Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rising business inventories combined with poor
sales for the second consecutive month in March, a sign of economic
weakness, the government said Friday, but economists said the trend
is not worrisome yet.
   The Commerce Department said inventories held on shelves and in
back lots climbed 0.3 percent to a seasonally adjusted $765.6
billion in March following a 0.4 percent rise in February.
   Business sales, meanwhile, were unchanged at a seasonally
adjusted $507.3 billion after plunging 0.9 percent in February, the
sharpest fall since January 1987.
   Rising inventories unaccompanied by sales increases sometimes
indicate a recession because manufacturers cut back production
until inventories are sold off. However, analysts said stockpiles
are not yet at troublesome levels.
   ``Inventories are fairly moderate,'' said economist Bruce
Steinberg of Merrill Lynch. ``There does not seem to be an excess
other than in the auto industry.''
   He said computerization and new inventory control techniques are
enabling businesses to respond more quickly to changes and sales,
preventing large backlogs from building.
   But economist Robert G. Dederick of Northern Trust Co. in
Chicago said inventories do bear watching. Anything more than a
moderate buildup could create a ``snap-the-whip effect'' and topple
the economy into a recession rather than the mild slowdown most
economists expect.
   ``We can't say there's been any rapid buildup ... but stocks
have been rising rapidly enough that they're vulnerable if sales
growth remains sluggish,'' he said.
   March business activity left the ratio of inventories to sales
at 1.51, meaning it would take 1.51 months to exhaust existing
inventories at the March sales pace. The ratio stood at 1.50 in
February and 1.48 in January.
   March's rise in inventories was led by a 0.5 percent gain at
manufacturing plants, followed by a 0.4 percent climb in retail
inventories and a 0.1 percent dip at the wholesale level.
   In sales, wholesalers showed a 0.2 percent gain and
manufacturers posted a 0.1 percent decline. Sales were unchanged at
retail stores in March. An advance report on retail sales in April,
released Thursday, showed a modest 0.4 percent gain.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
