closed to walk-in traffic</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Panama Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Panamanian Consulate was closed to
walk-in traffic Friday after the consul general walked out, saying
she was overcome by the recent volume of visa requests as civil
unrest intensified in her homeland.
   Consul General Elizabeth Martinez said through an interpreter
she was ``completely swamped'' with requests for travel visas. She
said she had been processing between 100 and 130 requests per month
from all over the world.
   The Tampa consulate is the only location in the United States
that issues travel visas for Panama, Martinez said. That was
confirmed by a woman at the Panamanian Embassy in Washington who
would not give her name.
   Journalists seeking visas at the consulate said they were turned
away by security guards after Martinez left with her files.
   She said she was still processing visa requests by mail.
   Ms. Martinez said she could approve requests by tourists, but
journalists' requests must be sent to Panama.
   Hundreds of American military dependents evacuated their homes
Friday in Panama as the first contingent of U.S. troops headed for
the Central American nation in the wake of annulled national
elections.
   The State Department has issued a travel advisory for Panama,
saying Americans shouldn't travel there due to ``extremely
unsettled conditions'' in the wake of the annulled presidential
election there.
