<HEAD>Police Deactivate Bombs Planted Near Exiles' Residence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALFONSO ANZUETO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GUATEMALA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police on Friday deactivated three bombs
planted inside a car near an apartment building occupied by
political leaders of Guatemala's leftist insurgency, one of the
leaders said.
   Police discovered the bombs after the leaders, members of the
Guatemalan Opposition Representation Union, received an anonymous
telephone threat, said opposition leader Frank Larue.
   The caller told them Thursday they had 12 hours to leave the
country.
   Larue and other exiles affiliated with the rebel's military
umbrella group, the Guatemalan National Revolutionary Union, have
been in Guatemala since April to participate in reconciliation
talks called for by a Central American peace plan.
   Guatemalan guerrillas have been fighting the government for 30
years.
   Employees at the apartment building in southern Guatemala City
also found flyers carrying death threats against the opposition
leaders littered around the grounds of the building, Larue said.
   Earlier, they discovered a car parked outside their building
with the word, ``Leave'' painted on a box inside.
   Larue said firefighters told the exiles shortly after midnight
Friday they were alerted by an anonymous caller that the bombs were
outside the building.
   National Police bomb experts disarmed the three devices after
evacuating nearby residents, Larue said.
   Another exiled leader, Rolando Castillo, told reporters he had
received death threats just before a coup attempt on Tuesday by
rebellious air force officers and troops against the government of
President Vinicio Cerezo.
   At least 10 officers have been jailed in connection with the
uprising, which was put down by loyalist troops without a shot
being fired.
