<FILEID>AP-NR-05-12-89 1728EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-AIDS-Poll     05-12 0323</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AIDS-Poll,0331</SECOND>
<HEAD>Poll Finds Fear of AIDS but Few People Changing Behavior</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One in five Californians has been tested
for the AIDS virus but few have taken steps to reduce the risk of
contracting the deadly illness, according to a Gallup Poll.
   The poll, paid for by hospital executives, found that while the
majority of residents have received some AIDS education, the
message is reaching a disproportionately low percentage of ethnic
minorities and poor people. Those are the groups in which the
disease, acquired immune deficiency syndrome, is spreading the most
rapidly.
   The survey, part of the Third Annual California Health Care
Poll, was one of the most comprehensive to be conducted in the
state, said George Gallup, who released the study Thursday.
   A demographic breakdown of those questioned indicated 22 percent
with a high school education or less were not aware of any AIDS
education programs, while 25 percent with incomes of less than
$20,000 said they were unaware. Among those with an annual income
of $75,000 or more awareness rose to 90 percent, the poll found.
   Only 26 percent of blacks and 38 percent of Asians had received
some AIDS education, according to the survey.
   The results indicated that some education is reaching most
Californians, but ``it suggests that the message be deepened and
that we find new approaches for reaching those who are not getting
the most effective messages possible,'' said Gallup.
   The poll was conducted in April by telephone to a sample of
1,000 California households and was designed by the Gallup
Organization, Inc., producers of the Gallup Poll, and executives
with the Southern California Hospital Council, said Robert Nielsen,
vice president of the Gallup Organization.
   The margin of error was plus or minus 3.1 percent.
   One-quarter of Californians fear becoming infected by the AIDS
virus, but only 15 percent have changed their way of life to
prevent contracting the illness, the poll found.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
