<FIRST>r i AM-Sudan-Ethiopia     05-12 0453</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sudan-Ethiopia,0466</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sudan Plays Peacemaker For Ethiopia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMED OSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sudan is acting as mediator for its
war-battered neighbor, Ethiopia, holding peace talks between the
Marxist government and the East African nation's largest rebel
movement, newspapers said Friday.
   Reports in three independent dailies indicate some movement
toward settling prolonged and expensive insurrections in both Sudan
and Ethiopia, which each support rebel movements fighting the
other's government.
   The three newspapers said no date has been set for the
conference, but that Ethiopian President Mengistu Haile Mariam and
leaders of the Eritrean People's Liberation Front have agreed to
direct negotiations in Khartoum.
   Sudanese Prime Minister Sadek Mahdi has said several times that
``peace is indivisible'' in northeastern Africa.
   Such comments are taken to mean he would end his support for
separatist rebels in Ethiopia's northernmost province of Eritrea
and other anti-Mengistu groups if the Ethiopian leader would
abandon the rebel Sudan People's Liberation Front.
   Eritrean rebels, who also espouse Marxism, have prosecuted
Africa's longest civil war. It began in 1961 and continued after
Mengistu and a clique of army officers deposed Emperor Haile
Selassie in 1974.
   The Eritrean People's Liberation Front boycotted an April
meeting in Khartoum involving Ethiopian officials and
representatives of four other Eritrean nationalist movements,
reportedly because of the type of autonomy the Addis Ababa
government wanted to discuss. In the absence of the largest rebel
group, the talks dissolved into squabbling and broke up with no
progress.
   The Khartoum newspapers reported that Mahdi gained approval for
the talks from the Eritrean Front's Secretary-General Asiasi Aforgi
at a meeting in the Sudanese capital last month.
   Mengistu informed Sudan of his government's ``complete
agreement'' to further discussions on causes of the rebellion and
to ``find a peaceful solution ... within the framework of a united
Ethiopian state,'' the newspaper Al-Ayam reported.
   Rancorous for years, relations between Sudan and Ethiopia have
improved in recent months, coinciding with major battlefield
successes by rebel groups in both countries.
   Sudan's civil war began six years ago when rebels from the
south, where the minority Christians and animists are in a
majority, took up arms in demand of more autonomy from the dominant
Moslems of the north. Hundreds of thousands of people have died as
a result, mostly civilians who starved from war-induced famine.
   On May 1, rebel leader John Garang declared a unilateral
month-long cease-fire that will help a massive U.N. relief effort 1
to stockpile food and save thousands from starvation before annual
heavy rains that cut off much of the region.
   Ethiopia and Sudan, which the World Bank says are among the
world's poorest nations, each spend more than a million dollars a
days prosecuting their wars.
</TEXT>
