<FIRST>r i AM-Philippines-US     05-12 0479</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Philippines-US,0496</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rebel Confesses to U.S. Colonel's Killing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FERNANDO, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A communist rebel has confessed
to taking part in the April killing of a U.S. Army colonel,
officials said Friday, but they have not charged him because he
keeps changing his story.
   Ricardo Prestosa said rebels assassinated Col. James ``Nick''
Rowe because he was a ``big hindrance to the revolutionary
movement,'' according to a recorded confession played to reporters
by Brig. Gen. Cesar Nazareno.
   Rowe, 51, was slain April 21 outside the headquarters of the
Joint U.S. Military Assistance Group in suburban Quezon city as he
was being driven to work. He was a Vietnam War hero from McAllen,
Texas, whose book ``Five Years to Freedom'' describes his five
years of imprisonment by the Viet Cong and his escape. In the
Philippines, he commanded U.S. ground forces.
   A senior Philippine officer said Prestosa, 29, admitted the
slaying Thursday to police in Bataan province, where he was
arrested, but recanted Friday and has repeated the confession
several times since then.
   Speaking on condition of anonymity, he said the rebel was
transferred to Manila for further investigation. He was arrested
Wednesday in his hometown of Dinalupihan, 40 miles west of the
capital, across Manila Bay in Bataan.
   Nazareno, the regional constabulary commander, said nothing
about Prestosa's renunciation, and the Bataan police commander,
Col. Ramsey Ocampo, denied in a telephone interview that a
confession was made at all. The line was cut, however, and efforts
to contact him again were unsuccessful.
   A senior officer under Ocampo's command said Prestosa claimed to
have taken part in the attack on Rowe. He said investigators doubt
the confession because Prestosa ``appeared confused'' and ``kept
changing his story.''
   Nazareno said no charges have been filed.
   In the tape, Prestosa said in the Tagalog language that he knew
Rowe because ``we had been watching him for a long time.''
   ``Why did you kill him?'' the interrogator asked.
   ``Because he was a big hindrance to the revolutionary
movement,'' Prestosa replied.
   The communist New People's Army claimed responsibility the day
after the slaying, saying its fighters killed Rowe because of
alleged U.S. interference in the Philippine government's
counterinsurgency campaign.
   Officials could give no reason for Prestosa's apparent confusion.
   ``He wants to insinuate he was there,'' the officer said. ``When
questioned repeatedly he says `yes.' Then, after a while, after
thinking things over, he backs out.''
   At least two details in Prestosa's recorded account did not jibe
with fact, another reason investigators are wary.
   Prestosa claimed Rowe was killed ``around 10 a.m.,'' but police
and witnesses say he was assassinated at 7:10 a.m.
   The rebel also said the killers abandoned a car in Manila's Paco
district. But police said they found the car in the San Francisco
del Monte district, four miles from Paco.
   Communist rebels have been fighting for 20 years to overthrow
the government.
</TEXT>
