<SECOND>AM-Poisoning,0205</SECOND>
<HEAD>Free Food Makes 97 Schoolchildren Ill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At least 97 students from two schools
were hospitalized after eating a free lunch provided under a new
government program, news reports and officials said Friday.
   The incident occurred Thursday in the Anuradhapur district, 103
miles northeast of Colombo.
   Most of the students, aged 8-19, showed symptoms of food
poisoning but were discharged later in the day, Anuradhapur
Education Director E.S.W. Perera said in an interview.
   Elmo Gooneratna, senior assistant secretary for education,
blamed the local government for employing food contractors despite
instructions for schools to preapre the food.
   ``The contractors, unconcerned about health standards, were
supplying the meals only with the intention of making profits,'' he
said. ``In one instance a contractor was found transporting buns in
a hearse.''
   The free meal scheme began on May 2 and will cost $59 million a
year, Gooneratna said.
   Lunches consist of rice and curries or buns with fish or eggs
and are supposed to provide 600 to 800 calories. The project is to
help raise nutritional standards in Sri Lanka, where more than 40
percent of the 16 million people live below the poverty line.
