<FIRST>r w AM-WheatProgram     05-12 0212</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wheat Program,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>USDA Urged To Keep Wheat Restrictions</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release at 6 p.m. EDT today, set by source</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The president of the National Association of
Wheat Growers said Friday he has urged the Agriculture Department
to keep restrictions on 1990 production despite severe losses to
this year's crop.
   Reggie Wyckoff, a Genoa, Colo., wheat farmer, said in a letter
to department officials that allowing all-out production next year
would ``do serious damage to the level of recovery'' that has been
achieved so far.
   The USDA is required by law to announce by June 1 the level of
land-idling that will be required in order for 1990 producers to
qualify for federal price supports and other benefits on their
wheat crop.
   Wheat farmers were required to set-aside 10 percent of their
wheat base acres for 1989. But drought and late-season freezes in
Kansas and some other major winter wheat states have trimmed this
year's harvest outlook sharply.
   The department may be under some pressure to discontinue its
acreage reduction program, or ARP, in 1990, he said. A zero
requirement ``could put the U.S. back on a rapid course'' to
surpluses, Wyckoff added.
   Next year's idling requirement should not be larger that the 10
percent for 1989, he said.
