<FILEID>AP-NR-05-12-89 2037EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Japan     05-12 0540</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan,0558</SECOND>
<HEAD>Scandal-Tainted Governing Party at a Loss for a Leader</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ERIC TALMADGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The scandal-plagued governing party was at a loss
for a leader Friday after senior politician Masayoshi Ito refused
requests that he lead the party and government.
   Analysts commenting on the unexpected refusal cited Ito's
statements that the Liberal Democratic Party does not realize how
seriously it has been damaged by an influence-peddling scandal that
has shrunk its popularity rating in polls to less than 4 percent.
   ``Mr. Ito formally expressed his rejection ... and, despite
party leaders' persistent attempts to persuade him, did not change
his position,'' party spokesman Ryutaro Hashimoto told a news
conference.
   ``Frankly, we are at a loss,'' he said.
   Ito, 75, is among a handful of senior members of the party
untainted by the Recruit scandal, which has forced Prime Minister
Noboru Takeshita to announce his resignation. Takeshita is expected
to step down later this month, and three of his Cabinet ministers
already have resigned.
   Fourteen businessmen and ex-bureaucrats have been arrested on
bribery or other charges in connection with sales of unlisted,
bargain-priced shares in a subsidiary of Recruit Co., an
information conglomerate.
   The party had asked Ito to replace Takeshita and improve the
party's image before summer elections for half the seats in the
upper house of Parliament. Because the party has a huge majority in
Parliament, its leader is virtually guaranteed to become prime
minister.
   Hashimoto said Ito's reasons for refusing were his health and
disagreements with party leaders over reform and the way the party
is taking responsibility for the scandal.
   This week, Ito complained the party lacks a sense of crisis, and
he told reporters ``revolutionary changes in the party's way of
thinking are needed.''
   He had demanded the resignations of all politicians linked to
corruption cases and an end to factions in the party, which is made
up of half a dozen cliques.
   Fund-raising plays a major role in factionalism and the scandal.
Takeshita has admitted receiving more than a million dollars in
donations from Recruit.
   ``Ito wanted the job, but didn't feel he would be able to carry
out reform under the current circumstances,'' said political
analyst Asao Yamaguchi.
   ``There is really no feeling of crisis in the party. They have
been at the top so long they just don't realize the danger, and it
will take big losses at the polls to open their eyes,'' he said.
   In a Saturday editorial, the nationally circulated newspaper
Asahi Shimbun agreed.
   ``There was a gaping crevice between Ito and the other LDP
members, including Takeshita, over the degree to which they
recognized the people's fury toward politics. That crevice was
never bridged,'' it said.
   Former Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa, head of the party
faction to which Ito belongs, told reporters he does not see the
rejection as final and will try to change Ito's mind.
   The party's top four executives, Ito among them, are to meet
Saturday to pursue the question of a leader.
   Yamaguchi said Shin Kanemaru, a former deputy prime minister and
Takeshita's mentor, now is the most likely candidate for prime
minister.
   However, Kanemaru is only a year younger than Ito and, like him,
suffers from diabetes.
</TEXT>
