<FIRST>r i AM-PolarIcewalk 1stLd-Writethru   05-12 0496</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Polar Icewalk, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0690,0509</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arctic Expedition Nearing North Pole</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS 8th graf, `The expedition...' to CLARIFY.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SOLL SUSSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An exhausted, eight-man expedition seeking to
dramatize environmental hazards in the Arctic has been hampered by
melting ice on the last days before its expected arrival at the
North Pole.
   ``They're walking non-stop, it seems,'' spokeswoman Tracey
Carpenter said in a telephone interview from Icewalk expedition
headquarters in Ottawa. ``They're zigzagging around all this broken
ice and making good progress.''
   On arrival, the expedition's leader, British explorer Robert
Swan, will become the first man to walk to the North and South
poles. He reached the South Pole with two other men in 1986.
   Progress has been slower than hoped in the last leg because of
the early spring weather conditions that produce crumbling,
drifting ice and the threat of open seas.
   ``It's looking good. We're pretty convinced that it's going to
be Sunday,'' Carpenter said.
   She said the expedition was 28 miles from the North Pole on
Friday. The men have been averaging 14 miles daily.
   Plans are for an Icewalk flight to pick up the expedition on
Sunday at the North Pole and fly them to Eureka on Ellesmere Island.
   The expedition, which has a $4 million budget, had hoped to
complete the 457-mile trek by mid-May at the latest. The departure
was several days later than hoped because of heavy snow in March.
Temperatures have been warmer than expected in recent days,
reaching as high as 28 degrees Fahrenheit.
   ``It's just wending their way through half water, half ice,''
Carpenter said.
   Solar flares have frequently disrupted radio contact since the
expedition began March 20 from Cape Aldrich on Ellesmere Island.
Supply flights have succeeded in reaching them.
   It differs from other Arctic expeditions in using only human
power to travel and take supplies along. The eight men ski, but do
not use dogsleds or skimobiles.
   The explorers have been gathering air and snow samples along
their route, as well as collecting data on the effect of cold on
humans.
   Canadian research over the past four years in the Arctic has
turned up dozens of pesticides and other toxic substances in the
region's fragile ecosystem, many of them entering the food chain.
Attention also has focused on the thinning of the world's ozone
layer, most notably at the world's poles, and on acid rain.
   The Icewalk team includes members from Britain, Canada, the
United States, the Soviet Union, Japan, Australia and West Germany.
   The American is Darryl Roberts, from New York City. He had
suffered frostbite on his feet in April when temperatures fell to
67 degrees below zero.
   ``Since the beginning there was great concern that he'd have to
(leave),'' Carpenter said. ``He was very committed to carrying on.''
   The Soviet member, Dr. Mikhail Malakov, treated Roberts and four
others for frostbite. Malakov, who also experienced frostbite,
completed the successful Canada-Soviet Polar Bridge Expedition last
year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
