<FIRST>u w AM-MathChamp 1stLd-Writethru a0677 05-12 0544</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Math Champ, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0677,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pennsylvania 13-Year-Old Wins National Math Contest</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 8th graf, Albert fended, to CORRECT wording of second math
problem</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Overcoming bad lighting and computer problems,
13-year-old Albert Kurz of Holland, Pa., became the nation's sixth
MathCounts champion Friday by calculating the price of a stock.
   The finals in the junior high school math competition, sponsored
by NASA, the National Society of Professional Engineers and other
organizations, capped nine months of local and state contests
entered by more than 700,000 students.
   A total of 224 math whizzes _ all but 30 of them boys _ made it
to the countdown rounds in Washington. As the winner, Albert takes
home a $10,000 scholarship, a gold medal and a personal computer.
He will also spend a week at the U.S. Space Camp in Huntsville,
Ala., and on Monday he goes to the White House to meet President
Bush.
   Lenny Ng of Chapel Hill, N.C., and Robert Kleinberg of Wales
Center, N.Y., the second and third place finishers, received
scholarships of $6,000 and $4,000, respectively. They will also
visit the space camp, as will Ng's three colleagues on the
top-scoring state team from North Carolina.
   No calculators are permitted in the competition. Students use
pencil, paper and their minds to figure out the problems.
   The 10 finalists viewed problems on computer monitors and
punched buzzers to indicate they were ready with answers _
sometimes even before the master of ceremonies had started reading
the problem to the audience.
   There were a number of tense moments, some because the lighting
made it hard to see who had hit his buzzer. And the last round was
delayed by a computer malfunction.
   Albert fended off all challengers with lightning-fast answers to
questions such as: ``The diagonal of a cube is the square root of
27. What is the volume?'' and ``If y equals the negative value of
the absolute value of x minus 2, for what value of x will y attain
its maximum value?''
   The answers: 27 and 2.
   The winning problem posed the following question: ``The price of
a stock increased 10 percent and then decreased 10 percent before
it was sold for $99. What was the original price of the stock?''
Albert gave the correct answer of $100.
   ``I spent nights from 3 p.m. to 10 p.m. studying and it really
paid off,'' Albert said after his victory. When asked how he could
figure problems so quickly, he replied, ``I can't do them on paper
because my hand's too shaky to write. I don't know. I just do it.''
   Albert said his mother is a housewife and his father a civil
engineer. He said his hobbies include basketball, ping pong and
computer games, and he would like to become ``either an engineer or
a mathematician.''
   MathCounts is described as the only national math coaching and
competition program for junior high school students. It is designed
to stimulate students' interest in math before they must make
course decisions that may affect their career choices.
   Other MathCounts sponsors in addition to NASA and the engineers
association are CNA Insurance Cos., the National Council of
Teachers of Mathematics, Cray Research Foundation and General
Motors Foundation.
</TEXT>
