<FIRST>r w AM-FarmLabor     05-12 0225</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Farm Labor,220</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sharp Seasonal Increase in Hired Hands</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The number of workers employed by farmers
showed a sharp seasonal increase this spring but trailed year-ago
levels, the Agriculture Department said Friday.
   A quarterly report said the hired work force on farms was
estimated at 830,000 workers during the week of April 9-15 used for
a survey, compared with 936,000 a year earlier. In January, the
previous survey showed 701,000 hired workers on farms.
   Those did not include 198,000 ``agricultural service'' workers
provided by crew chiefs and labor contractors. A year earlier those
totaled 224,000 workers.
   The report said rain during the survey week slowed field work in
the Southeast and most of the Delta. Also, spring wheat planting
was behind the normal pace in the major production states.
   The report said the national figures for hired workers had a
sampling error of 5.1 percent.
   Average pay for all workers hired directly by farmers was $5.35
per hour, up from $5 per hour a year earlier but below the average
of $5.51 in January, the report said.
   For workers hired by contractors, there was no national wage
rate available. However, workers in California were reported at
$6.45 per hour in April, compared with $6.42 in January and $5.68 a
year earlier. Florida workers averaged $6.24, $5.79 and $6.15 per
hour, respectively.
</TEXT>
