<FIRST>r w AM-IndianInvestigation 1stLd-Writethru   05-12 0710</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Indian Investigation, 1st Ld-Writethru,710</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: To update with statement from U.S. District Court in Oklahoma
City, adds 4 grafs after 12th graf previous, ``It seems</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Cheyenne-Arapaho woman, disabled from polio,
said Friday she can't get welfare as long as she is on federal oil
royalty rolls and since those checks stopped coming regularly she
lost her home and children.
   Mary Limpy choked back tears as she told a special investigating
committee of the Senate Select Committee on Indian Affairs that she
has lived three years in an abandoned house in Oklahoma City
because she could not pay her bills.
   The checks stopped coming regularly in 1983, said Mrs. Limpy,
who said the state took custody of her two youngest children two
years ago.
   Now, the money comes sporadically, and the Bureau of Indian
Affairs which manages her three wells can't say why, she told the
committee.
   ``I do not get my royalty checks right after the gas or oil is
sold,'' she said. ``I get my checks sometimes four to seven months
later. Recently, it has been about four months later.''
   She said the checks average $30 to $60. She told the committee
she would be better off if she did not have the royalties at all
and could apply for state welfare.
   Mrs. Limpy said her wells originally were leased by the Tenneco
Oil Co. which sold the leases to Koch Oil. She said at one point
she heard the wells had been capped, but the farmer who works the
land where the wells are located said trucks kept going on and off
the oilfield.
   Witnesses before the committee earlier in the week testified
that Koch, which is based in Wichita, Kan., had been stealing oil
from Indian wells, a charge the company has denied.
   Mrs. Limpy is part of a federal class-action lawsuit charging
that the government has violated its trust responsibilities to
Indians with oil well interests, said attorney Steve Moore.
   Moore said the suit's plaintiffs include 7,000 allottees with
interest in 944 oil leases in western Oklahoma.
   That lawsuit has been held under advisement by Judge Ralph
Thompson, of the western district of Oklahoma, for 2{ years, said
Moore.
   ``It seems outrageous that a federal judge has refused to act
when you have the obvious need,'' said DeConcini. He suggested that
the judge be investigated for possible negligence or misconduct.
   Thompson had no comment on Mrs. Limpy's testimony conerning
delays in the case.
   However, a statement issued by Bob Dennis, court clerk for the
western district of Oklahoma, said counsel for both sides have
reported to the court that settlement offers have been ongoing
while they watched an ``almost identical'' case pending in New
Mexico.
   The statement said the New Mexico case settled by an entry of
consent decree in March, and that both parties in Mrs. Limpy's case
filed a status report last month that ``specific settlement offers
were forthcoming'' and that the parties would report on their
progress in July.
   The court said they waited on the New Mexico case to avoid a
potential conflict in rulings, to avoid delays in possible appeals
and to ``enhance the prospects of an agreed settlement in the
case.''
   In Oklahoma, Indians have been allotted land by federal
treaties. When that land includes oil property, the federal
government is responsible for making sure the Indians get their
share of the royalties.
   The government supplies an ``explanation of payment'' that is
supposed to help the allottees understand the condition of the well
and why the check is for a certain amount.
   Every witness that appeared before the committee Friday said the
forms are nearly impossible to understand.
   Houston and Velma Decker, a Caddo Indian couple living in
Oklahoma, said they have been trying since March 1988 to find out
why their checks suddenly dropped in amount.
   Neither the BIA nor the Minerals Management Service has given
them an answer, despite repeated inquiries, they said.
   ``I have allottees that come in everyday,'' said Ken Young of a
BIA office in Utah. ``There's no way they can understand (the
forms).''
   He said he thought the government bureaucracy should be
elminated and the oil companies should pay the allottees directly.
</TEXT>
