<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Mongolia     05-12 0286</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Mongolia,0293</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets to Start Withdrawing Troops From Mongolia</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tass said Friday that Soviet tank and air defense
units will begin withdrawing from Mongolia on Monday, the same day
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev begins a visit to China.
   The news agency said the units will leave the Mongolian railroad
stations of Erdenet and Choir and cross the border at the Soviet
city of Kyakhta.
   Tass quoted Col. Gen. Dmitry Grinkevich, chief of the army
general staff, as saying about 50,000 men, more than 850 tanks and
nearly 1,100 infantry vehicles will be pulled out of Mongolia by
next year. He said the withdrawal also involves more than 820
different artillery systems, 190 planes and 130 helicopters. He did
not say how many Soviet military personnel are in Mongolia.
   Gorbachev announced the withdrawal plan in a speech to the U.N.
General Assembly in New York on Dec. 7. He gave few details, and
Grinkkevich's comments provided the first breakdown of units to be
pulled out.
   Soviet Foreign Ministry spokesman Gennady I. Gerasimov said on
March 7 that the Soviet Union had begun withdrawing three-fourth of
its troops from Mongolia, including all of its air force units, but
he did not say when the pullout began or how many troops were
involved.
   It was not clear why Tass reported Friday that the withdrawal
would only begin Monday, more than two months after Gerasimov said
it had started.
   Mongolia is between China and the Soviet Union, and China has
said the removal of Soviet troops from the country was a necessary
step to improving relations between the two communist powers.
   Gorbachev's visit to Beijing will be the first Chinse-Soviet
summit in 30 years.
</TEXT>
