<FIRST>u i AM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0627 05-12 0706</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0627,0727</SECOND>
<HEAD>Clashes Continue on Eve of Government Meetings</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS thruout to CORRECT time element, UPDATE with details on
clashes. ADDS dropped word `East' in final graf. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By G.G. LaBELLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir on Friday
scheduled the first political tests of his election plan for the
occupied lands. Arab doctors said Israeli troops shot and killed a
24-year-old Palestinian.
   At least 10 other Palestinians were wounded in confrontations
between soldiers and stone-throwers in the occupied West Bank and
Gaza Strip, Arab reports said.
   Shamir called meetings for Saturday and Sunday to consider
guidelines for the elections, the first with Cabinet ministers of
his right-wing Likud bloc and the second with the full Cabinet,
including members of the left-leaning Labor Party.
   Shamir's proposal to end the 17-month rebellion in the occupied
lands involves elections to choose Palestinian representatives who
would negotiate with Israel for limited autonomy. Talks would
follow three years later on a permanent settlement.
   When it meets Sunday, the 25-member government likely will
sidestep controversial issues such as the participation of
Palestinians from outside the territories _ a Palestinian demand
reportedly supported by the United States.
   ``What we are bringing are the main principles, the skeleton of
the plan, without getting into details,'' said a Shamir aide, who
spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The meetings come during a weekend visit by U.S. officials who
are expected to press Shamir for specifics such as whether 140,000
Palestinians living in east Jerusalem will be able to vote and
whether there will be international supervision.
   Both Radio Moscow and the Abu Dhabi newspaper Al Ittihad
reported that Palestine Liberation Organization chief Yasser Arafat
will accept the elections if they are held under international
supervision.
   Shamir introduced his idea for elections last month at a meeting
with President Bush following criticism of Israel's handling of the
uprising.
   Since then, Palestinians in the occupied territories and the
PLO, which is outlawed here, have rejected the elections.
   Clashes occur daily. On Friday, five confrontations erupted in
the Gaza Strip and one in the West Bank town of El Bireh, just
north of Jerusalem.
   The worst confrontation was in Gaza City, the seaside strip's
largest town, where troops opened fire on stone-throwing youths,
killing Mahmoud Awad Akraa and wounding six others, Arab hospital
officials said.
   A military spokesman confirmed Akraa's death but said a
preliminary report showed no troops were in the area at the time of
the alleged confrontation.
   He said the army was continuing its investigation into the death.
   The death would raise to at least 472 the number of Palestinians
killed since they started rebelling against Israeli occupation in
December 1987. Twenty-one Israelis also have died.
   The Gaza clashes occurred despite a curfew that confined the
strip's 700,000 residents to their homes for a fifth day.
   In the West Bank town of Nablus, troops shot and wounded two
Palestinians including a 15-year-old.
   In Israel, just north of Gaza, Israelis stoned Arab-owned cars
for a second day to protest the killing of one soldier in the area
and the disappearance of another soldier. Police have blamed
Palestinians.
   The incidents and the murder of two Israelis by a Palestinian in
Jerusalem last week have raised right-wing opposition to Shamir's
election plan.
   Among opponents is Trade Minister Ariel Sharon, who says they
will bring disaster.
   ``The plan will not bring peace, but a PLO Palestinian state,
terror and war, and the re-division of Jerusalem,'' he told Yediot
Ahronot newspaper.
   Most Likud ministers are expected to approve and ministers of
the Labor Party already approved the plan Thursday.
   After Sunday's meeting, Shamir will meet with Dennis Ross, a
senior aide to Secretary of State James Baker III. Ross arrives
Saturday night to brief Israeli leaders on Baker's talks in Moscow
with Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze.
   Ross also is expected to meet Palestinian leaders. He reportedly
is trying to make the election plan more attractive to them by
urging Israel to allow Arabs in east Jerusalem to vote _ a concept
opposed by Shamir but favored by Labor Party leaders.
   East Jerusalem was captured from Jordan in the 1967 Middle East
war and annexed into the Israeli capital.
</TEXT>
