<FIRST>u w AM-WrightProbe     05-12 0499</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wright Probe,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Witness in Wright Probe Accuses Ethics Commitee of Threatening Him</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A witness in the House ethics committee's
probe of Speaker Jim Wright charged Friday that the panel had
unfairly threatened him for attempting to correct what he saw as a
misleading account of his testimony.
   ``When Mr. Payte attempted to correct the record, you used the
power of your committee to attempt to silence him,'' wrote Preston
M. Geren III, an attorney for Fort Worth real estate developer S.
Gene Payte, in a letter to the ethics panel.
   Payte had testified before the panel last Oct. 17 and told of
his efforts to give money to Wright because he appreciated the
speaker's work in Congress. Wright declined the gift, and Payte
then sought to buy copies of Wright's book, ``Reflections of a
Public Man,'' to show his appreciation.
   According to the report of special ethics committee counsel
Richard J. Phelan, Payte then paid a total of $6,000, intended
partly to help revise and update the book and to pay for 1,000
copies.
   The report states that ``although he was equivocal on the point
in his testimony, Payte testified that he only received between 300
and 500 copies of the `old' book for his $6,000, and would still
like to receive the new books.''
   Apparently based on that testimony, the ethics committee deemed
the money for the undelivered books an improper gift to Wright and
added that to its formal charges against the speaker.
   Payte later disputed the account of his testimony, issuing a
public affidavit last month that contended the reference to 300 to
500 books came in a question from Rep. John T. Myers of Indiana,
the committee's ranking Republican, and that he had said several
times he received all 1,000 books he paid for.
   On Friday, Payte released a copy of a May 5 letter he received
from the ethics panel reminding him of a gag order on committee
witnesses.
   ``Your affidavit represents a course of conduct in direct
violation of the admonition given to you,'' the letter stated.
``Accordingly, we wish to notify you that the matter of your
violation may be taken up by the committee ...''
   Payte ``was very disturbed, and when he got over being
disturbed, was very angry'' at the letter, Geren said. ``He sees it
as an effort by the committee to make him keep quiet, an effort to
bluff him into silence.''
   He said Payte's affidavit addressed only matters that already
were public because they were included in the ethics committee's
published report.
   Committee Chairman Julian Dixon, D-Calif., said the letter ``in
no way'' was intended as a threat, but was a reminder that
witnesses are not to discuss testimony given in private.
   ``If he felt his testimony had been characterized unfairly, the
first people he should talk to is the committee,'' Dixon said,
adding that he was unaware of any effort by Payte to do so.
</TEXT>
