<FIRST>r w AM-FDA-GenericDrugs     05-12 0464</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-FDA-Generic Drugs,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dingell Says FDA Probe is Retaliation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of the House investigations
subcommittee said Friday an FDA inspection of a New Jersey drug
manufacturing plant appeared to be an attempt to retaliate against
the firm for testifying against the agency.
   Rep. John Dingell, D-Mich., asked the Food and Drug
Administration to explain the Thursday inspection of the Barr
Laboratories' plant, which began about the time Barr executives
were concluding their testimony before Dingell's panel.
   ``The committee is of the tentative view ... that there is an
attempt here to coerce, harass, intimidate or retaliate against the
persons who cooperated in the investigation,'' he said.
   The Pomona, N.Y.-based Barr Laboratories was informed by the FDA
on Thursday night the inspection had been suspended pending an
internal review, according to the company's attorney, H. Lawrence
Fox.
   The head of Mylan Laboratories in Pittsburgh told the
subcommittee at Thursday's hearing the FDA was holding up approvals
on some of the company's products in retaliation for Mylan having
started the investigation into alleged bribery and other corruption
at the agency's generic drug division.
   Mylan's complaints about discriminatory and arbitrary treatment
by the division sparked an inquiry by the House Energy and Commerce
investigations subcommittee a year ago. The panel turned over its
evidence to the U.S. attorney's office in Baltimore, though it is
continuing its investigation.
   Two FDA employees and a drug company executive have been charged
in the case, and more arrests are expected.
   FDA spokesman Jeff Nesbit said that ``due to the generics
investigation, FDA conducted a retrospective review of generic
products and manufacturing sites to be sure that no product was
released that was unsafe.
   ``We had no idea when this project was started weeks ago that an
inspection of Barr Labs would begin on the same day as the hearing.
As soon as we found out about the inspection, we called it off,''
he said.
   Investigators have said they have found no evidence that any
unsafe or ineffective drugs were put on the market as a result of
the alleged improprieties.
   Dingell said Thursday he would not tolerate reprisals against
any of the companies or individuals cooperating with his panel.
Later the same day, acting FDA Deputy Commissioner James Benson
wrote Dingell assuring him there would be no retaliation. Benson
also sent a memo to division employees warning against ``even the
appearance of retaliatory action.''
   Fox said the company was last inspected nine months ago and that
the FDA had found nothing wrong and the company has had no recalls
since then. In such circumstances, he said, inspections usually
occur at two-year intervals.
   ``It isn't real difficult to look back and see (the last
inspection) wasn't two years ago,'' Fox said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
