<FIRST>r i AM-Shakespeare 1stLd-Writethru a0614 05-12 0665</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Shakespeare, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0614,0681</SECOND>
<HEAD>Actors Urge Halt to Project on Site of Shakespeare-Era Theater</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 4th pvs, `As a...' to UPDATE with development
company saying remains of theater will be protected. Pick up 5th pvs, `Ridley,
who...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WEST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dustin Hoffman and other stars Friday urged the
government to halt a new office project on the remains of a 16th
century theater where Shakespeare once acted.
   In a letter to the newspaper The Independent, Hoffman and 15
actors and directors called for the site of the Rose theater to be
designated an ancient monument to ensure its preservation.
   Without the designation, the recently discovered remains will be
irrevocably damaged by the construction work due to start Monday,
they said. The remains include part of the stage and collapsed
walls of the Elizabethan theater where Shakespeare acted in 1592.
   ``As a last-ditch attempt to save the remains of the Rose
theater from destruction, we appeal to the Secretary of State for
the Environment (Nicholas Ridley) to schedule the site as an
Ancient Monument immediately. After Monday it will be too late.''
   Later Friday, the development company involved said the remains
of the Rose theater would be protected and preserved beneath the
building ``with minimal damage,'' but the Royal Shakespeare Company
said the assurances did not go far enough.
   Several actors said they still intended to go to the site in
protest on Sunday, and that Ian McKellen and Dame Peggy Ashcroft
would read from Shakespeare's ``Henry VI,'' the first play
performed at the Rose.
   Ridley, who opened an office building in Southampton on Friday,
said: ``I haven't decided what to do. When I have decided, I will
make an announcement.''
   In addition to Hoffman, the signatories included Simon Callow,
Dame Judi Dench, James Fox, Peter Hall, and Tim Pigott-Smith.
   Hoffman, winner of this year's best actor Oscar for the film
``Rain Man,'' is in Britain to play Shylock in a stage production
of Shakespeare's ``The Merchant of Venice'' later this month.
   In a letter Friday to The Times of London, Lord Olivier, Dame
Peggy Ashcroft and eight others wrote: ``Plans for the office block
... show the area peppered with concrete piles. One is to be placed
center-stage _ a stage on which (Christopher) Marlowe, Shakespeare
and (Ben) Jonson trod...
   ``Surely the secretary of state (Ridley) should intervene ... to
prevent building from proceeding and to save the entire Rose
theater site for the nation.''
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher on Thursday told the House of
Commons that ``everything possible'' will be done to preserve the
theater.
   ``There have been very constructive discussions between the
developers, English Heritage (a body that preserves historic sites)
and the Museum of London, with the result that the remains are
going to be preserved with the minimum of damage.''
   Imry Merchant Developers said Thursday: ``The remains are going
to be wrapped as carefully as a porcelain doll. There must be a
building over the top of it and to protect the Rose there has to be
a protective covering for it.''
   But Harvey Sheldon, the archaeologist who led Museum of London
excavations at the site, later said ``parts of the stage walls will
be demolished so that the piles for the new building can be driven
through it.''
   Museum experts located and uncovered the remains of the theater
after an office building was demolished in December.
   American actor-producer Sam Wanamaker has called the Rose the
``20th century's most important discovery regarding the cradle of
the great Elizabethan theater.''
   The museum excavations suggest that the theater, originally
thought to have been octagonal, had 17 or 18 sides or was
elliptical.
   Records show it was demolished not long after Shakespeare acted
there. The chalk foundations lie 6 feet below the modern surface.
   The excavations have unearthed thousands of hazelnut shells _
the Elizabethan equivalent of popcorn _ clay pipes dating from
1580, sheep bones and large numbers of oyster shells.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
