<FIRST>u i AM-PLO 1stLd-Writethru a0731 05-12 0705</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-PLO, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0731,0725</SECOND>
<HEAD>WHO Shelves PLO Membership Bid Until Next Year</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 19 grafs UPDATING with official U.S., Israeli reaction.
Picks up 16th pvs, `WHO Director...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HANNS NEUERBOURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Under U.S. prodding, the World Health Organization
on Friday shelved until next year a decision on whether to admit
the PLO's self-declared state of Palestine as its 167th member.
   The State Department in Washington hailed the action, saying the
organization ``rejected the PLO's efforts to politicize WHO's
important work.''
   The vote dashed PLO hopes of winning voting rights in all major
U.N. agencies this year after its legislature in Tunis, the capital
of Tunisia, last November proclaimed the ``State of Palestine.''
   The WHO annual assembly voted 83-47 in a secret ballot in favor
of a resolution co-sponsored by nine Western and Third World
countries. It coupled the deferral with a call for more aid to
residents of Israeli-occupied lands, where a Palestinian uprising
began 17 months ago. Twenty members abstained.
   The Soviet Union joined in supporting the resolution. Soviet
Health Minister E.I. Chazov told the assembly earlier that Moscow
wanted to find a ``solution avoiding confrontation .''
   Dr. Fathi Arafat, head of the Palestine Liberation Organization
observer delegation and the physician brother of PLO Chairman
Yasser Arafat, said the resolution means ``you will all stand
behind us next year. You will all vote so that we may assume our
role of peace in all the international organizations.''
   Earlier, the meeting refused to consider Nicaraguan amendments
that would have effectively turned the proposal into a call for the
PLO's immediate admission.
   The voting followed more than four hours of procedural wrangling.
   Nearly 100 countries have recognized the state of Palestine or
at least acknowledged its proclamation.
   Israel objected to Friday's resolution. In an official statement
released in Jerusalem moments after the vote, the Foreign Ministry
said deferring the decision to admit the PLO ``poses an obstacle to
peace in our region.''
   ``There is no place for this terrorist organization among the
members of this humanitarian organization,'' it said.
   The United States, which is contributing $74 million _ or 25
percent _ to the WHO's regular budget in 1989, threatened to
withdraw all payments to any U.N. agency admitting the PLO as a
full member.
   Thirty-eight senators led by Robert W. Kasten Jr, R-Wis., wrote
a letter last month to Secretary of States James A. Baker III,
vowing they would seek such cuts in U.S. contributions.
   In Washington, Kasten hailed Friday's vote as ``a very
significant defeat for the PLO. ... More importantly, it shows what
we can accomplish with a unified and bipartisan approach to foreign
policy with the executive and legislative branches working hand in
hand.''
   Baker, joined by all Western nations, argued that the
self-proclaimed new entity did not fullfill internationally
accepted criteria of statehood, including control of a defined
territory.
   He said PLO admission would harm the Middle East peace process
and the entire U.N. system.
   The State Department issued a statement saying the Bush
administration ``reaffirms U.S. support for the WHO'' and its
global health-improvement programs, while adding that Washington
also will continue to oppose any change in the non-voting observer
status of the PLO in the WHO or any other U.N. bodies.
   All 21 Arab countries backed the PLO's application.
   WHO Director General Hiroshi Nakajima, a Japanese physician, had
pleaded in vain with Yasser Araft to withdraw his application for
membership or at least put it off until the next assembly. Nakajima
said a cutoff of U.S. funds would ``completely destroy'' the agency.
   Hours before the debate started, the PLO said it would help
finance the WHO's African operations in case of a withdrawal of
U.S. funds. It said it raised the money from Arab countries.
   Nakajima told the assembly again that WHO's survival was at
stake.
   ``Let us do nothing that would jeopardize the future of our
organization,'' he told the more than 1,000 delegates crowding the
assembly hall of the Palais des Nations, the U.N. Office in Geneva.
   The World Health Organization, a specialized U.N. agency, began
operating in 1948 with its declared purpose to aid in ``the
attainment by all peoples of the highest possible levels of
health.''
</TEXT>
