<FIRST>u a AM-Goddard-Discrimination 1stLd-Writethru a 05-12 0554</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Goddard-Discrimination, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0701,0566</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jury Finds Discrimination By Goddard College</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to UPDATE with verdict, comments. Picks
up 8th graf pvs, ``Goddard, a ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MEG DENNISON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTPELIER, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury found Friday that Goddard College
discriminated against a black woman by barring her from a
conference on racism.
   The jury awarded Patricia Lewis $102,000 in damages.
   ``I think the fact that it was an all-white jury didn't
matter,'' said Neil Mickenberg, one of Lewis' attorneys. ``We
proved our case.''
   Lewis, 27, sued the college alleging she was barred from a
three-session workshop on racism, which was targeted at white
women. She said the incident caused her such turmoil as a student
that she had to leave school and has been unable to return.
   ``What we have here is a much more modern form of racial
discrimination that doesn't break your bones, doesn't leave
scars,'' said Frank Kochman, an attorney for Lewis, during Friday's
closing arguments. ``All it does is enter your mind and eat up your
soul.''
   The lawsuit sought $175,000 in damages for her lost wages as a
teacher, which was her initial career goal, and for emotional
distress.
   ``I left Goddard College because I was discriminated against,''
Lewis testified Thursday.
   But a lawyer for Goddard, Charles Hurt, contended in closing
arguments Friday that the case was not related to racial
discrimination, and that Lewis left school for reasons other than
the conference.
   ``It's hard to believe that that would be enough to drop out of
school and interrupt her career that was so important to her,''
Hurt said, suggesting that while Lewis may have been upset, it
didn't make her leave school.
   Hurt could not be reached for comment immediately following the
verdict.
   Goddard, a small, private alternative school in Plainfield,
works hard to educate its students against racism, which was one
reason for the conference, he said.
   During the four-day trial, jurors heard from faculty and staff
at the college, as well as Lewis' psychologist and other experts
who testified about the feelings and experiences of black students
on predominately white campuses. When the incident occurred in
1984, Lewis was one of three black students at Goddard. Fewer than
1,500 blacks live in Vermont.
   Kochman also argued that Goddard had admitted discrimination in
various letters after the incident and in its original response to
the lawsuit.
   ``What are they apologizing for if they didn't do anything
wrong? Nobody does that,'' Kochman said, urging jurors to review
letters from college President Jack Lindquist and others involved.
   In his instructions, Judge Matthew Katz said jurors must first
determine whether Lewis was excluded from the conference, and
second whether that caused her harm.
   Nicola Morris, the Goddard faculty adviser running the
conference ``Moon Over Vermont,'' testified during the trial that
Lewis expressed concern at the time that the group was ``somehow
being Ku Klux Klan.''
   Morris also said that she initially invited the sophomore to
participate in either the workshops or the planning. ``It is
absolutely clear in my mind that she did not want to be included in
the anti-racism conference,'' she said.
   But Lewis testified, ``(Morris) never invited me to the
conference.'' She said Morris asked her to leave when she had
confronted members attending the final workshop.
</TEXT>
