<FIRST>r a AM-WhitleyFuneral     05-12 0460</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Whitley Funeral,0478</SECOND>
<HEAD>Singer Eulogized By Friend Ricky Skaggs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE EDWARDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Country music singer Ricky Skaggs
tearfully eulogized fellow performer Keith Whitley on Friday by
imploring those with personal problems to seek help.
   Whitley, 33, one of country music's most promising entertainers,
was found dead of an accidental alcohol overdose Tuesday at his
suburban home.
   Skaggs, who played in Kentucky bluegrass bands with Whitley when
both were teen-agers, fought back tears as he eulogized his
longtime friend before more than 500 mourners.
   ``If any of you have a drinking problem or a drug problem or an
emotional problem, please go get help,'' Skaggs told those who
packed in St. Joseph Church.
   ``There's one person who can help: Jesus,'' Skaggs said. ``Keith
would say the same thing.
   ``I've lost so many friends,'' he added.
   Skaggs also sang a 10-minute medley of Whitley's favorite
gospel-bluegrass songs, including ``White Dove,'' ``The Fields Have
Turned Brown'' and ``Drifting Too Far From the Shore.''
   ``It's not easy for me to stand here and talk about my friend,''
he said as many in the church wept audibly. ``I love him so much.
   ``We loved music and we loved our families and we loved each
other.
   ``God is so good. This (funeral) is not about death but about
life.''
   Among those at the funeral were Duane Allen of the Oak Ridge
Boys, Jack Greene, Billy Walker and Vic Willis of the Grand Ole
Opry and country music performers John Hartford, Paul Overstreet
and David Frizzell.
   Some mourners arrived an hour before the 50-minute service.
Those who came late were forced to sit in a side room adjoining the
sanctuary.
   The Rev. Pat Kibby of St. Joseph's Roman Catholic Church talked
about Whitley's recent No. 1 hit record, ``I'm No Stranger to the
Rain.''
   ``None of us are strangers to the rain,'' he said about life's
setbacks. ``We get tossed and shoved about by things we can not
control.''
   He encouraged the mourners not to regard Whitley as gone.
   ``He is not dead; his life hasn't ended, only changed. He now
lives an eternal life.''
   An autopsy performed the day Whitley died showed his body
contained a blood alcohol level of 0.47. A 0.30 level is considered
lethal.
   Traces of cocaine and a tranquilizer also were found in his
body, but death was attributed to the alcohol.
   Whitley, a native of Sandy Hook, Ky., had three No. 1 records
during the past eight months: ``I'm No Stranger to the Rain,''
``Don't Close Your Eyes'' and ``When You Say Nothing at All.''
   His widow, Lorrie Morgan, is a regular country music singer on
the Grand Ole Opry. She is scheduled to perform on the live country
music show Saturday night.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
