<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     05-12 0523</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0537</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thunderstorms Hit The Plains, Flooding in Maine</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Showers and thunderstorms stretched across the Great Plains on
Friday, while heavy rains washed out roads and forced school
closures in Maine where residents braced for flooding along major
rivers.
   Record low temperatures, meanwhile, occurred Friday morning from
Missouri to Florida.
   Southerly winds spread showers and thunderstorms from eastern
portions of Texas and Oklahoma across central Kansas and central
Nebraska to portions of South Dakota and Wyoming.
   In Oklahoma, overnight rainfall from 1{ inches to 2 inches was
reported at Hobart and Fort Sill. Thunderstorms produced half-inch
hail at Laramie, Wyo., at midday.
   A low pressure system centered over New York and Pennsylvania
caused scattered areas of rain to fall from the upper Ohio Valley
and lower Michigan into New England.
   Heavy rainfall continued to plague Maine. Twenty-four hour
rainfall as of 2 p.m. EDT included about four inches at Portland
and Rumford.
   Some roads have been washed out in southwest Maine, where the
Presumpscot River was expected to reach all-time record levels. The
swift river was 2{ feet above flood stage Friday morning and rising
rapidly.
   A flood warning was also posted for the Kennebec, Androscoggin
and Saco rivers. Most major rivers were expected to crest between 6
a.m. and 3 p.m. Saturday.
   Schools in several areas were closed for the day and some
classes were dismissed early because of the worsening road
conditions.
   A low pressure system over Utah caused inclement weather in
parts of the West, with snow falling in central and western
Montana, the Yellowstone area of Wyoming and southeast Idaho. Four
inches of snow fell at Red Lodge, Mont.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 34
degrees at Lewistown, Mont., to 90 degrees at Miami, Fla.
   Miami had a record high temperature on Thursday and a record low
of 65 Friday morning. In the afternoon, the temperature climbed
back up to 91 degrees and surpassed the high mark of 90 degrees set
for May 12 in 1985.
   Other record Florida lows were in Fort Lauderdale (60 degrees;
61 in 1953); Hollywood (55 degrees; 65 in 1963); Miami Beach (65
degrees; 65 in 1944). Also registering record lows for the date
were Montgomery, Ala. (43 degrees; 45 in 1952); and Kansas City,
Mo. (40 degrees; 41 in 1979).
   Saturday's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms across
much of the Great Plains and into portions of Missouri, Arkansas
and Louisiana; widely scattered showers and thunderstorms from the
northern and central Rockies into portions of the intermountain
region; and showers from the Great Lakes region and upper Ohio
Valley across the northern and central Appalachians to the northern
and middle Atlantic Coast. Showers will be most numerous over New
England, and from the eastern Great Lakes to the central
Appalachians.
   High temperatures were expected in the 50s in portions of the
intermountain region, across much of Montana and Wyoming, the
central Appalachians and in portions of Maine; in the 80s from the
desert Southwest across most of Texas and the Gulf Coast region to
Florida; and in the 60s and 70s elsewhere.
</TEXT>
