<FIRST>r i AM-Salvador     05-12 0237</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salvador,0245</SECOND>
<HEAD>Army Disbands Civil Defense Unit Amid Death-Squad Concern</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The army announced the
disbanding Friday of a civil defense unit organized by rightists in
two wealthy neighborhoods. President Jose Napoleon Duarte had
expressed fear the organization could produce death squads.
   Gen. Eugenio Vides Casanova, the minister of defense, announced
the dissolution of the 40-man group that he said had been formed in
the capital ``with completely good intentions.''
   Members of the unit took a loyalty oath last week and were given
some military instructions at the downtown headquarters of the 1st
Army Brigade.
   Col. Rene Emilio Ponce, head of the joint chiefs of staff, told
reporters Thursday the group would be under army supervision and
deal primarily with ``intelligence work.''
   The unit was disbanded ``because of the misunderstanding of its
function on the part of government authorities and the church,''
Vides said during a ceremony dedicating a new military hospital.
   Duarte said Thursday that ``to see these people, who talk about
killing, in uniform and with rifles, this could generate structures
of death squads. The whole country should be worried about this
kind of thing.''
   Human rights organizations blame military-linked rightist death
squads for thousands of abductions and killings of suspected
leftists during the early 1980s.
   Most of the estimated 70,000 people who have been killed in El
Salvador's nine-year war between government forces and left-wing
guerrillas were civilians.
</TEXT>
