<FIRST>r i AM-Romania     05-12 0400</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Romania,0413</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ceausescu Attacks Communist Reforms</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Nicolae Ceausescu of Romania on
Friday strongly attacked reforms in the Soviet bloc and made plain
he did not intend to adopt similar policies, a report from the
state news agency Agerpres said.
   The report, monitored in Vienna, indicated that Ceausescu did
not name the Soviet Union, Hungary or Poland as countries adopting
far-reaching reforms of the Stalinist system.
   But Agerpres quoted the leader of communist Romania as telling
Communist Party members Friday in Drobeta-Turnu Severin, on the
Yugoslav border:
   ``I would like to tell some circles abroad which try to minimize
the realities of socialism ... that Romania through everything it
has achieved proves there can be no way back, that in no way can
the wonderful industrial, agricultural, social constructions be
privatized, to resort to a set phrase very much used today which
actually means a return to capitalism.
   ``For Romania, capitalism fell forever. There is only one way _
to advance on the revolutionary path of the Communist Party toward
socialism, toward communism.
   ``The building of communism cannot be achieved through
reformism, but through revolutionary fight.''
   The ruling Communist parties have adopted reforms in the Soviet
Union, Poland and Hungary that grant the private economy some role
in the overall national economy.
   Bulgaria also has gone some way to reform its centrally planned
economy.
   But in Romania, East Germany and Czechoslovakia, the Communist
leaderships have either rejected the need for change or adopted
cautious economic reforms.
   Ceausescu is to visit Czechoslovakia within days, according to
Prague's state-run media. His visit follows closely a trip to
Prague by East German leader Erich Honecker that ended with
declarations of unity on both sides.
   Elsewhere in his speech, Ceausescu was quoted as saying he
advocates a speedy reduction of short-range nuclear weapons in
Europe and wants talks for complete abolition of such weapons.
   The West German news magazine Der Spiegel said this week that
Romania now has the ability to make medium-range nuclear rockets
through the sale of Western missile launcher technology.
   Ceausescu said last month that Romania can make nuclear arms but
has not done so out of concern for world peace.
   Some Western analysts doubt the claim since Romania is still
apparently unable to complete its first nuclear power plant at
Cernavoda on the Danube River. Most technology for the plant was
imported from the West.
</TEXT>
