<FIRST>r i AM-Greece-Scandal     05-12 0453</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Greece-Scandal,0471</SECOND>
<HEAD>Parliament Closed Before Committee Issues Scandal Report</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Premier Andreas Papandreou on Friday
decreed the end of Parliament's session, stifling a committee's
report on the multimillion-dollar scandal that has shaken his
Socialist government.
   Papandreou and President Christos Sartzetakis signed the order
terminating the current Parliament's final legislative session.
   The 300-member, single-chamber Parliament had been scheduled to
meet through May, closing 16 days before the June 18 general
elections.
   The closing was proposed earlier this week by the conservative
New Democracy Party, the main opposition party, which noted most
deputies were out campaigning and wouldn't attend the sessions.
   But the party leader, Constantine Mitsotakis, had asked that
Parliament reconvene on May 18 when the committee was to submit a
report on the scandal involving fugitive banker George Koskotas.
   Under the closure order Parliament cannot be reconvened.
   ``We have to decide that with the closure of Parliament our
committee ceases to function, since whatever action we take has no
substance,'' said Dimitris Pagoropoulos, chairman of the 30-member
panel. He is a member of Papandreou's Panhellenic Socialist
Movement, which dominated the committee.
   New Democracy Deputy Dyonisios Bouloukos, a committee member,
said the legislature was closed ``to avoid the drafting and
submission of the report to Parliament.''
   The government said it ended the session in response to the
conservatives' request.
   The investigative committee was set up in November when Koskotas
fled Greece after being indicted in a $200 million fraud, forgery
and embezzlement scandal.
   He was arrested in the United States and is jailed in Salem,
Mass., awaiting an extradition hearing.
   In interviews at the jail, Koskotas claimed Papandreou and other
officials in his party received millions of dollars in payoffs and
authorized the looting of the Bank of Crete while Koskotas was its
chairman.
   Many people mentioned by Koskotas had been questioned by the
committee.
   In another development, a man accused of receiving money stolen
from the Bank of Crete was released on bail Friday for health
reasons, according to a court official.
   He said George Louvaris, a close friend of Papandreou, submitted
bail of $330,000. He was released on the conditions he not leave
the country and that he report to a police station every 10 days.
   Louvaris was jailed April 12 and is awaiting trial. Shorty after
his imprisonment he was transferred to an Athens hospital for
treatment of multiple sclerosis.
   A district attorney filed charges against Louvaris in February
after three of Koskotas' former bodyguards testified that they had
delivered boxes of money to Louvaris at his Athens home.
   Koskotas, in interviews in the United States, claimed Louvaris
was a middleman for payoffs to Socialist officials.
   Louvaris and Papandreou have denied any involvement in the bank
scandal.
</TEXT>
