<FIRST>u a AM-MurderLetter-Acquaintances     05-12 0586</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Murder Letter-Acquaintances,0606</SECOND>
<HEAD>Acquaintances Of Murder Suspect Mystified By Hit List</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Murder Letter, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JONATHAN YENKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Schoolmates of 30 years ago were stunned to
learn they may have been on a list of names to be ``punished'' by
David Schoenecker, who allegedly confessed to the killing of his
wife in a newspaper letter.
   ``I would have never guessed,'' said Lee Borowski, who played on
the basketball team with with Schoenecker at Custer High School.
``He was intense. But he was a happy-go-lucky guy.''
   Schoenecker was arrested near the Idaho-Montana border Friday,
the day after a newspaper columnist in Anaheim, Calif., received a
letter allegedly written by Schoenecker saying he had killed his
wife, Gail, last week in their California home.
   The letter also warned about a list of people who would be
``punished.'' When authorities found the woman's body, they
discovered a list of 54 names, many who are relatives or
acquaintances of Schoenecker living in the Milwaukee area.
   Some of those on the list were people he knew in high school,
police said.
   ``I gave him good grades _ so I hope he's not after me,'' said
William Van Valzah, an instructor at Custer High who taught
architectural drafting to Schoenecker. ``He was a doer, he wasn't a
bragger. He always worked to the best of his ability.''
   Schoenecker, 48, graduated from Custer High in 1959. He was the
senior class president, and among his activities were football,
basketball, track, the math club and the German club.
   Schoenecker's 1959 yearbook describes how he was a star football
player. ``He was an individual who performed well,'' said Richard
Hinchcliffe, a guidance counselor at the school who was an
assistant coach on the football team. ``He was a pleasure to
coach.''
   Two of the people on the hit list live in Wauwatosa, a suburb of
Milwaukee.
   ``They were surprised they were among the select few,'' said
police Lt. Greg Naumann, who did not disclose the names. ``There
was no rhyme or reason to it.''
   Naumann said the people described themselves as acquaintances of
Schoenecker, but not close friends.
   The list also included Schoenecker's ex-wife, Kathy Schoenecker,
who has remarried.
   ``He is absolutely not a violent person,'' she told The
Milwaukee Journal. ``He's a super-intelligent person, loves
attention.''
   David and Gail Schoenecker moved to Anaheim about two years ago,
where Mrs. Schoenecker worked as an elementary school teacher.
   Schoenecker worked as a chemical engineer for Johnson Controls
Inc., based in Milwaukee, and was eventually transferred to
California.
   Schoenecker's letter to an Orange County Register columnist said
he killed his wife because she didn't understand the premonitions
and ``images'' he had about people who had ``done wrong or evil''
against him.
   The Schoenecker neighbors in Anaheim described the couple as
reclusive and withdrawn.
   ``It was like they didn't exist,'' said neighbor David Burgin.
``Everybody in the neighborhood has kids and we are all very close.
But they just aren't part of that. The house always sits there like
it's empty. Here it's been a whole week but nobody noticed anything
wrong.''
   The couple's next door neighbor in Anaheim, Elizabeth Kish, said
she heard occasional arguments.
   ``I would hear them yelling at each other, although I don't know
what the arguments were about. I have sometimes heard her crying,''
she said.
   Nilsa Hernandez-Bakula, who taught with Mrs. Schoenecker at St.
Thomas Aquinas School in Milwaukee in 1981, said: ``She was always
citing (David's) immaturity. He was having problems holding a job.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
