<FIRST>r i AM-Panama-Reax     05-12 0504</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Panama-Reax,0518</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nicaragua, Soviets Denounce U.S. Troop Additions</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Panama, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Nicaragua and the Soviet Union on Friday denounced President
Bush's decision to send more U.S. troops to Panama, with Nicaraguan
President Daniel Ortega calling the action illegal.
   Vadim Perfiliev, a Soviet Foreign Ministry spokesman, told
reporters in Moscow the Panamanian situation was marred by U.S.
interference.
   ``It is a matter for the Panamanian people themselves to clear
up the situation and break the deadlock,'' he said. ``Any outside
interference is only exacerbating the already very serious
situation.''
   Perfiliev said it was vital to avoid creating ``another hotbed
of international tension.''
   The Soviet government newspaper Izvestia said Friday the
Panamanian government, controlled by Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega,
should try to reach a compromise with the opposition but it did not
make any suggestions.
   Ortega, speaking at a news conference in Dublin, Ireland at the
end of a 10-nation tour of Europe, said, ``What the Bush
administration has done is absolutely illegal under the U.N.
Charter.''
   ``It is absolutely inadmissible for the United States to resort
to the use or threat of use of force,'' he added. ``We can
guarantee that no Latin American is going to defend the U.S. use of
force or threat of the use of force in Panama.''
   Ortega claimed the United States spent millions of dollars to
destablize Panama's election. ``The United States had said even
before the elections took place that it would not respect the
results,'' he said. ``This has led us to a crisis which as Latin
Americans must concern us.''
   ``If foreign support is required for Panama, let it come from
within Latin American countries, but always within the framework of
international law,'' Ortega said.
   Barricada, the newspaper of Nicaragua's ruling Sandinistas, said
Friday Bush's decision to reinforce the U.S. troops in Panama means
the United States hopes to renege on the agreement to relinquish
the Panama Canal at the end of the century.
   The Managua newspaper said the Bush administration is seeking
``to recover perpetual rights over the canal and assure its control
over the hemisphere.''
   It quoted officials as saying the Sandinista army remained in a
state of combat alert to repel any possible U.S. military
intervention in Central America. Reporters in Managua said no
unusual military activity was apparent.
   In Japan, the Foreign Ministry said the government ``has been
deeply concerned with reports indicating various injustices in the
Panamanian presidential and other elections on May 7.''
   A statement said the government ``strongly deplores'' the
attacks against opposition candidates and such conduct is
inexcusable in international society.
   Commenting on the Panamanian Electoral Tribunal's action
Wednesday nullifying the election, the ministry said that although
it was a domestic issue ``the decision is totally regrettable.''
   ``The Panamanian people have the right to decide on the future
of the country,'' it said. ``Japan strongly calls upon the
government of Panama to respect the general will of its people and
hopes that political stability in Panama will be established as
soon as possible.''
</TEXT>
