<FIRST>u a AM-SecondAbduction 1stLd-Writethru a0686 05-12 0642</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Second Abduction, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0686,0654</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mother, Suspect in Second Daughter's Death; Charged in 1986 Case</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBs grafs 5-9, `An arrest ..., with 6 grafs to UPDATE with
Paula Sims surrendering, pleading innocent, released on bond, comments
by prosecutor and sheriff. Picks up 10th graf pvs: `The decomposed ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL DE LA GARZA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERSEYVILLE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mother was charged Friday with
concealing a homicide and obstructing justice in the 1986 death of
her firstborn daughter, as authorities try to unravel the mystery
of her second baby's slaying two weeks ago.
   Paula Sims, 29, and her husband, Robert, reported each of the
baby girls abducted by a masked gunman who threatened Mrs. Sims and
took the infants while Sims was at work.
   Authorities have considered them suspects in both deaths. No
charges have been filed in the latest case.
   Jersey County State's Attorney Richard J. Ringhausen signed a
criminal complaint Friday alleging one count of concealing a
homicide and three counts of obstructing justice in the death three
years ago of 13-day-old Loralei Sims, said Linda Long, chief deputy
court clerk.
   Mrs. Sims turned herself to county authorities a few hours after
charges were filed. She was arrested and then released on 10
percent of a $100,000 bond, covered with a cashier's check signed
by her father.
   She was accompanied by her attorney, Donald Groshong, who
entered a plea of innocent on all charges. Groshong demanded access
to all information gathered by the state.
   Neither Mrs. Sims nor her attorney had any comment, although
Groshong has said previously the couple is innocent of any
wrongdoing.
   Sims was not named in the complaint, which says Mrs. Sims knew
Loralei had died ``by homicidal means'' and gave false information
to county Sheriff Frank Yocom and state police investigators.
   At a news conference, Ringhausen said the charges were prompted
by concerns that the three-year statute of limitations on the
charges was about to run out. The statute does not apply to murder
cases.
   ``Certainly it has been on my mind a long time,'' said county
Sheriff Frank Yocom, the chief investigator. ``Indeed I've said for
a long time I want to see this cleared.''
   The charges are the first in the case, which began June 17,
1986, when the Simses told police that a masked gunman broke into
their home and abducted Loralei.
   The decomposed remains of a baby, believed to be Loralei, were
found several days later following an intensive search near the
couple's home in Brighton, a rural Jersey County community.
   The Simses refused to answer questions before the grand jury
that considered the case in early 1987, citing their Fifth
Amendment protection against self-incrimination. The panel took no
action.
   Mrs. Sims appeared Thursday before a grand jury in Madison
County, where the couple have since moved. That jury is hearing
evidence in the death of the Simses' 6-week-old second baby girl,
Heather Lee. Mrs. Sims' parents and her husband's sister and
brother-in-law also were subpoenaed.
   Sims, 37, was not asked to appear. Police have said he told them
he believes his wife may have killed their daughters accidentally.
   On April 29, the couple reported that Heather Lee was abducted
from the family's new home in Alton, about 10 miles from Brighton.
   Her body was found in a trash barrel May 3 across the
Mississippi River in West Alton, Mo. An autopsy showed she was
smothered by someone putting a hand over her mouth. Tests also
indicated that the body had been frozen.
   The family buried Heather on Wednesday next to the unmarked
grave containing the remains believed to be Loralei's.
   The couple also have a son, 15-month-old Randy, who was removed
to state custody last week. Witnesses have said Mrs. Sims wanted a
son and was unhappy at the births of her daughters.
</TEXT>
