<FIRST>r i AM-Flight103     05-12 0260</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Flight 103,0264</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.N. Man's Suitcase Still Seen As Possible Air Bomb</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four months after the Pan Am Flight 103 bombing,
the FBI is still inquiring about the suitcase carried by one
victim, Bernt Carlsson, the United Nations commissioner for
Namibia, a news report said Saturday.
   The London newspaper The Independent said it was clear from
conversations with Carlsson's family and friends that investigators
have not ruled out the possibility that he was the unwitting
carrier of the bomb.
   The paper said it had never been suggested Carlsson was the
target of the bomb. But it said Carlsson's sister, Inger, recently
reported that FBI investigators asked her to describe his suitcase,
and on Friday the FBI interviewed a woman ``with whom Carlsson had
been living.''
   Other reports have said the FBI and the CIA concluded the
bombing was done by the Popular Front for the Liberation of
Palestine-General Command at Iran's behest. Some speculated that a
U.S. student who had an Arab boyfriend may have been tricked into
bringing the device on board.
   New York-bound Flight 103 blew up over Lockerbie, Scotland last
Dec. 21, killing all 259 people aboard and 11 on the ground. The
flight originated in Frankfurt, West Germany, changing planes at
London's Heathrow airport.
   Investigators say a bomb in a portable radio in the hold
destroyed the plane. The crime is still under investigation.
   The Independent said that since Carlsson traveled business
class, his suitcase would have been loaded in a forward bay of
Flight 103 where investigators say the bomb exploded.
</TEXT>
