<FILEID>AP-NR-05-12-89 2329EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-UN-Somalia     05-12 0352</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-Somalia,0364</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.N. Prepares Program to Aid Somalia War Victims</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar
on Friday announced a $19.4 million emergency aid program for a
million people in Somalia driven from their homes by war and
rebellion.
   The United Nations approved the program after Somalia adopted
political reforms. The West has criticized the East African nation
over its tactics in fighting a rebellion by the Somali National
Movement.
   The government of President Mohammed Siad Barre has been
battling the insurrection in the north for the last seven years.
   Somalia's 5.3 million people live in one of the poorest nations
in the world.
   The office of the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees
temporarily withheld food aid this year because it feared Somalia
was drafting Ethiopian refugees into its army to fight the
insurgents.
   Amnesty International and other human rights groups accused
Somalia of widespread arrests, detentions and sanctioning summary
executions last year in an attempt to crush the Ethiopia-based
rebels.
   A U.N. mission to Somalia from Feb. 25 to March 12 found ``the
constitution has been amended to include the principle of habeas
corpus. A general amnesty has been proclaimed and many political
detainees have been released,''said a U.N. statement.
   The director of the U.N.'s Office of Emergency Operations,
Charles-Henri La Muniere, has said more than 600,000 people are
living in camps and 400,000 are scattered throughout Somalia
because of attacks on towns and villages.
   In addition to shipping 7,290 tons of food, the program proposes
to rebuild water systems, restore hospitals and basic health care,
and rehabilitate war-damaged areas.
   Ethiopia and Somalia went to war in 1977 for control of the
Ogaden region, leading to hundreds of thousands of Somali and
Ethiopian rerfugees. A treaty last year formally ended the conflict.
   About 70,000 Somalis are displaced in their own nation.
   Somalia receives U.S. aid because of agreements under which the
U.S. military may use Somali bases in the event of Mideast conflict.
   The United States already has a large naval base at Berbera,
Somalia, on the Gulf of Aden.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890512-0220 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-12-89 2332EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-AIDSRent     05-12 0219</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AIDS Rent,0225</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rent Hike Compromise Proposed for Subsidized AIDS Victims</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   People with AIDS who are living in
city-sponsored apartments may have their rent raised from 25
percent of their stipends to 30 percent, the city said Friday.
   The proposed increase would initially affect only about 20
people who have AIDS and live in city-sponsored apartments, said
Lee Jones, a mayoral spokesman. More people would be affected as
additional apartments are readied.
   The proposal was disclosed after City Council President Andrew
Stein criticized an earlier proposal to raise the amount to 40
percent.
   ``People with AIDS are barely able to survive under the current
formula,'' Stein said in letters to city Human Resources
Administrator William Grinker and Budget Director Paul Dickstein.
   ``It is unjust for your office to now institute a policy
compelling these individuals to hand over almost half of their
monthly check,'' he wrote.
   Grinker and Dickstein replied that, given the current
Supplemental Security Income each person with AIDS gets per month,
the increase to 30 percent will leave them with $312 to spend for
other needs.
   They said it costs the city about $1,500 a month to support each
apartment because of social-support services provided.
   The proposed increase will be included in the mayor's fiscal
1990 budget proposal, due next week.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
