<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     05-12 0795</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0836</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Retail sales rose by a lackluster 0.4 percent
in April, the government said in a report cited by analysts as
evidence that higher interest rates are taking a toll on economic
growth.
   The Commerce Department said Thursday sales climbed to a
seasonally adjusted $139.9 billion last month after remaining flat
in March and falling 0.4 percent in February.
   Economists had expected a much stronger rebound in April,
anticipating a surge of between 1 percent and 2 percent on the
strength of higher auto sales.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Depositors withdrew a net $8.5 billion from
the nation's savings and loans in March, the government says. The
outflow was more than $2 billion below January's record, but still
considered very large.
   The Federal Home Loan Bank Board said Thursday the March outflow
compared with $9.2 billion in February and a record $10.8 billion
in January. It was the 11th month of withdrawals in a row and the
fifth of withdrawals in excess of $7 billion.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Arthur Levitt Jr. said he was resigning as
chairman of the American Stock Exchange after 11 years at the
nation's third-largest stock market, which has attempted to stem
the loss of business to its bigger Wall Street peers by expanding
into innovative new securities.
   Levitt, 58, said Thursday he would remain at the exchange until
a successor was named. He said he plans to build his 3-year-old
Levitt Communications Inc. into a larger publishing company.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate and House negotiators agreed on a $1.17
trillion budget for fiscal 1990.
   The spending plan constrains the Pentagon, treats many domestic
programs generously and leaves many prickly decisions for later.
Both houses are expected to give final approval to the document
next week.
   Bargainers from the House and Senate agreed to the document
Thursday on only their second day of public meetings.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Exxon Corp. said it would go along with many of
the changes some of its shareholders suggested to better prepare
for future environmental disasters in the wake of its Alaskan oil
spill.
   Exxon said Thursday it will recommend its board of directors
approve setting up a new committee to review corporate policies and
programs related to worker safety and the environment.
   In addition, Exxon said it would consider spending more money on
environmental research and pollution prevention. About $5.5 billion
has been spent in that area from 1970 to 1988, it said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Amway Corp. plans to spin off Avon Products
Inc.'s retail operation, comprising the popular Giorgio perfume and
other fragrances, if its $2 billion-plus takeover bid for Avon
succeeds.
   Amway disclosed the plan in a document submitted to the
Securities and Exchange Commission. It said it would retain Avon's
worldwide direct selling division if acquires its much larger rival.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House has voted in favor of raising the
minimum wage to $4.55 an hour by October 1991, leaving only a final
Senate vote before the bill goes to President Bush, who has
promised to veto it.
   Bush insists that the minimum should be raised only to $4.25 by
January 1992 _ and then only if the proposal allows employers to
pay a lower ``training wage'' to new workers for six months.
   The minimum is now $3.35, where it has been since 1981.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate Foreign Relations Committee voted
narrowly to approve the $7 billion FSX deal involving joint
U.S.-Japanese development and production of a next-generation
fighter for Japan.
   On a 9-8 vote, the committee Thursday rejected a resolution to
disapprove the deal, which has generated sharp criticism on Capitol
Hill over technology and economic issues.
   Action then shifted to the Senate floor, where FSX opponents
voiced hope they would still be able to muster majority support for
the disapproval resolution.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A generic-drug company executive accused the
Food and Drug Administration of holding up approvals of its
products to retaliate against the firm for having sparked an
investigation into alleged bribery at the agency.
   Roy McKnight, chairman of Mylan Laboratories in Pittsburgh, told
a House subcommittee the company has met all the regulatory
requirements for approval to make a number of drugs at its new
Puerto Rico plant, drugs for which Mylan has approval to make at
other plants.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices rose slightly Thursday in restrained trading that
reflected uncertainties over news from Panama, the progress of a
Treasury debt auction and an upcoming report on inflation. The Dow
Jones average of 30 industrials rose 8.43 to 2,382.88.
   Bond prices rose following three days of declines. The dollar
also gained.
   Crude oil futures climbed back above $20 a barrel.
</TEXT>
