<FILEID>AP-NR-05-12-89 0112EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-AmexResignation Bjt   05-12 0657</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Amex Resignation, Bjt,0681</SECOND>
<HEAD>American Stock Exchange Chairman To Step Down</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY52 of May 11</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of the American Stock Exchange says
he will leave the nation's third-largest stock market ``stronger
than ever'' when he steps down to try to build a large
communications company.
   Arthur Levitt Jr. announced Thursday he was resigning after 11
years at the exchange, which has attempted to stem the loss of
business to its bigger Wall Street competitors by expanding into
innovative new securities.
   Levitt, 58, said he would remain at the exchange until a
successor was named and that a search committee had been formed. He
said he plans to expand his three-year-old Levitt Communications
Inc.
   ``I believe the American Exchange today is stronger than ever in
its history,'' Levitt told a news conference at the exchange in
Lower Manhattan. ``I believe the staff is better, the quality of
listed companies is stronger.''
   The Amex, which caters to medium-sized companies, is far
outpaced in volume by the New York Stock Exchange and the National
Association of Securities Dealers' over-the-counter market traded
electronically nationwide.
   The Amex grew from an average daily volume of 3.9 million shares
traded when Levitt took over in 1978 to 9.94 million shares last
year, but the number of companies traded has fallen from 1,004 to
895 currently.
   The exchange dates to the 1790s, when its brokers traded
unlisted securities on the streets of lower Manhattan while others
moved indoors. It was known as the New York Curb Exchange until
1953, when its present name was adopted.
   Levitt said he would enlarge Levitt Communications, which has
revenue of about $16 million and owns 33-year-old Roll Call, a
twice-weekly Washington newspaper delivered to the White House and
98 percent of the nation's congressmen.
   The company in April agreed to acquire B&amp;B Enterprises Inc.,
which owns the publisher of Stagebill, a magazine distributed at
performing arts centers in New York and Washington.
   Levitt, president of a Shearson Lehman Hutton predecessor,
Shearson Hayden Stone Inc., from 1969-78, said he planned other
media aquisitions, and ``quite possibly'' would seek to enter daily
print journalism.
   ``Art has been doing this for 11 years. I think he's
accomplished the goals he set out for himself,'' said Jeffrey B.
Lane, an Amex board member and president of Shearson Lehman Hutton
Inc.. ``I think he's leaving the exchange in a strong position.''
   A search committee composed of present and former exchange board
members will choose a successor to Levitt.
   Under Levitt, the Amex introduced index options, including one
based on an index of foreign stocks that begins trading Friday. The
Securities and Exchange Commission also has approved plans for the
trading of so-called ``baskets'' of stocks on the Amex.
   The exchange undertook the options innovations to give the
exchange another avenue of business, although industry observers
say Amex remains far behind the Chicago Board of Options in that
area.
   ``I think we have carved out a very specific place in the U.S.
for emerging growth companies, the mid-range companies,'' Levitt
said.
   Average daily trading volume of the Amex's 895 listed companies
was 11.49 million shares in April. Average daily volume is 161.9
million shares for the NYSE's 1,680 listed companies and 133.3
million for about 5,080 issues traded on the national
over-the-counter market.
   The American exchange in 1988 reported net income of $2.6
million on revenue of $102.8 million, compared with profits of $8.3
million and revenue of $114.5 million in 1987, Amex's most
profitable year.
   ``The Amex always has had the difficulty of being the little
brother in the same city as the big brother,'' said Julius W.
Peake, who heads a capital markets consulting firm and studies the
nation's exchanges.
   ``It used to be considered the training ground for stocks that
were not yet qualified to make the Big Board. But in last 15 years
NASDAQ has dwarfed the Amex.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890512-0241 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-12-89 0137EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Dunkin'Donuts     05-12 0336</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dunkin' Donuts,0349</SECOND>
<HEAD>Company Ready to Fight Proposed Takeover</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHELLE LOCKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dunkin' Donuts has remained cool to the advances
of a Canadian suitor, saying it would review a request for a
meeting to discuss a $42-per-share, or $300 million, buyout offer.
   Kingsbridge Capital Group made its request for a meeting
Thursday in a letter to Dunkin' Donuts Chairman Robert M.
Rosenberg, indicating the Toronto company believes the profitable
Massachusetts business is worth the trip.
   ``A meeting would facilitate avoiding the unnecessary disruption
and expense that so frequently accompany a misunderstanding of
intentions,'' said the letter from Kingsbridge chairman George S.
Mann.
   Kingsbridge, the merchant banking arm of Unicorp Canada Corp.,
said in an earlier filing with the Federal Trade Commission it had
already bought 7.6 percent of stock in the doughnut maker, which
owns or franchises more than 1,780 shops and reported earnings of
$13.5 million on sales of $112.8 million last year.
   Dunkin' Donuts vice president Richard N. Hart Jr. said there was
little reaction to the letter.
   ``Mr. Rosenberg will review the letter with his board at some
point,'' Hart said.
   Dunkin' Donuts has implemented a shareholders' rights plan and
an employee stock ownership plan, both aimed at thwarting an
unfriendly takeover.
   Kingsbridge has said its options include buying more shares of
Dunkin' Donuts, proposing a merger, mounting a hostile takeover or
waging a proxy battle for control of the board.
   ``Hopefully, they'll agree to sit down at the table with us so
we can sort it out,'' said Eric W. Evans, a Kingsbridge spokesman.
   Dunkin' Donuts stock rose to $39.62{ a share Thursday on the
over-the-counter market, up from $34.75 Wednesday.
   ``They're involved and they obviously want to stay involved so
time will tell how serious they are,'' said Roger Lipton, an
analyst with Landenburg, Thalmann in New York who follows Dunkin'
Donuts.
   ``I think management's made it clear they're going to resist
strongly,'' Lipton said. ``Bob Rosenberg doesn't want to work for
someone else.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
