<DOCNO> AP890512-0242 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-12-89 0150EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-HayStocks     05-12 0494</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hay Stocks,0511</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iowa Hay Prices Soar While National Supply Plummets</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOINA CHIACU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farmers who ran out of hay to feed their
livestock during last summer's drought may face a more serious
shortage this summer, Iowa Secretary of Agriculture Dale M. Cochran
warns.
   ``The depletion of our hay stocks, combined with poor pasture
conditions, could lead to serious shortages of livestock feed this
summer,'' Cochran said Thursday.
   The nation's hay supply dropped by 10 million tons in 1989, and
severe drought-induced shortages in some Midwestern states have
caused Iowa hay prices to skyrocket, agriculture officials said.
   The nation's farmers had 17.63 million tons of hay on hand as of
May 1, 1989, down from 27.35 million tons at the same time in 1988,
according to figures released by the U.S. Agriculture Department.
   ``We had larger hay supplies on hand last year, but they were
quickly exhausted during the drought,'' Cochran said. ``Continued
dry weather may cause this year's smaller stocks to be depleted
much further.''
   Iowa's hay stock fared better than those of its neighboring
states, with 1.02 million tons on May 1, compared with 1.34 million
last year, the department said.
   ``Some neighboring states are down substantially and that is
putting a lot of pressure on hay prices in Iowa,'' said Bernie
Janssen of the Iowa Department of Agriculture. ``Drought-wise, they
ended up worse than we did.''
   Janssen said hay prices in Iowa soared to an average $96 a ton
as of mid-April, doubling from $48 in April 1988.
   Iowa's average hay price is much higher along the borders of
neighboring states such as South Dakota, Minnesota and Wisconsin,
where hay stocks were significantly depleted last year because of
the drought, Janssen said.
   Those states also didn't have as many setaside acres from
Conservation Reserve Programs on which to plant hay.
   ``They didn't produce a lot of hay last year and had to use up a
lot of the hay they had on hand,'' Janssen said.
   South Dakota's hay stocks plummeted 1.5 million tons _ from 2.77
million tons on May 1, 1988 to 1.17 million this spring. Minnesota
is down to 626,000 tons of hay on hand from 1.48 million tons last
year, while North Dakota dropped from 1.34 million in 1988 to
442,000 in 1989.
   Hay supplies in Wisconsin are down 1 million tons, falling to
887,000 tons.
   ``They're down a lot, so consequently if you're selling hay in
Iowa it has really helped keep Iowa hay prices up here,'' Janssen
said.
   He said the national hay stock figures this year included all 48
states in the continental United States, of which only 11 showed an
increase in hay stocks. Most of the increase was on eastern
seaboard states, he said.
   No 1989 production estimates for corn, soybeans and other major
spring-planted crops were included in Thursday's report. The USDA
will issue projections for those crops later in the growing season.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
