<FIRST>r f PM-CrashTests     05-12 0337</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Crash Tests,0354</SECOND>
<HEAD>NHTSA Releases New Crash-Test Results</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: also on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Drivers who crash in a Dodge Spirit 4-door
sedan have the least protection against head injuries among seven
vehicles tested so far this year, the National Highway Traffic
Safety Administration says.
   The cars were smashed at 35 mph into a fixed barrier, and the
resulting stresses were measured by sensors on human-shaped dummies
protected by seat belts or, when sold as standard equipment, air
bags.
   Stresses on the head were reported as an index referred to as
the head injury criterion.
   The crash test of the Spirit, which is in the large- and
mid-size car category, produced a head-injury criterion of 1,421 in
the driver's position, NHTSA said.
   The Spirit was the first 1989 model tested to exceed the maximum
head-injury criterion of 1,000 allowed by federal regulations in
the required 30 mph barrier crash. However, NHTSA's public testing
is performed at 35 mph, which produces higher results than the
mandatory test.
   Other new test results by weight class produced these driver
head-injury criteria:
   _Subcompact cars: Dodge Daytona 2-door hatchback, 399; Honda
Civic CRX 2-door hatchback, 750.
   _Large and mid-size cars: Ford Thunderbird 2-door, 541.
   NHTSA said the crash tests are the equivalent of a head-on
collision between two identical vehicles, each moving at 35 mph, or
between one vehicle moving at 70 mph and a parked vehicle.
   Small differences in test results shouldn't be considered
significant, NHTSA said. Only one vehicle of each type is tested,
and slight variations in construction or test conditions could
produce differing results in additional tests, the agency said.
   Previous test results, by weight class, were:
   _Subcompact: Mitsubishi Mirage 4-door sedan, 960.
   _Compact: Mitsubishi Galant 4-door sedan, 971.
   _Large and mid-size: Eagle Medallion 4-door sedan, 745.
   Automakers are required to crash-test their products for safety
certification under federal regulation, but the results are rarely
made public.
   NHTSA began its own assessment program for public release in
1979.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890512-0248 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-12-89 0747EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-OilSpillFund     05-12 0659</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Oil Spill Fund,0678</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Spill Prompts Congress to Revisit Government Cleanup Issue</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: also on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Alaska oil disaster is prompting Congress
to revisit an idea that has languished on Capitol Hill for 15
years: the creation of a government-controlled fund to pay for an
oil spill's devastation.
   The Bush administration on Thursday sent to a House panel a
proposal for a $500 million emergency fund to deal with oil spill
cleanup and recovery. The money would come from a 1.3-cent-a-barrel
fee on all domestic and imported petroleum.
   As Transportation Secretary Samuel Skinner explained the details
to members of the subcommittee on Coast Guard and navigation,
several panel members noted that the subject is far from new.
   Rep. Gerry Studds, D-Mass., pointed out that similar legislation
has been debated without attracting much interest in every Congress
since 1975. Three times bills cleared the House but not the Senate.
   ``I hope we're not going to reinvent the wheel. We've had
numerous hearings on this,'' said Rep. Donald Young, R-Alaska.
   But the spill of 11 million gallons of oil from the Exxon Valdez
tanker in Alaska's Prince William Sound on March 24 and the
problems that have surfaced since then in containing and cleaning
up the oil have virtually ensured that similar legislation will
pass this year, some congressmen suggested.
   ``It took a tragedy like the Exxon Valdez to cause the entire
Congress to focus on the issue,'' said Rep. Walter Jones, D-Okla.,
chairman of the Merchant Marine and Fisheries Committee.
   In addition to the administration bill, the House is considering
a slightly different measure sponsored by Jones that calls for a
$300 million cleanup fund.
   Some provisions of the administration bill likely will be
incorporated into Jones' bill, one congressional staffer said. A
subcommittee vote already is scheduled for later this month.
   The fund would be tapped only for costs beyond those for which
the company or shipper is directly liable. The administration's
legislation establishes a $78 million liability ceiling, while the
Jones bill sets a $60 million maximum.
   Legislation was introduced in the Senate on Wednesday by Sen.
Ted Stevens, R-Alaska, calling for creation of a $500 million
federal oil spill cleanup fund. It, too, would be financed through
a fee on domestic and imported oil.
   The Stevens legislation also would require the Coast Guard to
respond to a major oil spill and would give the Coast Guard access
to up to $150 million of the cleanup fund.
   In more than a dozen congressional hearings since the Exxon
Valdez spill, congressmen have bemoaned the lack of industry and
government preparedness to such an emergency.
   Skinner, who has been the Bush administration's point man on the
Alaska spill, said when the Exxon Valdez ran aground, the
government had only a few million dollars available in oil spill
recovery funds.
   Had that spill been caused by a company less well-to-do than the
Exxon Corp., the government would have had to scramble for funds
and ask Congress for tens of millions of dollars to get the cleanup
effort going, Skinner said.
   Estimates of the cost of the Exxon spill, the worst in U.S.
history, ranged from about $100 million to many times that amount.
   Skinner said it was too early to predict the eventual total.
Salaries for the thousands of workers cleaning the fouled Alaska
beaches alone run as high as $75,000 an hour for 20-hour work days,
Skinner said.
   ``The numbers are very big,'' he continued, indicating at one
point that even the proposed $500 million cleanup fund might have
been inadequate. He suggested that something in the range of ``$500
million to $1 billion should cover it.''
   The administration proposal would make $500 million available in
the event of another major spill, but Skinner said the president
would have the authority to exceed that amount. The government
could then seek additional fees from the industry.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
