<DOCNO> AP890512-0249 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-12-89 0750EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Apples-AlarBan     05-12 0402</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Apples-Alar Ban,0414</SECOND>
<HEAD>EPA Effort to Ban Alar, Once Launched, Could Take Three Years</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: also on general news wires.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It could take up to three years to implement a
ban on the apple-ripening agent Alar, even though the Environmental
Protection Agency expects to soon begin formal steps to prohibit
its use.
   ``We are going to do it. And shortly, probably within the next
10 days,'' EPA spokesman Albert Heier said Thursday.
   Consumer groups says the growth regulator presents a health
risk, especially to children, and the EPA has said ``inescapable''
laboratory evidence exists that Alar triggered cancerous tumors in
test mice.
   Nonetheless, the EPA, the Agriculture Department and the Food
and Drug Administration have all pronounced apples safe for
consumption. An estimated 5 percent of the crop is treated with
small amounts of Alar.
   The EPA, which previously said it could not justify an emergency
ban of Alar, announced in February that it planned within 90 days
to initiate more routine procedures to eliminate its use in the
future. That period elapsed without a formal rulemaking proposal.
   Processed Apples Institute, Inc., the trade organization
representing processors of apple products, urged an immediate
announcement by the EPA of its action toward a ban in hopes it will
send a ``loud and clear signal'' to dissuade growers from using the
chemical, even while it's legal. May is the month when many
orchards are sprayed.
   Public fears about the use of Alar by some growers have caused
the sales of apple products such as juice and sauce to drop off 20
percent from the same period last year, said Larry Davenport,
executive director of the institute.
   ``We know, and all federal government agencies have reaffirmed,
that apples and apple products are safe,'' said Davenport. ``But
with the public hysteria and misinformation surrounding this issue,
it has been difficult for makers of apple juices and sauces to get
the truth across about product safety.''
   He said processors have refused since 1986 to buy apples
containing Alar, although small amounts have slipped through the
screening process.
   The banning process that could take at least 15 months at best,
and up to three years if contested.
   Alar, the Uniroyal Chemical Co.'s marketing name for daminozide,
is an organic acid that helps keep apples on the tree until they
are ripe, and also keeps them red and crisp for a longer period
after harvest.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
