<DOCNO> AP890512-0250 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-12-89 0759EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-SeabrookLicense     05-12 0647</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Seabrook License,0666</SECOND>
<HEAD>Seabrook Foes Seek Low-Power Testing Ban From Court</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: also on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opponents of the $6 billion Seabrook nuclear
reactor are seeking an emergency court order barring low-power
atomic tests at the embattled New Hampshire plant.
   A request for an immediate stay to block a low-power license
pending further judicial review was filed at the U.S. Circuit Court
of Appeals here Thursday by Massachusetts, the town of Hampton,
N.H., the Seacoast Anti-Pollution League and the New England
Coalition on Nuclear Pollution.
   Seabrook opponents are anticipating that the Nuclear Regulatory
Commission will reject their pleas for a regulatory stay and issue
the license soon.
   Late Thursday, NRC counsel Gregory Alan Berry recommended that
the commissioners reject the stay request. That issue is the last
of a long series of regulatory obstacles that has held up the
license for three years.
   An emergency court order blocking the tests is critical to the
opponents' strategy of ensuring that the 1,150-megawatt reactor
never operates commercially. If the NRC grants the license and the
court refuses an emergency stay, Seabrook operators could start and
finish the low-power tests before the full appeal is heard by the
courts, rendering the case moot.
   ``Low-power operation can commence as soon as the license (is
issued). Therefore, absent a stay, low-power operation will
immediately cause severe environmental and financial harm to
residents of New Hampshire and Massachusetts,'' the opponents wrote
in a 77-page memorandum to the court.
   Seabrook officials have said they will begin low-power tests 10
days after the NRC authorizes operations, a move that could come as
early as Monday.
   The opponents asked the appeals court to rule on their emergency
stay request before Monday, but there was no indication when a
ruling would come, said Diane Curran, a Washington attorney
representing the New England Coalition on Nuclear Pollution.
   Massachusetts Deputy Attorney General Stephen A. Jonas said he
believes the NRC will not issue the license until the court rules.
   Low-power tests are a critical step toward commercial operation
for the plant, which New England utilities say is badly needed to
meet the region's energy needs into the 21st century.
   Seabrook critics, who believe the coastal towns near the plant
could never be safely evacuated, fear low-power tests will provide
momentum as Seabrook pushes for a full-power commercial license.
   In court papers, opponents argued that potential difficulties in
evacuating nearby coastal communities in southern New Hampshire and
northeastern Massachusetts, coupled with the plant's financial
problems, make it doubtful that Seabrook will ever operate
commercially. Therefore, they said, low-power tests will
unnecessarily contaminate the reactor with radioactivity, vastly
increasing the cost of dismantling.
   ``It's an exercise in self-gratification,'' said Massachusetts
Attorney General James M. Shannon in Boston. ``They want to do it
because it's going to make them feel good _ at a terrible
environmental and economic cost to the people of this region.
   ``As long as there remains the very real possibility that this
plant will never go on line, it is completely irrational to take
this irreversible step,'' he added.
   Issues the opponents list in their request for an emergency
court order include an NRC rule change last year allowing low-power
tests without an emergency public alert siren system in place in
nearby towns.
   Massachusetts forced Seabrook officials to remove sirens in the
Bay State communities that fall within Seabrook's 10-mile
evacuation zone. Plant officials since have developed a system of
truck- and helicopter-mounted sirens to notify Massachusetts
residents of a Seabrook emergency.
   Seabrook spokesman Rob Williams said plant officials would
withhold specific comments until they saw the legal papers, but he
defended the atomic reactor and its safety.
   ``There's never been a plant in history so much scrutinized and
passed so many tests,'' Williams said. ``This is a safe plant with
outstanding individuals prepared to operate it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890512-0251 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-12-89 0802EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-TankerSpill     05-12 0634</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tanker Spill,0655</SECOND>
<HEAD>Authorities Consider Use of Powerful Chemicals On Oil</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: also on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE BARTLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VALDEZ, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A top Coast Guard officer told Exxon to
study the use of powerful chemicals to break down the goo on
beaches fouled by the company's oil spill, a move likely to draw
opposition from environmentalists.
   Meanwhile, a newspaper reported Thursday that Joseph Hazelwood,
the fired skipper of the tanker Exxon Valdez, will not testify
before the National Transportation Safety Board and will try to get
his June 20 trial transferred out of Valdez.
   Coast Guard Vice Adm. Clyde Robbins, the ranking federal
official in the spill zone, said Thursday that the chemicals _
called ``dispersants'' _ may have to be used on the rocky island
shores of Prince William Sound because other cleansing methods have
proven ineffective.
   ``I`m not hot on dispersants but I think we've got to look at
it,'' Robbins said.
   He told Exxon to develop a plan to use the dispersants and
submit it for federal review.
   Dispersants are chemicals that are sprayed onto the oil, break
the oil down and thin it out, then allow it to be washed away by
the tides. Environmentalists say they may harm marine life and
remain in the water for long periods.
   The Alaska Department of Environmental Conservation said the
methods used to clean the beaches to date ``are not efficient at
removing this oil which is trapped in the soil ... or trapped
within the shoreline sediment. More effective methods neeed to be
used.''
   Attorney Dick Madson was quoted in the Fairbanks Daily
News-Miner as saying that Hazelwood, 42, had provided information
in writing to the NTSB, which is to begin its hearings Tuesday in
Anchorage.
   Hazelwood is accused of three misdemeanor counts that include
operating the 987-foot vessel while drunk. He was in command of the
tanker March 24, when it slammed into a reef about 25 miles off
Valdez and leaked more than 10 million gallons of crude into Prince
William Sound.
   ``I think Fairbanks is the best place to have this trial. There
are no close ties to the fishing industry here,'' Madson said.
   Fairbanks, Alaska's second-largest city, has strong ties to the
oil industry, with about half of the city's $950 million-a-year
economy stemming from oil.
   Hazelwood faces a maximum penalty of 27 months in jail and
$11,000 in fines if convicted of all charges. He is also the
subject of a felony grand jury investigation in Anchorage.
   In other developments:
   _Officials said Thursday that 14 Exxon cleanup workers became
temporarily ill from inhaling oil fumes and received medical
emergency treatment, forcing a halt in part of the Alaska oil spill
cleanup.
   The workers were taken ill Tuesday in the Port Chatham area of
the Kenai Peninsula, and treated at a nearby medical center and
discharged Wednesday.
   The symptoms included nausea, skin irritation, respiratory
complaints and burning eyes, said officials of the interagency
Center for Disaster Assistance. Work in the area is suspended until
respirators are obtained, officials said.
   _Authorities said more than 20 tons of animals that have been
killed by the spill are being held in deep freeze while Exxon and
government officials try to agree on a way to dispose of the
carcasses.
   The dead animals include more than 9,400 birds and 600 sea
otters, along with 28 bald eagles.
   Exxon wants to use hospital incinerators, but residents say they
worry air quality would suffer and officials are uncertain if
incineration would require exemptions from environmental
regulations.
   Exxon's overall proposal for cleaning up the spill calls for
5,000 people scouring the shores by midsummer, with 364 miles of
beaches cleaned by Sept. 15. Thus far, the cleanup has cost the
company nearly $100 million, according to Exxon executives.
</TEXT>
