<SECOND>BC-Hilton Offers,0239</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hilton Open To Offers, But None Pending, Chairman Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Barron Hilton, who gained control of 34
percent of Hilton Hotels Corp. after a 10-year struggle over his
father's estate, said the company would consider offers from
interested buyers.
   Addressing shareholders at the hotel-casino company's annual
meeting Thursday, Hilton said he had received calls from investment
bankers since Monday about generating a deal. After the meeting,
however, Hilton noted that there have been no potential suitors
have yet surfaced.
   Speculation about Hilton's future drove the company's stock up
$6.50 a share Thursday in heavy trading on the New York Stock
Exchange. It ended the day at a new high of $72 a share.
   Hilton, the company's chairman and chief executive, said he was
``neutral'' about a sale of the company.
   Executors of founder Conrad N. Hilton's estate on Monday
distributed the final amount of shares of Hilton Hotels, about 13.5
million, which set off speculation on Wall Street that the firm may
be sold within months.
   As a result of a negotiated settlement, Hilton owns 25 percent
of the stock and has voting control over another 9 percent that is
held in trust.
   Under the agreement, he received about $334 million of the $654
million market value that the stock represented at that time. The
Conrad N. Hilton Foundation received the remaining $320 million.
