<FILEID>AP-NR-05-12-89 0858EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-SearsMeeting     05-12 0424</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sears Meeting,0438</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sears Chairman Hopes For June Decision On Moving Merchandising Group</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sears, Roebuck and Co. is continuing negotiations
to sell its landmark headquarters, but the company would like to
keep most major operations based in the Chicago area, Chairman
Edward A. Brennan says.
   ``These are our roots,'' Brennan said. ``We have been here
almost since the beginning.''
   Sears hopes to announce in June where its 6,000-employee
Merchandising Group will be relocated, but is ``nowhere near making
a determination'' now, Brennan told reporters after the company's
annual meeting Thursday.
   ``All I can say is that we're looking very hard at all of the
alternatives,'' Brennan said. ``The truth is that we really don't
have all of the costs laid out.''
   Sears would need at least 1 million square feet to house the
Merchandise Group, space that would be ``greater than most of the
parcels we own in the Chicago area,'' Brennan said.
   State economic development officials have reportedly offered
Sears sites near O'Hare International Airport and in Hoffman
Estates.
   The Merchandise Group is currently housed in the Sears Tower,
which the retailer plans to sell as part of a restructuring program
announced last fall.
   Concerning the sale of the Sears Tower, the world's tallest
building located in the heart of Chicago, Brennan would only say
``negotiations are proceeding.''
   He called Wednesday's discussions with Illinois Gov. James R.
Thompson and Chicago Mayor Richard M. Daley concerning a site for
the Merchandise Group ``excellent,'' and said Illinois officials
were supportive in trying to keep the Sears subsidiary in the state.
   ``We intend to meet with the governor and the mayor again,
probably within the next two weeks to three weeks,'' Brennan said.
``We hope to be able to make a decision as we move into the month
of June.''
   He would not discuss incentives, nor would he compare them to
those offered by other states.
   While Brennan reiterated the company's position that it ``would
prefer to remain in the Chicago-land area,'' he said the retailer
has a responsibility to its shareholders ``to look at all of the
options'' based on comparisons of land costs, the costs of
relocation and taxes.
   Among the cities vying to land the Merchandise Group are Dallas,
Charlotte, N.C. and Kansas City, Mo.
   Brennan's news conference followed the company's first annual
meeting since it announced last October that it would sell the
Sears Tower, move the Merchandise Group to new and cheaper
quarters, offer more brand-name products and shift to an everyday
low-pricing strategy for its stores.
</TEXT>
