<FILEID>AP-NR-05-12-89 0918EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-AllstateChairman     05-12 0162</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Allstate Chairman,0168</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hedien Named Allstate Chairman</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wayne E. Hedien has been named chairman and chief
executive officer of the Allstate Insurance Group, succeeding
Richard J. Haayen, who is retiring after more than 37 years with
the company, officials said.
   Haayen, who served as Allstate's chief executive officer since
1986, will retire June 30 when he turns 65, Allstate's parent,
Sears Roebuck and Co., announced Thursday.
   Hedien, 55, a native of Evanston, Ill., joined Allstate in 1966
as an investment analyst. He moved up through the company ranks to
become president in October 1986.
   The company said Raymond H. Kiefer would replace Hedien as
Allstate's president. Kiefer, 62, joined Allstate in 1952 as a
claims adjuster and most recently was president of Allstate's
personal property and casualty unit.
   Sears Chairman Edward A. Brennan said Haayen ``has provided
outstanding leadership in guiding Allstate's continued profitable
growth and in forging closer and more profitable links with Sears
other business groups.''
</TEXT>
