<DOCNO> AP890512-0256 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-12-89 0919EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-FordMeeting     05-12 0528</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ford Meeting,0549</SECOND>
<HEAD>Change Fuel Economy Law, Ford Chairman Urges</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto DT4 of May 11</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal government should revamp its system
for forcing improvements in car fuel economy and hold all
automakers to the same percentage improvement each year, Ford Motor
Co.'s chairman says.
   ``I think people are being very misguided in thinking they are
helping the environmental question by ramping up the fuel
economy,'' Donald Petersen said Thursday after the No. 2 U.S.
automaker's annual meeting.
   Petersen said corporate average fuel economy standards are a
``real penalty'' to Ford and industry-leader General Motors Corp.
   Because of its reliance on smaller cars, Chrysler Corp. has had
little trouble in the past meeting federally mandated fuel
standards.
   ``An alternative we are suggesting,'' he said, ``would be ... to
ask all manufacturers to achieve an equal percentage improvement in
x-number of vehicles.''
   Petersen said Ford should be ready within five years to put on
the road a fleet of cars powered by a variety of fuels.
   ``We are negotiating with the state of California right now to
provide them with a fleet of 2,500 flexible fuel vehicles,''
Petersen said, adding that such a fleet could be ready well before
1995.
   There has been increasing debate recently about the use of fuels
other than gasoline to power cars and trucks, spurred in part by
rising oil prices and concern about vehicle emissions contributing
to a global warming trend.
   Much of the effort has been concentrated on use of methanol,
which would require substantial changes in automobile engineering.
   Research into alternative fuels is facing a dilemma, Petersen
said.
   Oil companies don't want to commit large resources to develop
alternative fuels because automakers haven't developed vehicles
that can use them, he said. Automakers haven't made vehicles that
can use alternative fuels because oil companies haven't developed
the fuels.
   ``Flexible-fuel vehicles are an obvious way around the chicken
and egg problem,'' Petersen said.
   During Thursday's meeting, the Rev. Louis Johnson of Detroit
urged Petersen and the board of directors to cut all connections
with South Africa, which is limited to licensing the use of the
Ford nameplate on vehicles made by Samcor, a successor to Ford's
manufacturing operations in South Africa.
   Ford withdrew its financial presence from South Africa beginning
in late 1987 by donating and selling its portion of Samcor to
employees and the corporation.
   The company continues to sell vehicles with Ford nameplates in
South Africa, spokesman Al Chambers said, and some are sold to the
government.
   ``Since the company's products are still available, the
withdrawal amounts to corporate camouflage,'' Johnson said.
   Petersen said the company decries the segregationist policies of
the South African government, but keeping the automaker in
business, rather than selling it off two years ago, was the proper
course to take.
   Thursday's meeting also saw two great-grandsons of founder Henry
Ford assume important committee posts within the company.
   Edsel Ford II and his cousin, William Clay Ford Jr., members of
Ford's board of directors since January 1988, were appointed to the
automaker's executive and audit committees.
   The Ford family controls about 40 percent of the company's stock.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
