<FIRST>u f PM-Ogilvy-WPP     05-12 0216</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ogilvy-WPP,0226</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ogilvy Group in Takeover Talks With WPP</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ogilvy Group Inc. today said it has begun talks
with Britain's WPP Group PLC, which has made a $50-a-share takeover
offer for the American advertising company and indicated its
willingness to increase the bid.
   Ogilvy said there is no guarantee the discussions will produce
an agreement on WPP acquiring Ogilvy, the world's fifth-largest
advertising concern based on 1988 billings.
   Takeover speculators on Wall Street have expected WPP to make a
more generous offer. WPP's current offer values Ogilvy at about
$750 million.
   Arbitragers earlier this week pushed Ogilvy's stock $2 above the
latest WPP bid and in early over-the-counter trading today, Ogilvy
shares were up 87{ cents, at $52.75.
   WPP started its bidding at $45 a share and has maintained all
along that it wanted to negotiate a friendly deal, avoiding the
possibly costly delays of a hostile transaction.
   Purchasing Ogilvy would make WPP, the London-based owner of the
U.S. agency J. Walter Thompson and the world's third-largest
advertising company, roughly match in size industry leader Saatchi
&amp; Saatchi Co. PLC.
   A statement issued by Ogilvy said any agreement between the two,
which would have to be approved by both companies' boards, would be
contingent upon certain conditions, which were not specified.
</TEXT>
