<FILEID>AP-NR-05-12-89 1008EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Newmont-Peabody     05-12 0477</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Newmont-Peabody,0495</SECOND>
<HEAD>Peabody Plans for Recapitalization, Change in Ownership Announced</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Peabody Holding Co., the largest coal company in
North America, will undergo a recapitalization and partial change
of ownership, according to Newmont Mining Corp., Peabody's largest
shareholder.
   The recapitalization, which will include the payment of a $425
million dividend to Newmont, will help pay down Newmont's $1.2
billion debt, Newmont said in a statement released Thursday by its
Denver office.
   Newmont executives said the deal had nothing to do with an
attempt by South African-controlled Minorco SA to take over
Britain's Consolidated Gold Fields PLC.
   Gold Fields owns 49 percent of Newmont. Analysts said Newmont's
long-range plans was to use the proceeds of the recapitalization at
Peabody toward buying back its shares in Gold Fields and becoming
an independent company.
   Newmont owns 49.97 percent of Peabody. Under the plan announced
Thursday, the three largest of Peabody's four other stockholders,
Bechtel Instruments Inc., Boeing Co. and Eastern Enterprises, have
granted Peabody the right until Oct. 31 to purchase their shares
for an aggregate price of $518 million.
   A similar per-share offer was made to the fourth shareholder,
which was identified in news reports as Equitable Life Assurance
Society.
   Peabody will refinance most of its debt before the stock
buyback, and, after the stock is repurchased, pay the $425 million
dividend to Newmont, which at that point will briefly be Peabody's
sole owner.
   Newmont will then sell 50.03 percent of the coal company for $75
million to Salomon Brothers Inc. and Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
   As a result of the transaction, Newmont will be left with a
stake in Peabody identical to what it currently owns, and will have
a total of $500 million with which to reduce its debt to
approximately $750 million, Newmont said.
   Newmont will also have the option after four years to repurchase
the stake held by Salomon and Shearson.
   The deal will increase the debt on Peabody's books. But Peabody
President Robert H. Quenon said he did not expact the
recapitalization and ownership change to have a major effect on the
company's busienss.
   ``We have gone through similar situations before and have
emerged a stronger company,'' he said in a statement.
   Newmont reported $1.2 billion debt at the end of 1988, which
included the cost of expansion programs and the payment of a $2.2
billion dividend in 1987, James Hill, a Newmont spokesman said.
   Peabody is the parent of a group of coal mining, marketing and
related corporations that produce more coal than any other company
in the United States.
   In 1988, Peabody sold 81.5 million tons of coal, producing
revenue of $1.7 billion. It has long-term contracts to deliver more
than 1 billion tons of coal over the next 30 years.
   Newmont, based in New York, has interests in gold, copper and
other metals and energy resources including coal.
</TEXT>
