<FILEID>AP-NR-05-12-89 1041EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-MagazineMuddle 1stLd-Writethru   05-12 0372</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Magazine Muddle, 1st Ld-Writethru,0382</SECOND>
<HEAD>Our `Cover' Story: Which Magazine Are You Reading on the Checkout
Line? ^Eds: subs 9th graf to CORRECT million to billion; uppicks 10th graf
pvs: Time Inc. ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge said Celebrity Plus magazine's
cover looks too much like People Weekly and ordered changes in
Celebrity's cover format.
   U.S. District Judge Robert Sweet issued a preliminary injunction
Thursday barring Globe Communications Corp., which has published
Celebrity Plus since January 1987, from using elements of the
People Weekly cover.
   Time Inc., which owns People, sued last month even after Globe
changed the dot over the ``i'' in Celebrity to a star and added the
words ``A Globe Publication,'' to the cover.
   ``We intend to further refine the logo,'' said Leonard M. Marks,
an attorney for Globe. ``That will end any possible complaint
People has. We really think People brought this action as a way to
stifle competition, but we intend to compete with them nose to
nose.''
   Not surprisingly, People magazine took a different view.
   ``At this stage, the court has found that Globe intentionally
set out to mislead the public and to intentionally copy People's
cover format,'' said Betsy Wagner, a spokeswoman for People.
   In a 23-page decision, Sweet said Time Inc. ``has shown that
they will suffer irreparable harm if the injunction is not granted
...''
   More than half of People's sales, at $1.79 per copy, occur at
newsstands, supermarket checkouts and bookstores.
   Court papers said People sold 1.1 billion copies between 1981
and 1988.
   Time Inc., which has published People since 1974, claimed that
``the cover of People plays a critical role in the newsstand sales
and that the substantially consistent cover subject and cover
format are used to attract readers who rely on the distinctive
cover format in selecting the magazine.''
   Celebrity Plus, a monthly that prints 250,000 copies a month at
$1.95 each, altered its cover format for its May 1989 issue to
contain elements ``which were already a part of People's cover
format,'' wrote Sweet.
   Those elements included bordering the letters in the magazine's
name in a contrasting color and having the letters touch or blend
into each other.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890512-0261 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-12-89 1109EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-WholesalePrices 4thLd-Writethru   05-12 0881</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wholesale Prices, 4th Ld-Writethru,0906</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wholesale Prices Rise 0.4 Percent in April</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5th graf pvs, The April, with 4 new grafs with reax, market
update and inventories report; deletes last 2 grafs pvs for length; version
moving general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wholesale prices rose a moderate 0.4 percent
in April, despite the sharpest increase in energy costs in nearly
2{ years, the government said today.
   The gain in the Labor Department's Producer Price Index
reflected a steep jump in gasoline prices, counterbalanced by a
substantial drop in auto prices and broad declines in food costs.
   It followed an identical 0.4 percent gain in March and large,
back-to-back 1 percent jumps in January and February.
   Because of the steep rises early in the year, wholesale price
inflation, one stop short of retail, advanced at a 9 percent annual
rate in the first four months of 1989.
   Bond prices soared in early trading. The Treasury's key 30-year
bond _ a widely-watched barometer of inflationary speculation _ was
up more than $20 per $1,000 in face amount with its yield tumbling
about a quarter point from 9.06 percent late Thursday.
   On Wall Street, the Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks
rocketed more than 44 points higher in the first 20 minutes of
trading. By 11 a.m. EDT, the Dow was up 36.29 points at 2,419.17.
   ``This is very good news ... but the inflation watch is not
over,'' said Dirk Van Dongen, president of the National Association
of Wholesaler-Distributors. ``My concern is it's dangerous to
generalize long-term trends from any 30-day snapshot. We still have
some sectors in the economy that are hot even though some have
slowed.''
   In a separate report today, the Commerce Department said
business inventories in March rose 0.3 percent while sales were
flat, confirming earlier government statistics showing economic
growth slowing.
   Economists were paying particular attention to the inflation
rate for goods other than the volatile food and energy categories,
which edged down 0.1 percent in April following a 0.3 percent rise
in March. It was the first drop since an identical fall in October
1987.
   A 0.6 percent decline in food costs was the biggest since a 1.1
percent decline in December 1987 and represented the first
substantial price relief since last year's drought.
   The huge 7.2 percent rise in energy costs matched the increase
in January 1987. Energy prices have not risen more sharply in one
month in 15 years.
   The energy increase was almost entirely attributable to a 13.4
percent climb in gasoline prices, the steepest since January 1987.
Fuel oil rose a comparatively moderate 0.6 percent after zooming
16.8 percent in March. Natural gas prices advanced 1.9 percent
   The decline in food was led by a 15.9 percent drop in eggs.
Vegetables fell 7.5 percent; pork, 3.6 percent; fruit, 2.7 percent;
and fish, 1.3 percent. The prices of turkeys, rice and candy rose.
   The biggest drop in categories other than food and energy came
in autos, where prices fell 2.8 percent, the result of
manufacturers' incentives to lure customers into showrooms and
revive slumping sales.
   There were also declines in children's clothing, cosmetics,
magazines and tires. Prices rose for jewelry and electronic
equipment.
   The overall April increase left the Producer Price Index for
finished goods at 113.0, meaning that a hypothetical selection of
goods costing $100 in 1982 would have cost $113 last month, up from
$112.20 in March.
   Inflation measures earlier in the production process also showed
moderation. Intermediate goods rose 0.4 percent in April following
a 0.7 percent jump in March. Crude goods rose 0.6 percent following
a 2.3 percent gain.
   An example of the three processing levels would be finished _
wholesale bread; intermediate _ flour, and crude _ wheat.
   The 9 percent annual rate of wholesale inflation so far this
year is more than double the 4 percent price rise last year and
four times the 2.2 percent gain in 1987.
   Analysts, however, are divided over whether inflation will
continue accelerating later this year.
   Michael Boskin, President Bush's chief economic adviser,
acknowledged earlier this week that ``we may see another bumpy
month or two.'' But he pointed out that ``the great bulk of the
acceleration was due to the increased price of crude oil.''
   ``As (oil prices) stabilize, they will no longer contribute to''
inflation, Boskin said in a speech to the National Association of
Manufacturers.
   Stock and bond markets had been trading quietly most of the week
as traders awaited today's report. They worried that if the
inflation number was too severe, the Federal Reserve Board would
push interest rates higher to cool the economy and ease inflation
pressure.
   The Fed's Open Market Committee, which stepped up its fight
against inflation in February after the bad news for January was
released, meets next Tuesday to set monetary policy through June.
Analysts generally expect the committee to leave policy unchanged.
   The Fed pushed up short-term interest rates three percentage
points between March 1988 and March 1989 and there is some evidence
that its tight-money moves are working.
   Job growth slowed in April as the unemployment rate jumped to
5.3 percent from 5.0 percent in March. Retail sales for the month
rose a modest 0.4 percent after two weak months.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
