<FILEID>AP-NR-05-12-89 1120EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f BC-Salomon-Thrifts     05-12 0291</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Salomon-Thrifts,0302</SECOND>
<HEAD>Salomon To Invest Up To $75 Million In Failed Thrifts, Banks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wall Street's Salomon Inc. will be the lead
investor in a partnership that intends to buy failed savings and
loans with $10 billion or more in combined assets.
   Big Wall Street firms and private investors that once ignored
S&amp;Ls are pouring money in, partly because of assistance that should
be provided by the government through a $157 billion financial
package now making its way through Congress.
   If the new partnership, Stone Capital Partners, gets all the
investors it is seeking, it would form the largest pool of private
money solely dedicated to buying failed thrifts, John H. Gutfreund,
Salomon's chief executive, said Thursday.
   Picking and managing the S&amp;Ls will be Blackstone Group, a New
York investment banking firm, and Old Stone Corp. of Providence,
R.I., which is a holding company for thrifts.
   ``We think the fund will be a very good investor in the
industry,'' Laurence Fink, chairman of Blackstone Financial
Management, an affiliate of Blackstone Group, said in an interview
Friday.
   Stone Capital Partners intends to raise $300 million to $600
million. Through leverage, that would allow it to buy institutions
with $10 billion to $20 billion in assets. However, since capital
requirements are rising, it is unlikely that the higher figure
would be attained.
   A Salomon affiliate has agreed to provide at least 9.9 percent
of the money committed to the fund, up to a maximum of $75 million.
Other investors will include pension funds and insurance companies,
both in the United States and abroad, Fink said.
   The fund is dedicated to buying financial service companies in
general, but thrifts are expected to make up the vast majority of
its portfolio.
</TEXT>
