<FIRST>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   05-12 0320</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0332</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Open Higher, Turn Lower On Weather</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices were mostly
lower in early trading today on the Chicago Board of Trade as
weather factors took precedence over a bullishly construed crop
report.
   Prices opened higher in reaction to Thursday's Agriculture
Department report, which projected an 8 percent decline in 1989
U.S. winter wheat production, due mainly to dry conditions and
harsh winter weather in Kansas.
   Forecasts for rain this weekend in the Great Plains and the
Midwest prompted the early selling, but some observers said traders
were unsure how to interpret the forecasts.
   Showers in the Plains could be accompanied by high winds and
hail, ``so it might do more damage than good,'' said Joel Karlin, a
research analyst with Research Department Inc. in Chicago.
   In the eastern Corn Belt, cold, wet weather has delayed planting
to the point that more rain may be viewed as positive for prices,
Karlin said.
   In early trading, wheat was } cent to 3{ cents lower with the
contract for delivery in May at $4.24{ a bushel; corn was \ cent to
2 cents lower with May at $2.75{ a bushel; oats were unchanged to
1\ cents lower with May at $1.84{ a bushel; soybeans were 3{ cents
lower to 1{ cents higher with May at $7.53 a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were higher in early trading on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .13 cent to .38 cent higher with June at 72.35
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .22 cent to .80 cent higher with
May at 77.37 cents a pound; live hogs were .05 cent lower to .12
cent higher with June at 48.12 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies
were .40 cent to .68 cent higher with May at 35.50 cents a pound.
   Cattle futures settled mostly higher on Thursday while pork
futures retreated.
</TEXT>
