<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreet2pm     05-12 0333</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 2pm,0350</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices were approaching new highs in
active trading today after the better-than-expected producer price
report.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was up 44.91 points to
2,427.79 at 2 p.m. EDT. The blue-chip indicator was up 38.86 at
noon after jumping about 45 points after the opening.
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by about 13 to 4 on the
New York Stock Exchange, with 1,116 issues up, 351 down and 451
unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board totaled 157.99 million shares.
   The Labor Department reported today that the producer price
index rose 0.4 percent in April, the same as in March, despite a
sharp increase in energy prices. The market had expected a bigger
increase.
   Traders interpreted the report to mean a further softening of
the economy and an easing of inflationary pressures.
   ``The reason why the market is responding so positively to the
data is people were bracing for the worst,'' said James Solloway,
director of economic research at Argus Research Corp. ``The fact
that we had just a 0.4 percent increase in producer prices despite
the massive 7 percent rise in energy prices is a very good
development. It takes the pressure off the Fed to consider
tightening monetary policy even further.''
   However, economists cautioned that despite indications of
weakness in some areas, the economy is still running at a high rate
of activity.
   ``The number in no way implies that inflation is set to move
lower on a permanent basis,'' Solloway said.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks was
up 2.60 to 174.31.
   At the American Stock Exchange, the market value index had risen
1.71 to 347.33.
   Among actively traded issues on the NYSE, Motorola was up 1{ to
49~, American Express had advanced 1{ to 33\ and IBM had risen 1{
to 110|.
   Eastman Kodak, meanwhile, was down { to 42}, Chrysler was off \
to 23[ and Northwest Airlines had lost } to 102\.
</TEXT>
