<FILEID>AP-NR-05-12-89 1547EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-TI-ChipVenture     05-12 0320</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-TI-Chip Venture,0333</SECOND>
<HEAD>Texas Instruments Announces Taiwanese Chip Production Venture</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texas Instruments Inc. on Friday announced the
creation of a privately held joint venture with Taiwan's Acer Inc.
to produce advanced memory chips in Taiwan.
   The venture will give Dallas-based Texas Instruments its first
memory-chip production capacity in the Asia-Pacific region outside
of Japan, the company said.
   It also will provide Acer, Taiwan's largest computer
manufacturer, an assured source of dynamic random access memory
chips, or DRAMs, for its personal computers, peripherals and
communications products, the company said.
   DRAMs are tiny silicon circuits used in computers and other
electronic devices.
   Representatives of both companies announced the venture Friday
in Taipei, Taiwan. Construction of the $250 million wafer
fabrication plant is scheduled to start in September, with initial
production in mid-1991.
   Output from the facility will be sold exclusively to Texas
Instruments, which will guarantee up to 50 percent of the total to
Acer.
   Acer will own 74 percent of the company, while TI will own 26
percent. TI will have an option to buy up to 51 percent during the
next five years.
   The Taiwanese company will put up the majority of cash to fund
the company, and TI will provide a lesser amount of money plus the
technology to build and run the plant.
   ``Customers are looking for a long-term source of product, and
they want closer relationships with their memory suppliers,'' said
William P. ``Pat'' Weber, president of TI's semiconductor group.
   ``This joint venture provides that kind of relationship between
Acer and TI,'' he said. ``It will give us some much-needed
production capacity in a key location, and it spreads the financial
risk inherent in building new increments of capacity.''
   Stan Shih, Acer's chairman and chief executive officer, will
serve as chairman of the joint venture.
   Application-specific integrated circuits also may be
manufactured by the new company in the future, according to TI
officials.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
