<DOCNO> AP890512-0275 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-12-89 1446EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f BC-Britain-Stocks 1stLd-Writethru f0034 05-12 0236</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0034,0242</SECOND>
<HEAD>London Shares Surge To Close At New Post-Crash Peak</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: RECASTS throughout to UPDATE with later activity, closing index;
No pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices surged Friday to close at a new
post-crash high on the London Stock Exchange after the release of
better-than-expected U.S. inflation figures fueled optimism about
the outlook for interest rates.
   The apparently brighter picture for interest rates should prompt
further rises in share prices in the near term, dealers predicted.
   At the close, the Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index
was up 25.1 points, or 1.2 percent, at 2,135.7, surpassing the
previous post-crash closing peak of 2,132.8 reached last Friday.
   The index moved in positive territory all day, showing a gain of
just 3.4 points in early trading before rallying to a maximum net
rise of 26.3 points at mid-afternoon.
   Volume jumped to 532.7 million shares from 430.5 million on
Thursday.
   The U.S. government reported that its producer-price index rose
0.4 percent in April, about half the expected increase.
   ``People are saying, `There is now no possibility of the (U.S.
Federal Reserve) raising rates for the foreseeable future,' and
although that doesn't directly relate to U.K. rates, it certainly
helps,'' said a salesman at a major British brokerage firm.
   The Financial Times 30-share index was up 20.4 points at 1,779.1
at the close. The Financial Times 500-share index rose 12.78 points
to close at 1,209.70.
</TEXT>
