<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   05-12 0275</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0285</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crop Futures End Widely Mixed On Weather, USDA Report</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Futures prices of grain and soybeans closed mixed
Friday on the Chicago Board of Trade on a combination of bearish
weather forecasts and bullish signals from the Agriculture
Department's latest crop report.
   Wheat futures ended lower. The corn and soybean markets both
finished with higher prices for old-crop deliveries and losses in
the new-crop contracts.
   The drop in wheat prices reflected the arrival of badly needed
rain in the parched winter wheat fields of the southern Plains.
   ``These rains are going to do good,'' said Dale Gustafson, an
analyst with Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. in Chicago.
   The USDA, in a crop report issued after Thursday's close of
trading, estimated an 8 percent decline in 1989 winter wheat
production from last year's level. But the the market had already
discounted the crop damage and traders focused instead on the
weather.
   The USDA lowered to 135 million bushels from 145 million bushels
its projection for the Aug. 31 U.S. soybean stockpile, which
supported prices for beans from last year's crop.
   Strong spot markets boosted the old-crop corn contracts, while
forecasts for favorable planting weather this weekend prompted
selling of new-crop corn and soybeans.
   At the close, wheat was 1\ cents to 5{ cents lower with the
contract for delivery in May at $4.22{ a bushel; corn was 1 cent
lower o 2\ cents higher with May at $2.78{ a bushel; oats were 2}
cents to 5 cents higher with May at $1.89{ a bushel; soybeans were
4{ cents lower to 7 cents higher with May at $7.58{ a bushel.
</TEXT>
