<FIRST>u f AM-Canada-InsiderTrading 1stLd-Writethru   05-12 0277</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Canada-Insider Trading, 1st Ld-Writethru,0285</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former British Columbia Premier Acquitted</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS Domans to Bennetts in 6th graf.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VANCOUVER, British Columbia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former British Columbia
premier Bill Bennett was found innocent Friday of insider trading
in shares of Doman Industries.
   Provincial Court Judge Wallace Craig also acquitted Bennett's
brother Russell and Herb Doman, president of the Vancouver
Island-based forest company, in Canada's highest-profile insider
trading case.
   ``I've said all along that I've done nothing wrong,'' Doman said
after the verdict. ``Now I can go on and run my business.''
   The three, prominent businessmen drawn together by ties to
horse-racing and the Social Credit political party, faced up to
$100,000 in fines and five years in jail.
   Each was charged with one count each of selling shares using
information not disclosed to the public. Russell Bennett and Doman
also faced one count of buying shares on the basis of inside
information. Doman faced one count each of tipping someone to buy
and sell using inside information.
   The Bennetts still face insider trading charges in Toronto.
   Bill Bennett, 57, was British Columbia premier from 1975 until
retiring in May 1986. His father, W.A.C. Bennett, led the
provincial government for 20 years, ending in 1972.
   Judge Craig said prosecutors had failed to prove the case beyond
a reasonable doubt.
   ``Not only has the prosecution failed to prove beyond a
reasonable doubt that Bill Bennett's sale of (Doman's) shares was
as a result of Herb Doman giving him inside information, it has
established at least on a balance of probabilities that he made the
decision to do so before he could possible have received any
alleged tip,'' he said.
</TEXT>
