<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreetClosing     05-12 0273</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street Closing,0287</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices surged in heavy trading today,
ending the day at new post-crash highs after a government report on
wholesale prices eased investor fears about inflation.
   Prices spurted at the opening as traders shook off the fears
that had held the market back all week, keeping many players on the
sidelines.
   The market stabilized at the higher level during the trading
session until a last-minute buying spree in the final hour pushed
prices up further.
   The Labor Department reported that the producer price index rose
0.4 percent in April, the same as in March, despite a sharp
increase in energy prices. The index measures prices at the
wholesale level.
   The market had expected a rise of as high as 1 percent.
   Investors decided the report meant that inflationary pressures
were not building as suggested by last week's unemployment report
and that the Federal Reserve might not continue raising interest
rates. The April jobless report showed more people were out of work
but at the same time hourly earnings climbed substantially.
   ``The fear until now was not that the economy would overheat but
that inflation would rise rapidly and keep the Fed from making
moves to ease credit,'' said Michael Metz, technical analyst for
Oppenheimer &amp; Co. ``Now it looks like that has changed.''
   However, economists cautioned that despite indications of
weakness in some areas, the economy is still running at a high rate
of activity.
   ``The number in no way implies that inflation is set to move
lower on a permanent basis,'' said James Solloway, director of
economic research at Argus Research Corp.
</TEXT>
