<FIRST>u f AM-Apples-Alar     05-12 0591</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Apples-Alar,0615</SECOND>
<HEAD>Alar Costs Growers $90 Million</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICHOLAS K. GERANIOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YAKIMA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Alar scare has already cost Washington
apple growers $90 million this year, and slumping prices and sales
reported Friday indicate losses will be even higher.
   Sales dropped 15 percent last week, while prices have slumped
another $1 per box, both attributed to continuing public concern
over the possible health effects of the farm chemical.
   The outlook is even gloomier because round two of the Alar
controversy is about to begin, with more news reports, a
congressional hearing and movement by the U.S. Environmental
Protection Agency toward banning the chemical.
   Bill DeWitt of the Wenatchee Valley Traffic Association reported
Friday that out-of-state shipments of Washington apples were 1.2
million 42-pound boxes during the week that ended Thursday.
   That compared to nearly 1.5 million boxes the week before, and
nearly 1.7 million boxes the same week last year.
   Shipments to retailers are considered an accurate indicator of
consumer sales.
   Tom Hale, president of the Washington State Apple Commission,
has attributed the decline to retailers dropping their inventories
until the impact of the latest Alar battle becomes clear.
   The industry is anxiously awaiting another Alar report on the
CBS television program ``60 Minutes,'' scheduled for this Sunday.
The show's story on the NRDC report in late February sparked the
controversy.
   The industry has contacted people interviewed for the second
``60 Minutes'' story and believes it will be a negative piece.
   ``It's an attempt to offset the broad criticism the original
segment had,'' said Hale, who heads the promotion group for the
state's 5,000 growers.
   Also set for next week are congressional hearings on food safety
that will focus on Alar. And the EPA announced Thursday that it
plans to begin formal steps to ban Alar within 10 days.
   The NRDC report concluded that eating apples treated with Alar,
the trade name for daminozide, increased cancer risk in children.
   The industry has attacked the report as misleading, and federal
regulators have pronounced apples safe to eat, but alarmed
consumers have backed away.
   Alar is sprayed on apple trees in the spring and is used
primarily to improve color and crispness and extend shelf life of
red apples.
   Washington grows about half the nation's apples, but provides 88
percent of the domestic production this time of year. The state's
growers have been hardest hit by the controversy.
   Prices, which were $13 to $14 per box just before the
controversy erupted in late February, have dropped to around $10
per box in recent weeks, said Jeff Main of the federal-state Market
News Service in Yakima.
   With about 30 million boxes of red apples sold since late
February, the cost to Washington growers about $90 million.
   Those losses are partially offset by increases in prices for
much smaller supplies of Golden Delicious and Granny Smith apples.
   Warehouses in the state still have over 13 million boxes of red
apples left in storage, 3 million more than at this time last year.
   ``If we don't sell all of these, which is a possibility, we will
lose much more,'' DeWitt said.
   Earlier this week, John Rice, president of the International
Apple Institute, estimated that the controversy had cost growers
across the nation $100 million, with another $100 million lost by
juice and applesauce processors.
   The sales slowdown also means that stored fruit, which normally
would have been sold a month ago, is becoming unsuitable for
supermarkets and must be diverted at a much lower price to juice
and sauce makers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890512-0284 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-12-89 1645EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Ogilvy-WPP Bjt   05-12 0664</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ogilvy-WPP, Bjt,0686</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ogilvy Group in Takeover Talks With WPP</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ogilvy Group Inc. has begun talks with Britain's
WPP Group PLC, which has offered to buy the American advertising
company for about $800 million but indicated it may increase its
bid, the companies said Friday.
   Ogilvy said in disclosing the talks that there was no guarantee
the discussions would produce an agreement on WPP acquiring Ogilvy,
the world's fifth-largest advertising concern.
   A combination of WPP and Ogilvy would create a company that
would vie with Saatchi &amp; Saatchi Co. PLC for the ranking as the
world's largest advertising company.
   Takeover speculators on Wall Street have expected WPP to make a
more generous offer in an effort to avoid the costly delays and
potential client losses that could occur due to a result of a
hostile transaction.
   In over-the-counter trading Friday, Ogilvy shares rose $1.25 a
share to $53.12{.
   Analysts took a cautious approach toward interpreting the
significance of the discussions.
   Andrew Wallach, who follows advertising agencies for Drexel
Burnham Lambert, said it may be ``a signal that in all probability
we will see an agreed transaction.'' But, he quickly added, ``you
can't rule out anything at this point.''
   Fred Anschel, an analyst at Dean Witter Reynolds Inc., said the
Ogilvy announcement ``suggests they have no other feasible options
available to them.'' Ogilvy reportedly has considered seeking a
friendly buyout by another company, a management-led buyout or a
recapitalization.
   But another securities analyst, speaking on condition that he
not be identified, said Ogilvy management may be talking with WPP
simply to gather information in advance of a regular board meeting,
set for Tuesday.
   A statement issued by Ogilvy said any agreement between the two,
which would have to be approved by both companies' boards, would be
contingent upon certain unspecified conditions.
   In London, WPP confirmed in a one-sentence statement that
``discussions are in progress ... regarding the possible
acquisition of Ogilvy by WPP.''
   London-based WPP, the world's third-largest advertising company
and parent of the U.S. agency J. Walter Thompson, opened the
bidding for Ogilvy two weeks ago when it proposed a friendly buyout
at $45 a share. Earlier this week, WPP said it would be willing to
pay $50 a share.
   Ogilvy has about 16 million shares outstanding on a fully
diluted basis, making WPP's current offer worth about $800 million.
   Purchasing Ogilvy would make WPP nearly equal in size to
industry leader Saatchi &amp; Saatchi. Saatchi had worldwide billings
of $13.5 billion last year, while WPP had $7.8 billion and Ogilvy
came in at $5.7 billion.
   Ogilvy's Ogilvy &amp; Mather ad agency is recognized as one of the
most famous names in advertising and counts among its clients
American Express, Seagram Co. and the Kraft General Foods unit of
Philip Morris Cos.
   But analysts have faulted Ogilvy for below-average operating
margins. Ogilvy executives insist that margins in its advertising
agency are near the industry average of about 10 percent but that
its research operations have depressed companywide margins.
   WPP is led by Martin Sorrell, who is credited as the architect
of the acquisition strategy that made Saatchi the world's biggest
ad company.
   After leaving Saatchi, he applied what he had learned in
building WPP from a small maker of shopping baskets to a global
consortium of advertising, public relations, sales promotion and
marketing services companies.
   His boldest move was two years ago when WPP successfully
acquired JWT Group Inc., the parent of J. Walter Thompson and the
smaller ad agency Lord Geller Federico Einstein and the public
relations giant Hill &amp; Knowlton. It was the first hostile
acquisition in the American ad business and cost $566 million.
   Analysts say Sorrell prizes Ogilvy's brand name and its
strengths in Europe, where Thompson is weaker. They say Ogilvy also
would give Sorrell a second global ad company to be run
independently of Thompson much as Saatchi and other advertising
behemoths run separate global ad networks.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
