<FIRST>r f AM-SleepingBeauty     05-12 0325</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sleeping Beauty,0337</SECOND>
<HEAD>Voice Behind `Sleeping Beauty' Sues Disney For Royalties</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The voice of the princess in the
1959 animated classic ``Sleeping Beauty'' is suing Walt Disney Co.
for something no one envisioned when the movie was made _ videotape
royalties.
   New York attorney Glenn Every called the lawsuit filed Thursday
in Palm Beach Circuit Court ``a straightforward contractual
dispute'' between Disney and his client, opera singer Mary Costa,
who sang and spoke the words of the princess.
   ``She had agreed with the Disney people to provide her services
as a singer, and the Disney people agreed that they would not make
recordings or a transcription without her permission, and they
haven't paid royalties,'' Every said.
   In Ms. Costa's 1952 contract with Disney, the company agreed not
to ``make phonograph recordings and-or transcriptions for sale to
the public.''
   The suit contends videocassettes fit that description, and the
Palm Beach soprano is seeking royalties from videocassette sales.
   Another of her attorneys says the ``Sleeping Beauty'' video has
been a big seller since it went on sale in October 1986.
   ``It's sold over 1.8 million in Italy alone,'' said Christopher
Larmoyeux, ``so you can imagine the income.''
   In November, singer Peggy Lee filed a similar lawsuit. She
co-wrote the lyrics and performed on the soundtrack of Disney's
1955 film ``Lady and the Tramp.''
   Lee claimed she hadn't gotten any money from sales of nearly 4
million videocassettes of that movie. Her case is still pending in
California.
   Disney representatives in California don't want to talk about
Costa's suit.
   ``We're not going to comment on anything that is in
litigation,'' said company spokesman Mike Ferguson.
   Disney has been embroiled in several legal controversies
recently. The company sued the producers of the Academy Awards for
unauthorized use of the character Snow White in a song-and-dance
number and a Broward County day care center to remove murals of
Disney characters from its walls.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
