<FIRST>u f AM-BigBlueDispute 1stLd-Writethru   05-12 0329</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Big Blue Dispute, 1st Ld-Writethru,0336</SECOND>
<HEAD>Computer Dealer Blue Over Name Fight</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd, 8th grafs to show Alnwick has 30 days to submit a
phase-out plan, not 30 days to come up with a new name.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   remove reference to 30 day
   NORTHPORT, N.Y. (AP) _ What's in a name? Well, according to
International Business Machines Corp., that depends on what you're
selling.
   IBM has told a Long Island computer company called Big Blue
Products Inc. to find a new name or face legal action for trademark
infringement. ``Big Blue'' is a trademark long associated with IBM,
said company spokeswoman Rita Black.
   But Jeff Alnwick, owner of the 5-year-old company, says other
firms have used the Big Blue name without any problem _ and Black
agrees. If you're just selling wine, ``Big Blue'' is fine, she said.
   Why?
   ``We don't make wine,'' said Black, adding the corporation knew
about and had no problem with the ``Big Blue'' brew marketed by the
Rivendell Winery in New Paltz.
   Alnwick's firm _ which has five employees and does about $3
million business per year _ distributes computer products to office
machine dealers. He claims IBM representatives have seen him at
trade shows and thought his name was cute.
   But IBM officials weren't laughing when they notified Alnwick he
had 30 days to submit plans detailing how he would go about
changing the name and when that change will be complete. Alnwick,
who accused IBM of bullying him, vowed to fight for his right to
use the name.
   ``I guess I'll have to hire an attorney to fight this. I can't
afford to, but what choice do I have?'' Alnwick asked.
   The Long Island businessman may have a tough fight in court, but
he has at least one supporter already _ Bob Ransom, owner of the
Rivendell Winery.
   ``His is a real David and Goliath story. Now that he has an
established business they are looking to squash it,'' said Ransom.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
