<HEAD>Energy Futures Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The energy futures market closed narrowly mixed
in dull trading Friday.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the June contract for West
Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S. crude oil, settled
3 cents higher at $20.09 a barrel after rising 54 cents on
Thursday. All other contracts were lower, however.
   Among refined petroleum products traded on the exchange, June
heating oil, which rose 1.20 cents on Thursday, gained another 0.42
cent to finish at 49.10 cents a gallon.
   Wholesale unleaded gasoline for June delivery slipped 0.27 cent
to 67.01 cents a gallon. On Thursday the near-term contract soared
2.56 cents a gallon.
   Analysts said gasoline prices were negatively affected by
legislation introduced in the House of Representatives late in the
day proposing to hike the federal gasoline tax by 9 cents a gallon.
According to Rep. Jim Moody, D-Wis., who introduced the bill, the
roughly $9 billion in annual proceeds would be used to help cut the
federal deficit.
   ``That put downward pressure on gas,'' said William Byers, an
analyst with Bear, Stearns &amp; Co. The current federal gasoline tax
amounts to 9.1 cents per gallon.
   While the bill gave dealers a reason to sell, analysts noted
that trading was mostly quiet all day.
   ``It's just deadly dull,'' Byers said. The market's attention is
turning to the upcoming meeting next month of the Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries in Vienna, Austria.
