<FIRST>r f AM-McDonald'sESOP     05-12 0354</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-McDonald's ESOP,0367</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fast-Food Giant Selling $100 Million New Issue to ESOP</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OAK BROOK, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   McDonald's Corp. announced plans Friday
to sell $100 million of a new issue of preferred stock to its
Employee Stock Ownership Plan to increase employee holdings.
   ``This transaction is a continuation of a long-held strategy and
tradition established by our founder (the late) Ray Kroc of
encouraging employee share ownership,'' said Fred L. Turner,
chairman of the fast-food giant.
   The ESOP can borrow long-term funds and purchase stock at
current prices ``to help our employees own more stock in the
company,'' he said. ``It will not increase the company's total
employee-benefit costs.''
   The new issue is convertible into less than 1 percent of
outstanding common shares, McDonald's said. The preferred's
dividend and coversion ratio will be determined at the time of sale
based on market conditions, and each share will have one vote.
   Selling stock into an employee ownership plan has become popular
among corporations because it cuts the company's tax bill while
erecting a new takeover defense. Employees who own stock are
considered more inclined to side with the company in a takeover
battle, choosing long-term gains over a short-term windfall.
   Such concerns were not at issue in this case, said McDonald's
spokesman Chuck Ebeling.
   ``I don't think that has anything to do with it,'' Ebeling said.
   The sale ``only represents 1 percent of outstanding common
shares. I'm told that's not significant enough'' to thwart a
takeover attempt, he said.
   The company's ESOP is distinctive for its ``breadth of coverage.
Our restaurant managers and full-time restaurant crew all
participate,'' Turner said.
   ``This transaction will help to achieve our long-term goal of
increasing stock ownership among the largest number of employees.''
   The ESOP intends to borrow the money needed to purchase the
stock under a $300 million shelf registration filed Friday with the
Securities and Exchange Commission, the company said.
   McDonald's says it is the world's largest food-service
organization, serving 22 million people each day in more than
10,500 restaurants in 50 countries. Three-quarters of its
restaurant businesses are locally owned and operated by independent
entrepreneurs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
