<FILEID>AP-NR-05-12-89 2055EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-S&amp;Ls-Takeovers     05-12 0170</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-S&amp;Ls-Takeovers ,0174</SECOND>
<HEAD>New S&amp;L Protection Planned</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal regulators said Friday they will draft
new rules designed to protect savings institutions from hostile
takeovers after they convert from the mutual form of ownership to
stock ownership.
   The Federal Home Loan Bank Board said it has directed its staff
to rewrite the agency's rules to make the hostile intent of an S&amp;L
stock buyer one of the grounds for denial of an application for
three years after an institution converts from mutal to stock
ownership. The bank board normally has authority to decide who may
own a thrift institution.
   The move comes after the board denied investor groups permission
to acquire more than 10 percent of the stock of two institutions,
Gateway Federal Savings and Loan Association of Cincinnati, and
Home Unity Savings and Loan Association of Lafayette Hill, Pa. The
institutions said the purchase efforts were unsolicited.
   The board said hostile takeovers ``divert managerial resources''
and would discourage S&amp;Ls from converting from mutual to stock
ownership.
</TEXT>
