<HEAD>Dollar Rises, Gold Mixed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar bobbed up to its highest level in
months Friday in spite of an adverse economic report and persistent
efforts by central banks to knock it down.
   The U.S. currency fell and then rose in heavy trading, ending
around a 30-month high against the West German mark, a 28-month
high against the French franc, an 18-month high against the British
pound and eight-month highs against the Japanese yen and the French
franc.
   ``Volatile is an understatement'' for the day's trading, said
Kevin Lawrie, senior foreign-exchange manager for Bank of Boston in
New York.
   The dollar dropped in the morning after a Labor Department
report that wholesale prices rose 0.4 percent in April, below the
market's expectations.
   Traders sold dollars thinking that U.S. interest rates might
decline, which could make global investors switch their money to
other currencies.
   Central banks of the United States, Canada and Europe seized the
opportunity to sell dollars themselves, driving the currency still
lower. But the decline ran out of momentum in early afternoon and
the dollar quickly shot back up.
   Traders said the dollar's rise came from persistent, underlying
bullish sentiment that was undeterred by the inflation report and
the central banks. In Tokyo, the dollar rose to 135.80 Japanese
yen, up from 134.55 yen Thursday. Later, in London, it edged up
further to 135.90 yen. In New York the dollar rose to 136.11 yen
from 135.38 late Thursday.
   The British pound fell against the dollar in London to $1.6615,
down from $1.6655 late Thursday. The pound also fell against the
dollar in New York, to $1.6615 from $1.6645.
   Other late dollar rates in New York compared with late rates on
Thursday included: 1.9195 West German marks, up from 1.9161; 1.7175
Swiss francs, up from 1.7080; 1.1880 Canadian dollars, up from
1.1871; 6.4880 French francs, up from 6.4755; and 1,398.75 Italian
lire, up from 1,395.75.
   Late dollar rates in Europe compared with late rates on Thursday
included: 1.9195 German marks, up from 1.9135; 1.7080 Swiss francs,
up from 1.7060; 6.4870 French francs, up from 6.4665; 2.1407 Dutch
guilders, down from 2.1580; 1,385.50 Italian lire, down from
1,395.75; and, 1.1868 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1870.
   Gold bullion rose in Zurich to a late bid price of $379.25 a
troy ounce, up from $378.20 bid late Thursday.
   In London, gold fell to $377 bid, down from $379 bid late
Thursday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $2.30 an ounce to close at a
bid of $380.26.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for current
delivery fell to $377.90 a troy ounce from $381. Gold had been
bolstered Thursday by investors who used it as a haven because of
tension over Panama.
   Later, Republic National Bank of New York said gold was bid at
$376.25 an ounce as of 4 p.m. EDT, down from $379.40 late Thursday.
   Silver bullion fell in London to a late bid price of $5.63 a
troy ounce, down from $5.66 bid late Thursday. On New York's Comex,
silver bullion for current delivery fell to $5.535 from $5.65 on
Thursday.
</TEXT>
