<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     05-12 0651</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0677</SECOND>
<HEAD>Silver Hits 26-Month Low On Weak Inflation, Stronger Dollar</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Silver futures prices sank to a 26-month low Friday on New
York's Commodity Exchange as inflation fears eased and investment
demand for precious metals evaporated.
   On other markets, pork bellies rose, grains and soybeans were
mixed and energy futures were mixed.
   Silver settled 12 cents to 18.1 cents lower with the spot
delivery price at $5.53 a troy ounce and the most actively traded
contract, for delivery in July, at $5.61 a troy ounce. Gold was
$3.20 to $3.90 lower with June at $378.90.
   The spot silver price was the lowest since March 20, 1987, when
spot silver settled at $5.52 an ounce.
   Friday's Labor Department report of a moderate 0.4 percent rise
in wholesale prices last month delivered the day's first blow to
the precious metals, which tend to rise and fall with inflation
fears.
   Later in the day, the dollar posted strong gains against other
major currencies, which further weakened investment interest in
precious metals.
   Analysts said recent economic indicators have not clearly
indicated an inflationary trend and the speculation prompted by
reports of sharply rising prices earlier this year has abated.
   To spark strong demand for precious metals, ``you need to have
the consumers and the specultors and the commercials completely
convinced that we are on a strong trend toward inflation,'' said
Jack Barbanel, director of futures trading for Gruntal &amp; Co. in New
York.
   Analysts said that if silver fails to find support at $5.50 an
ounce, it probably will continue to slide, perhaps as low as $5.25
before buying interest surfaces.
   ``We're in a negative trend and we can't shake it off,'' said
Stephen Platt, an analyst with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. in Chicago.
   Frozen pork belly futures prices leaped for the fourth session
in the last five in a continuing rebound from 9-year lows.
   Seasonal factors are playing a role in the booming belly market,
but chart-watchers say the market was oversold and due for a
correction.
   Hog futures settled mixed while cattle futures mostly were
higher on strong cash markets.
   Live cattle settled .03 cent lower to .43 cent higher with June
at 72.07 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .25 cent to .77 cent
higher with May at 77.45 cents a pound; live hogs were .15 cent
lower to .22 cent higher with June at 48.22 cents a pound; frozen
pork bellies were 1.18 cents to 1.50 cents higher with May at 36.42
cents a pound.
   Wheat futures ended lower on the Chicago Board of Trade while
the corn and soybean markets finished with higher prices for
old-crop deliveries and losses in the new-crop contracts.
   The drop in wheat prices reflected the arrival of badly needed
rain in the parched winter wheat fields of the southern Plains.
   The USDA lowered to 135 million bushels from 145 million bushels
its projection for the Aug. 31 U.S. soybean stockpile, which
supported prices for beans from last year's crop.
   Strong cash markets boosted the old-crop corn contracts, while
forecasts for favorable planting weather this weekend prompted
selling of new-crop corn and beans.
   Wheat settled 1\ cents to 5{ cents lower with May at $4.22{ a
bushel; corn was 1 cent lower to 2 cents higher with May at $2.78\
a bushel; oats were 2} cents to 4 cents higher with May at $1.88{ a
bushel; soybeans were 4 cents lower to 6\ cents higher with May at
$7.57} a bushel.
   Energy futures ended narrowly mixed in dull trading on the New
York Mercantile Exchange.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 7 cents lower to 3
cents higher with June at $20.09 a barrel; heating oil was .10 cent
lower to .42 cent higher with June at 49.10 cents a gallon;
unleaded gasoline was .35 cent lower to .03 cent higher with June
at 67.01 cents a gallon.
</TEXT>
