<FIRST>u f AM-WallStreet 1stLd-Writethru   05-12 0541</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wall Street, 1st Ld-Writethru,0561</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JULIA C. MARTINEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market surged to a new post-crash high
in heavy trading Friday amid renewed investor confidence in the
economy after the government's April wholesale price report.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials soared 56.82 points to
end the week at 2,439.70, its highest level since the October 1987
stock market collapse and the biggest daily gain since a
74.68-point rise on May 31, 1988.
   The Dow industrials' previous post-crash high was 2,418.99 at
the close on April 27.
   Broader market indicators also rose sharply. Advancing issues
outnumbered decliners by about 10 to 3 in nationwide trading of New
York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 1,214 up, 360 down and 410
unchanged.
   Analysts said the Labor Department's report that April wholesale
prices rose a moderate 0.4 percent _ compared with some pre-report
estimates of as high as 1 percent _ triggered the rally by raising
speculation that the Federal Reserve was less likely to push
interest rates higher to curb inflation.
   Investors also apparently decided the report meant inflationary
pressures were not building as suggested by last week's
unemployment report. The April jobless report showed more people
were out of work but also that hourly earnings climbed
substantially during the month.
   ``The fear until now was not that the economy would overheat but
that inflation would rise rapidly and keep the Fed from making
moves to ease credit,'' said Michael Metz, technical analyst for
Oppenheimer &amp; Co. ``Now it looks like that has changed. Inflation
is under control.''
   Prices took off at the opening bell, and many players who had
remained out of the market in anticipation of the wholesale price
report joined the broad-based buying spree.
   But some Wall Street observers cautioned that the market might
have gone too far too fast.
   ``We're still going to have some uncomfortably high numbers,''
said Hugh Johnson, senior vice president of First Albany Corp. ``It
was great today. It lifted everyone's spirits. But investors should
be very careful because the market has overstated the case. So on a
short-term basis we could give some ground.''
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came to 221.49 million
shares, up from 151.62 million in the previous session.
   Nationwide, consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including
trades in those stocks on regional exchanges and in the
over-the-counter market, totaled 261.42 million shares.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market rose $55.32 billion, or 1.82
percent, in value.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
jumped 3.42 to 175.13.
   Among actively traded issues on the NYSE, IBM rose 1| to 110},
Motorola gained 2\ to 50|, General Electric advanced 2 to 51 and
American Express jumped 2\ to 34.
   Eastman Kodak fell { to 42}, Northwest Airlines dropped } to
102\ and Newmont Mining slid 2] to 39\.
   Standard &amp; Poor's industrial index rose 7.40 to 360.88, and
S&amp;P's 500-stock composite index closed 6.89 higher at 313.84.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market rose
4.20 to 434.83. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index closed at 348.30, up 2.68.
</TEXT>
