<FIRST>u f AM-Bonds     05-12 0620</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bonds,0646</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bond Prices Surge In Strong Rally</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bond prices surged Friday and long-term interest
rates tumbled to three-month lows as a smaller than expected rise
in wholesale prices provided further evidence of an economic
slowdown.
   The Treasury's benchmark 30-year bond leaped 25-16 points, or
more than $23 per $1,000 face amount. Its yield, which moves
inversely from its price, tumbled to 8.83 percent from 9.06 percent
late Thursday.
   The single-day price increase was the largest since the long
bond gained 2| points last Sept. 2. The yield on the 30-year
government security dipped to its lowest level since early February.
   Yields on three-month Treasury bills plunged to 8.47 percent,
their lowest level since Jan. 3.
   The surge in prices followed the Labor Department's report that
wholesale prices rose 0.4 percent in April, about half as much as
some analysts had expected.
   ``That tended to allay the market's fear that inflation was
accelerating,'' said William V. Sullivan, director of money market
research for Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. ``It also suggested for the
first time in well over a year that the Fed may be in a position to
ease credit policy.''
   The indication of an economic slowdown buttressed a government
report Thursday that showed retail sales up 0.4 percent last month,
well under the 1.3 percent many economists had expected.
   Sullivan said an economic slowdown along with lower prices could
lead the Federal Reserve to relax its monetary policy, encouraging
lower interest rates and boosting the value of bonds.
   ``People are thinking we are past the bulge in inflation caused
by oil prices rising,'' said Robert Brusca, chief economist with
Nikko Securities International Inc.
   The bond market had declined steadily this week until a small
rise Thursday amid pessimism over a less-than-satisfactory
government quarterly refinancing auction and the belief that the
wholesale prices would rise more.
   In the secondary market for Treasury bonds, prices of short-term
governments were up by between { point and 1 point, intermediate
maturities advanced by 15-32 point and 1~ points and long-term
issues were up as much as 27-16 points, according to Telerate Inc.,
the financial information service.
   The movement of a point is equivalent to a change of $10 in the
price of a bond with a $1,000 face value.
   The Shearson Lehman Hutton Daily Treasury Bond Index, which
measures price movements on all outstanding Treasury issues with
maturities of a year or longer, climbed 13.83 to 1,145.49.
   The rise in the index was the largest since a gain of 15.00 on
Oct. 22, 1987, three days after the stock market's Black Monday
crash.
   In corporate trading, industrials rose. Moody's Investment Grade
Corporate Bond Index, which measures total return on a portfolio of
80 corporate bonds with maturities of five years or longer, rose
4.29 to 309.41.
   In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively
traded municipal bonds rose ~ point to 9227-32. The average yield
to maturity dropped to 7.52 percent from 7.60 percent.
   Yields on three-month Treasury bills tumbled to 8.47 percent as
the discount fell 24 basis points to 8.19 percent. Yields on
six-month bills fell to 8.65 percent as the discount dropped 23
basis points to 8.19 percent. Yields on 1-year bills fell to 8.73
percent as the discount fell 26 basis points to 8.09 percent.
   A basis point is one-hundredth of a percentage point. The yield
is the annualized return on an investment in a Treasury bill. The
discount is the percentage that bills are selling below the face
value, which is paid at maturity.
   The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between
banks, traded at 99-16 percent, down from 911-16 late Thursday.
</TEXT>
