<FILEID>AP-NR-05-12-89 2202EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-ChristianBrothers     05-12 0392</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Christian Brothers,0405</SECOND>
<HEAD>Christian Brothers Winery Rumored Up For Sale; Company Denies It</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACK SCHREIBMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Christian Brothers winery is denying
industry rumors that the venerable church-owned Napa Valley
operations might be sold, following a flood of news inquiries.
   Ron Batori, spokesman for the 107-year-old winemaking
institution, said Friday that winery President Richard Maher has
been denying the rumors of a possible sale, but Batori conceded
``there are definitely things going on.''
   ``Our position is that we are going to address (that) issue
sooner rather than later,'' he said.
   Christian Brothers, which is owned by the Catholic church, is
Napa Valley's largest premium vineyard landowner, including some of
most fabled country in the nation's top wine-producing region.
   The rumors are that Christian Brothers might be sold to a
beverage conglomerate such as Heublein, which owns Beaulieu
Vineyard, or Hiram Walker, whose holdings include Clos du Bois.
   Industry sources were skeptical that the church would consider
selling the operation while it was one of its most dynamic periods
ever, engaging in multiple ventures, dramatically improving wines,
and selling products in the United States and 40 other countries.
   The winery, believed the largest church-owned operation of its
kind in the world, has been steadily buying land and is largest
owner or controller of premium vineyard land in Napa Valley with
about 1,250 acres.
   Recent estimates indicating that a top grape-producing Napa
Valley acre is worth $50,000 would make Christian Brothers'
vineyard land alone worth at least $60 million. The company also
has liquid and property assets over a large pasrt of the state.
   The Christian Brothers teaching order was founded in France in
the 17th century. The worldwide order supports schools and colleges
in some 80 countries.
   A few years ago, winery business was slumping from a number of
elements, including a a philosophy against vintage dating. When it
was reconized that this as well as market forces required change,
the brands started swinging up. The catalyst for change was the
loss of brandy market share to Gallo's E&amp;J brand.
   Christian Brothers boasts one of largest lineups of brands in
the U.S. wine industry, including generic burgundy, claret,
chablis, rhine and sauterne, and a full line of premium varietals
including ``Montage,'' a Napa Valley-French blend, plus dessert
wines and champagne.
   The company also makes sacramental wine.
</TEXT>
