<FILEID>AP-NR-05-12-89 1924EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-LTVPensions 1stLd-Writethru   05-12 0563</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-LTV Pensions, 1st Ld - Writethru,0577</SECOND>
<HEAD>Appeals Court: Government Can't Force Pension Plans on LTV</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 2 new grafs after 7th graf pvs, The PBGC...to UPDATE
with LTV comment.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government agency that insures millions of
workers' pensions can't force LTV Corp. to take back several plans
it dumped when it filed for bankruptcy law protection, a federal
appeals court said Friday.
   The 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals upheld a lower court
ruling that the federal Pension Benefit Guaranty Corp. was
``arbitrary and capricious'' in ordering LTV to take back more than
$2 billion in pension fund obligations.
   The appeals court, which sits in Manhattan, agreed with U.S.
District Judge Robert Sweet that the PBGC's grounds for restoring
the pension plans to LTV ``were not supported by the administrative
record'' and the agency's decision should be reversed.
   The appeals court sent the matter back to the PBGC for further
consideration.
   ``The PBGC is studying the opinion,'' said Judith Bekelman, a
spokeswoman for the agency in Washington, who said she could not
comment further until agency lawyers completed their study of the
ruling.
   The PBGC is responsible for insuring pension benefits much like
the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. insures bank deposits. The
agency had claimed that LTV taking unfair advantage of federal
funds to cut costs and gain labor peace while it goes through U.S.
Bankruptcy Code Chapter 11 reorganization.
   The PBGC also has claimed it doesn't have enough money to cover
all the other pension plans it has had to take over.
   ``LTV is very pleased with the unanimous decision of the appeals
court,'' said Charles Palmer, an LTV corporate spokesman.
   ``Until we can sort the thing out, I don't think we can say much
more,'' Palmer said, although he added, ``The pension litigation
has been a major obstacle in the forward movement in the Chapter 11
proceeding.''
   Dallas-based LTV, a giant steel, aerospace and energy concern,
filed for protection from its creditors in July 1986 and five
months later, stopped paying for three pension plans in its
Cleveland-based steel-making subsidiary, LTV Steel Co.
   The PBGC took control of the plans for some 100,000 current and
retired employees in January 1987, making the agency LTV's largest
creditor.
   When the PBGC eliminated benefits not covered by its guarantees,
several thousand LTV pensioners had their benefits cut by as much
as $400 a month.
   That prompted the United Steelworkers of America to sue in
bankruptcy court for restoration of the lost benefits and threaten
a crippling strike.
   LTV and the steelworkers union reached a new labor contract in
June 1987 that replaced most of the lost benefits but the PBGC
balked at subsidizing the plans for LTV and last September shifted
responsibility for the pension plans back to LTV.
   LTV sued in bankruptcy court, claiming the PBGC action violated
federal bankruptcy law, which bars legal action against companies
in reorganization.
   The PBGC had the case moved to the district court level before
Sweet, claiming it was concerned that if LTV was able to get out of
its pension plan obligations, that would encourage other companies
with underfunded pension plans to use the bankruptcy code to shed
their obligations.
   But Sweet ruled last September that ``PBGC's conclusion (to
restore the plans to LTV) was reached in an arbitrary and
capricious manner.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
